quoteText: Let me see the child, and die.
subQuotationList: ['Let me see the child, and die.']
speaker: Agnes Fleming

quoteText: Oh, you must not talk about dying yet.
subQuotationList: ['Oh, you must not talk about dying yet.']
speaker: The Surgeon
referringExpression: he rose and advancing to the beds head said

quoteText: Lor bless her dear heart, no!
subQuotationList: ['Lor bless her dear heart, no!']
speaker: Mrs. Thingummy

quoteText:
Lor bless her dear heart, when she has lived as long as I have, sir,
and had thirteen children of her own, and all on 'em dead except two,
and them in the wurkus with me, she'll know better than to take on in
that way, bless her dear heart! Think what it is to be a mother,
there's a dear young lamb do.
subQuotationList:
["Lor bless her dear heart, when she has lived as long as I have, sir,
and had thirteen children of her own, and all on 'em dead except two,
and them in the wurkus with me, she'll know better than to take on in
that way, bless her dear heart! Think what it is to be a mother,
there's a dear young lamb do."]

quoteText: It's all over, Mrs. Thingummy!
subQuotationList: ["It's all over, Mrs. Thingummy!"]
speaker: The Surgeon

quoteText: Ah, poor dear, so it is! Poor dear!
subQuotationList: ['Ah, poor dear, so it is!', 'Poor dear!']
speaker: Mrs. Thingummy

quoteText:
You needn't mind sending up to me, if the child cries, nurse, It's very
likely it _will_ be troublesome. Give it a little gruel if it is.
subQuotationList: ["You needn't mind sending up to me, if the child cries, nurse,", "It's very\nlikely it _will_ be troublesome. Give it a little gruel if it is."]
speaker: The Surgeon

quoteText: She was a good-looking girl, too; where did she come from?
subQuotationList: ['She was a good-looking girl, too; where did she come from?']
speaker: The Surgeon
referringExpression: He put on his hat and pausing by the bedside on his way to the door added

quoteText:
She was brought here last night, by the
overseer's order. She was found lying in the street. She had walked
some distance, for her shoes were worn to pieces; but where she came
from, or where she was going to, nobody knows.
subQuotationList:
['She was brought here last night,', "by the
overseer's order. She was found lying in the street. She had walked
some distance, for her shoes were worn to pieces; but where she came
from, or where she was going to, nobody knows."]
speaker: Mrs. Thingummy
mentionEntitiesList: [[['Agnes Fleming']], [['Agnes Fleming'], ['Agnes Fleming'], ['Agnes Fleming'], ['Agnes Fleming'], ['Agnes Fleming']]]

quoteText:
The old
story, no wedding-ring, I see. Ah!
Good-night!
subQuotationList: ['The old\nstory,', 'no wedding-ring, I see. Ah!\nGood-night!']
speaker: The Surgeon

quoteText:
Goodness gracious! Is that you, Mr. Bumble, sir? (Susan, take Oliver and them two brats upstairs, and wash 'em
directly.) My heart alive! Mr. Bumble, how glad I am to see you,
sure-ly! Lor, only think, only think of that! That I should have
forgotten that the gate was bolted on the inside, on account of them
dear children! Walk in sir; walk in, pray, Mr. Bumble, do, sir.
subQuotationList:
['Goodness gracious! Is that you, Mr. Bumble, sir?', "(Susan, take Oliver and them two brats upstairs, and wash 'em
directly.) My heart alive! Mr. Bumble, how glad I am to see you,
sure-ly!", 'Lor, only think,', 'only think of that! That I should have
forgotten that the gate was bolted on the inside, on account of them
dear children! Walk in sir; walk in, pray, Mr. Bumble, do, sir.']
speaker: Mrs. Mann
mentionEntitiesList: [[['Mr. Bumble'], ['Mr. Bumble'], ['Mr. Bumble']], [['Oliver Twist'], ['Mr. Bumble'], ['Mr. Bumble']], [], [['Oliver Twist'], ['Mr. Bumble'], ['Mr. Bumble'], ['Mr. Bumble']]]

quoteText:
Do you think this respectful or proper conduct, Mrs. Mann, to keep the parish officers a waiting
at your garden-gate, when they come here upon porochial business with
the porochial orphans? Are you aweer, Mrs. Mann, that you are, as I may
say, a porochial delegate, and a stipendiary?
subQuotationList:
['Do you think this respectful or proper conduct, Mrs. Mann,', 'to keep the parish officers a waiting
at your garden-gate, when they come here upon porochial business with
the porochial orphans? Are you aweer, Mrs. Mann, that you are, as I may
say, a porochial delegate, and a stipendiary?']
speaker: Mr. Bumble
mentionEntitiesList: [[['Mrs. Mann'], ['Mrs. Mann']], [['Mrs. Mann'], ['Mrs. Mann'], ['Mrs. Mann'], ['Mrs. Mann']]]

quoteText:
I'm sure Mr. Bumble, that I was only a telling one or two of the dear
children as is so fond of you, that it was you a coming,
subQuotationList: ["I'm sure Mr. Bumble, that I was only a telling one or two of the dear\nchildren as is so fond of you, that it was you a coming,"]
speaker: Mrs. Mann

quoteText:
Well, well, Mrs. Mann, it may be as you
say; it may be. Lead the way in, Mrs. Mann, for I come on business, and
have something to say.
subQuotationList: ['Well, well, Mrs. Mann,', 'it may be as you\nsay; it may be. Lead the way in, Mrs. Mann, for I come on business, and\nhave something to say.']
speaker: Mr. Bumble

quoteText:
Now don't you be offended at what I'm a going to say, You've had a long walk, you know, or
I wouldn't mention it. Now, will you take a little drop of somethink,
Mr. Bumble?
subQuotationList: ["Now don't you be offended at what I'm a going to say,", "You've had a long walk, you know, or\nI wouldn't mention it. Now, will you take a little drop of somethink,\nMr. Bumble?"]
speaker: Mrs. Mann

quoteText: Not a drop. Nor a drop,
subQuotationList: ['Not a drop. Nor a drop,']
speaker: Mr. Bumble

quoteText:
I think you will, Just a leetle drop,
with a little cold water, and a lump of sugar. Now, just a leetle drop,
subQuotationList: ['I think you will,', 'Just a leetle drop,\nwith a little cold water, and a lump of sugar.', 'Now, just a leetle drop,']
speaker: Mrs. Mann

quoteText: What is it?
subQuotationList: ['What is it?']
speaker: Mr. Bumble

quoteText:
Why, it's what I'm obliged to keep a little of in the house, to put
into the blessed infants' Daffy, when they ain't well, Mr. Bumble, It's gin. I'll not deceive you, Mr. B. It's gin.
subQuotationList: ["Why, it's what I'm obliged to keep a little of in the house, to put\ninto the blessed infants' Daffy, when they ain't well, Mr. Bumble,", "It's gin. I'll not deceive you, Mr. B. It's gin."]
speaker: Mrs. Mann

quoteText: Do you give the children Daffy, Mrs. Mann?
subQuotationList: ['Do you give the children Daffy, Mrs. Mann?']
speaker: Mr. Bumble

quoteText:
Ah, bless 'em, that I do, dear as it is, I
couldn't see 'em suffer before my very eyes, you know sir.
subQuotationList: ["Ah, bless 'em, that I do, dear as it is,", "I\ncouldn't see 'em suffer before my very eyes, you know sir."]
speaker: Mrs. Mann

quoteText:
No no, you could not. You are a humane
woman, Mrs. Mann. I shall take a early
opportunity of mentioning it to the board, Mrs. Mann. You feel as a mother, Mrs. Mann. I I drink your health with cheerfulness, Mrs. Mann
subQuotationList: ['No', 'no, you could not. You are a humane\nwoman, Mrs. Mann.', 'I shall take a early\nopportunity of mentioning it to the board, Mrs. Mann.', 'You feel as a mother, Mrs. Mann.', 'I I drink your health with cheerfulness, Mrs. Mann']
speaker: Mr. Bumble

quoteText:
And now about business, The child that was half-baptized Oliver Twist, is nine
year old to-day.
subQuotationList: ['And now about business,', 'The child that was half-baptized Oliver Twist, is nine\nyear old to-day.']
speaker: Mr. Bumble

quoteText: Bless him!
subQuotationList: ['Bless him!']
speaker: Mrs. Mann

quoteText:
And notwithstanding a offered reward of ten pound, which was
afterwards increased to twenty pound. Notwithstanding the most
superlative, and, I may say, supernat'ral exertions on the part of this
parish, we have never been able to discover who is his
father, or what was his mother's settlement, name, or condition.
subQuotationList:
["And notwithstanding a offered reward of ten pound, which was
afterwards increased to twenty pound. Notwithstanding the most
superlative, and, I may say, supernat'ral exertions on the part of this
parish,", "we have never been able to discover who is his
father, or what was his mother's settlement, name, or condition."]
speaker: Mr. Bumble

quoteText: How comes he to have any name at all, then?
subQuotationList: ['How comes he to have any name at all, then?']
speaker: Mrs. Mann
referringExpression: Mrs Mann raised her hands in astonishment but added

quoteText: I inwented it.
subQuotationList: ['I inwented it.']
speaker: Mr. Bumble
referringExpression: The beadle drew himself up with great pride and said

quoteText: You, Mr. Bumble!
subQuotationList: ['You, Mr. Bumble!']
speaker: Mrs. Mann

quoteText:
I, Mrs. Mann. We name our fondlings in alphabetical order. The last
was a S, Swubble, I named him. This was a T, Twist, I named _him_. The
next one comes will be Unwin, and the next Vilkins. I have got names
ready made to the end of the alphabet, and all the way through it
again, when we come to Z.
subQuotationList:
['I, Mrs. Mann. We name our fondlings in alphabetical order. The last
was a S, Swubble, I named him. This was a T, Twist, I named _him_. The
next one comes will be Unwin, and the next Vilkins. I have got names
ready made to the end of the alphabet, and all the way through it

quoteText: Why, you're quite a literary character, sir!
subQuotationList: ["Why, you're quite a literary character, sir!"]
speaker: Mrs. Mann

quoteText: Well, well, perhaps I may be. Perhaps I may be, Mrs. Mann.
subQuotationList: ['Well, well,', 'perhaps I may be. Perhaps I may be, Mrs. Mann.']
speaker: Mr. Bumble

quoteText:
Oliver being now too old to remain here, the
board have determined to have him back into the house. I have come out
myself to take him there. So let me see him at once.
subQuotationList: ['Oliver being now too old to remain here, the\nboard have determined to have him back into the house. I have come out\nmyself to take him there. So let me see him at once.']
speaker: Mr. Bumble
referringExpression: He finished the ginandwater and added
mentionEntitiesList: [[['Oliver Twist'], ['Mr. Limbkins', 'The Gentleman In The White Waistcoat'], ['Oliver Twist'], ['Oliver Twist'], ['Oliver Twist']]]

quoteText: I'll fetch him directly,
subQuotationList: ["I'll fetch him directly,"]
speaker: Mrs. Mann

quoteText: Make a bow to the gentleman, Oliver,
subQuotationList: ['Make a bow to the gentleman, Oliver,']
speaker: Mrs. Mann

quoteText: Will you go along with me, Oliver?
subQuotationList: ['Will you go along with me, Oliver?']
speaker: Mr. Bumble

quoteText: Will she go with me?
subQuotationList: ['Will she go with me?']
speaker: Oliver Twist

No, she can't, But she'll come and see you
sometimes.
subQuotationList: ["No, she can't,", "But she'll come and see you\nsometimes."]

subQuotationList: ['Bow to the board,']

addressees: ['Mr. Limbkins', 'The Gentleman In The White Waistcoat', 'Oliver Twist']

quoteText:
What's your name, boy? Boy, listen to me. You know
you're an orphan, I suppose?
subQuotationList: ["What's your name, boy?", 'Boy,', "listen to me. You know\nyou're an orphan, I suppose?"]
speaker: Mr. Limbkins
addressees: ['The Gentleman In The White Waistcoat', 'Oliver Twist', 'Mr. Bumble']

quoteText: What's that, sir?
subQuotationList: ["What's that, sir?"]

addressees: ['Mr. Limbkins', 'The Gentleman In The White Waistcoat', 'Mr. Bumble']

quoteText: The boy _is_ a fool I thought he was,
subQuotationList: ['The boy _is_ a fool I thought he was,']
speaker: The Gentleman In The White Waistcoat
referringExpression: said the gentleman in the white waistcoat

quoteText:
Hush! You know you've got
no father or mother, and that you were brought up by the parish, don't
you?
subQuotationList: ['Hush!', "You know you've got\nno father or mother, and that you were brought up by the parish, don't\nyou?"]

addressees: ['The Gentleman In The White Waistcoat', 'Oliver Twist', 'Mr. Bumble']
referringExpression: said the gentleman who had spoken first

quoteText: Yes, sir,
subQuotationList: ['Yes, sir,']
speaker: Oliver Twist
addressees: ['Mr. Limbkins', 'The Gentleman In The White Waistcoat', 'Mr. Bumble']

quoteText: What are you crying for?
subQuotationList: ['What are you crying for?']
speaker: The Gentleman In The White Waistcoat
referringExpression: inquired the gentleman in the white waistcoat

quoteText:
I hope you say your prayers every night, and pray for the people who feed you, and take care of
you like a Christian.
subQuotationList: ['I hope you say your prayers every night,', 'and pray for the people who feed you, and take care of\nyou like a Christian.']
speaker: _unknowable
addressees: ['Mr. Limbkins', 'The Gentleman In The White Waistcoat', 'Oliver Twist', 'Mr. Bumble']

quoteText: Yes, sir,
subQuotationList: ['Yes, sir,']
speaker: Oliver Twist
addressees: ['Mr. Limbkins', 'The Gentleman In The White Waistcoat', 'Mr. Bumble']

subQuotationList: ['Well! You have come here to be educated, and taught a useful trade,']
speaker: Mr. Limbkins
addressees: ['The Gentleman In The White Waistcoat', 'Oliver Twist', 'Mr. Bumble']
referringExpression: said the redfaced gentleman in the high chair

quoteText: So you'll begin to pick oakum to-morrow morning at six o'clock,
subQuotationList: ["So you'll begin to pick oakum to-morrow morning at six o'clock,"]
speaker: The Gentleman In The White Waistcoat
referringExpression: added the surly one in the white waistcoat

quoteText:
Oho! we are the fellows to set this to rights;
we'll stop it all, in no time.
subQuotationList: ['Oho!', "we are the fellows to set this to rights;\nwe'll stop it all, in no time."]
speaker: _group
addressees: ['Mr. Limbkins', 'The Gentleman In The White Waistcoat']
mentionEntitiesList: [[], [['Mr. Limbkins', 'The Gentleman In The White Waistcoat'], ['Mr. Limbkins', 'The Gentleman In The White Waistcoat']]]

quoteText: Please, sir, I want some more.
subQuotationList: ['Please, sir,', 'I want some more.']
speaker: Oliver Twist

quoteText:
Mr. Limbkins, I beg your pardon, sir! Oliver Twist has asked for
more!
subQuotationList: ['Mr. Limbkins, I beg your pardon, sir! Oliver Twist has asked for\nmore!']
speaker: Mr. Bumble
addressees: ['Mr. Limbkins', 'The Gentleman In The White Waistcoat']
referringExpression: Mr Bumble rushed into the room in great excitement and addressing the gentleman in the high chair said

quoteText:
For _more_! Compose yourself, Bumble, and answer
me distinctly. Do I understand that he asked for more, after he had
eaten the supper allotted by the dietary?
subQuotationList: ['For _more_!', 'Compose yourself, Bumble, and answer\nme distinctly. Do I understand that he asked for more, after he had\neaten the supper allotted by the dietary?']
speaker: Mr. Limbkins
addressees: ['Mr. Bumble', 'The Gentleman In The White Waistcoat']

quoteText: He did, sir,
subQuotationList: ['He did, sir,']

addressees: ['Mr. Limbkins', 'The Gentleman In The White Waistcoat']

quoteText:
That boy will be hung, I
know that boy will be hung.
subQuotationList: ['That boy will be hung,', 'I\nknow that boy will be hung.']
speaker: The Gentleman In The White Waistcoat
referringExpression: said the gentleman in the white waistcoat

quoteText:
I never was more convinced of anything in my life, I never was more convinced of anything in my life, than
I am that that boy will come to be hung.
subQuotationList: ['I never was more convinced of anything in my life,', 'I never was more convinced of anything in my life, than\nI am that that boy will come to be hung.']
speaker: The Gentleman In The White Waistcoat
referringExpression: said the gentleman in the white waistcoat

quoteText: Wo o!
speaker: Mr. Gamfield
referringExpression: said Mr Gamfield to the donkey

quoteText: This here boy, sir, wot the parish wants to 'prentis,
subQuotationList: ["This here boy, sir, wot the parish wants to 'prentis,"]

quoteText: Ay, my man, What of him?
subQuotationList: ['Ay, my man,', 'What of him?']
speaker: The Gentleman In The White Waistcoat
referringExpression: said the gentleman in the white waistcoat

quoteText:
If the parish vould like him to learn a right pleasant trade, in a
good 'spectable chimbley-sweepin' bisness, I wants
a 'prentis, and I am ready to take him.
subQuotationList: ["If the parish vould like him to learn a right pleasant trade, in a\ngood 'spectable chimbley-sweepin' bisness,", "I wants\na 'prentis, and I am ready to take him."]

quoteText: Walk in,
subQuotationList: ['Walk in,']
speaker: The Gentleman In The White Waistcoat
referringExpression: said the gentleman in the white waistcoat

quoteText: It's a nasty trade,
subQuotationList: ["It's a nasty trade,"]
speaker: Mr. Limbkins
addressees: ['Mr. Gamfield', 'The Gentleman In The White Waistcoat']

quoteText: Young boys have been smothered in chimneys before now,
subQuotationList: ['Young boys have been smothered in chimneys before now,']
speaker: _unknowable
addressees: ['Mr. Limbkins', 'Mr. Gamfield', 'The Gentleman In The White Waistcoat']

quoteText:
That's acause they damped the straw afore they lit it in the chimbley
to make 'em come down again, that's all smoke, and no
blaze; vereas smoke ain't o' no use at all in making a boy come down,
for it only sinds him to sleep, and that's wot he likes. Boys is wery
obstinit, and wery lazy, Gen'l'men, and there's nothink like a good hot
blaze to make 'em come down vith a run. It's humane too, gen'l'men,
acause, even if they've stuck in the chimbley, roasting their feet
makes 'em struggle to hextricate theirselves.
subQuotationList:
["That's acause they damped the straw afore they lit it in the chimbley
to make 'em come down again,", "that's all smoke, and no
blaze; vereas smoke ain't o' no use at all in making a boy come down,
for it only sinds him to sleep, and that's wot he likes. Boys is wery

blaze to make 'em come down vith a run. It's humane too, gen'l'men,
acause, even if they've stuck in the chimbley, roasting their feet
makes 'em struggle to hextricate theirselves."]

addressees: ['Mr. Limbkins', 'The Gentleman In The White Waistcoat']

speaker: Mr. Limbkins
addressees: ['Mr. Gamfield', 'The Gentleman In The White Waistcoat']
mentionEntitiesList: [[['Mr. Limbkins', 'The Gentleman In The White Waistcoat'], ['Mr. Gamfield'], ['Mr. Limbkins', 'The Gentleman In The White Waistcoat']]]

quoteText: Not at all,
subQuotationList: ['Not at all,']

referringExpression: said the gentleman in the white waistcoat

quoteText: Decidedly not,
subQuotationList: ['Decidedly not,']

addressees: ['Mr. Limbkins', 'Mr. Gamfield', 'The Gentleman In The White Waistcoat']

addressees: ['Mr. Limbkins', 'The Gentleman In The White Waistcoat']

No, at least, as it's a nasty business, we
think you ought to take something less than the premium we offered.

speaker: Mr. Limbkins
addressees: ['Mr. Gamfield', 'The Gentleman In The White Waistcoat']

What'll you give, gen'l'men? Come! Don't be too hard on a poor man.
What'll you give?
subQuotationList: ["What'll you give, gen'l'men? Come! Don't be too hard on a poor man.\nWhat'll you give?"]

addressees: ['Mr. Limbkins', 'The Gentleman In The White Waistcoat']
referringExpression: he returned to the table and said

speaker: Mr. Limbkins
addressees: ['Mr. Gamfield', 'The Gentleman In The White Waistcoat']

Come! say four pound, gen'l'men. Say four pound, and

Come! I'll split the diff'erence, gen'l'men, Three
pound fifteen.

addressees: ['Mr. Limbkins', 'The Gentleman In The White Waistcoat']

Pooh! pooh! nonsense! He'd be cheap with nothing at all, as a premium. Take him, you silly
fellow! He's just the boy for you. He wants the stick, now and then:
it'll do him good; and his board needn't come very expensive, for he
hasn't been overfed since he was born. Ha! ha! ha!

be made a 'prentice of, Oliver.

quoteText:

Well, well, Mr. Bumble, there's no denying that, since the new system of
feeding has come in, the coffins are something narrower and more
shallow than they used to be; but we must have some profit, Mr. Bumble.
Well-seasoned timber is an expensive article, sir; and all the iron
handles come, by canal, from Birmingham.

have been better off, and have paid rates for many years, are the first
to sink when they come into the house; and let me tell you, Mr. Bumble,
that three or four inches over one's calculation makes a great hole in
one's profits: especially when one has a family to provide for, sir.
subQuotationList:

and our drink. I see no saving in parish children, not I; for they

say the boy isn't too dainty to eat 'em are you, boy?

hear?

the matter of that. Neither his father nor his mother will ever
interfere with him. All his relations let him have his own way pretty

quoteText:
Promptness, indeed! But what's the consequence;
what's the ungrateful behaviour of these rebels, sir? Why, the husband
sends back word that the medicine won't suit his wife's complaint, and
so she shan't take it says she shan't take it, sir! Good, strong,
wholesome medicine, as was given with great success to two Irish
labourers and a coal-heaver, only a week before sent 'em for nothing,
with a blackin'-bottle in, and he sends back word that she shan't take
it, sir!

you've a life to lose!
subQuotationList: ['Nobody shall go near her,', "Keep back! Damn you, keep back, if\nyou've a life to lose!"]

quoteText: Nonsense, my good man, Nonsense!
subQuotationList: ['Nonsense, my good man,', 'Nonsense!']
speaker: Mr. Sowerberry

quoteText:
I tell you, I tell you I won't have her put into the ground. She
couldn't rest there. The worms would worry her not eat her she is so
worn away. Ah! kneel down, kneel down kneel round her,
every one of you, and mark my words! I say she was starved to death. I
never knew how bad she was, till the fever came upon her; and then her
bones were starting through the skin. There was neither fire nor
candle; she died in the dark in the dark! She couldn't even see her
children's faces, though we heard her gasping out their names. I begged
for her in the streets: and they sent me to prison. When I came back,
she was dying; and all the blood in my heart has dried up, for they
starved her to death. I swear it before the God that saw it! They
starved her!
subQuotationList:
['I tell you,', "I tell you I won't have her put into the ground. She

quoteText:
She was my daughter, Lord, Lord!
Well, it _is_ strange that I who gave birth to her, and was a woman
then, should be alive and merry now, and she lying there: so cold and
stiff! Lord, Lord! to think of it; it's as good as a play as good as a
play! Stop, stop! Will she be buried
to-morrow, or next day, or to-night? I laid her out; and I must walk,
you know. Send me a large cloak: a good warm one: for it is bitter
cold. We should have cake and wine, too, before we go! Never mind; send
some bread only a loaf of bread and a cup of water. Shall we have some
bread, dear?

["Meat, ma'am, meat,", "You've
over-fed him, ma'am. You've raised a artificial soul and spirit in him,
ma'am unbecoming a person of his condition: as the board, Mrs.
Sowerberry, who are practical philosophers, will tell you. What have
paupers to do with soul or spirit? It's quite enough that we let 'em
have live bodies. If you had kept the boy on gruel, ma'am, this would
never have happened."]

quoteText:
Ah! the only thing that can be done now, that I know of, is to
leave him in the cellar for a day or so, till he's a little starved
down; and then to take him out, and keep him on gruel all through the
apprenticeship. He comes of a bad family. Excitable natures, Mrs.
Sowerberry! Both the nurse and doctor said, that that mother of his
made her way here, against difficulties and pain that would have killed
any well-disposed woman, weeks before.

trade! Five of 'em strung up in a row, and none left to play booty, or
turn white-livered!

obtained possession of that book, under very suspicious and
disreputable circumstances; and you may think yourself very fortunate
that the owner of the property declines to prosecute. Let this be a
lesson to you, my man, or the law will overtake you yet. The boy is
discharged. Clear the office!

quoteText:
Why, what the blazes is in the wind now! Who
pitched that 'ere at me? It's well it's the beer, and not the pot, as
hit me, or I'd have settled somebody. I might have know'd, as nobody
but an infernal, rich, plundering, thundering old Jew could afford to
throw away any drink but water and not that, unless he done the River
Company every quarter. Wot's it all about, Fagin? D me, if my
neck-handkercher an't lined with beer! Come in, you sneaking warmint;
wot are you stopping outside for, as if you was ashamed of your master!
Come in!

quoteText:
Why didn't you come in afore? You're getting too proud

your 'prentice, I'd have done it long ago, and no, I couldn't have sold
you afterwards, for you're fit for nothing but keeping as a curiousity
of ugliness in a glass bottle, and I suppose they don't blow glass
bottles large enough.

know,

Well, well! you get well as fast
as ever you can, dear, and it shall be hung up again. There! I promise
you that! Now, let us talk about something else.

Bless us, and save us! Wash your hands, and let me part your hair
nicely for you, child, Dear heart alive! If we had
known he would have asked for you, we would have put you a clean collar
on, and made you as smart as sixpence!
subQuotationList:
['Bless us, and save us! Wash your hands, and let me part your hair
nicely for you, child,', 'Dear heart alive! If we had

subQuotationList: ['There are a good many books, are there not, my boy?']
speaker: Mr. Brownlow

quoteText: A great number, sir, I never saw so many.
subQuotationList: ['A great number, sir,', 'I never saw so many.']
speaker: Oliver Twist

quoteText:
You shall read them, if you behave well, and you will like that, better than looking at the
outsides, that is, some cases; because there are books of which the
backs and covers are by far the best parts.
subQuotationList: ['You shall read them, if you behave well,', 'and you will like that, better than looking at the\noutsides, that is, some cases; because there are books of which the\nbacks and covers are by far the best parts.']

of a much smaller size. How should you like to grow up a clever man,
and write books, eh?

speaker: Mr. Brownlow

subQuotationList: ['I think I would rather read them, sir,']
speaker: Oliver Twist

quoteText:
What! wouldn't you like to be a book-writer? Well, well, Don't be
afraid! We won't make an author of you, while there's an honest trade
to be learnt, or brick-making to turn to.
subQuotationList: ["What! wouldn't you like to be a book-writer?", 'Well, well,', "Don't be\nafraid! We won't make an author of you, while there's an honest trade\nto be learnt, or brick-making to turn to."]

quoteText: Thank you, sir,
subQuotationList: ['Thank you, sir,']

quoteText:
Now, I want you to pay great attention, my boy, to what I am
going to say. I shall talk to you without any reserve; because I am
sure you are well able to understand me, as many older persons would
be.
subQuotationList:
['Now,', 'I want you to pay great attention, my boy, to what I am
going to say. I shall talk to you without any reserve; because I am
sure you are well able to understand me, as many older persons would
be.']

quoteText:
Oh, don't tell you are going to send me away, sir, pray! Don't turn me out of doors to wander in the streets
again. Let me stay here, and be a servant. Don't send me back to the
wretched place I came from. Have mercy upon a poor boy, sir!
subQuotationList: ["Oh, don't tell you are going to send me away, sir, pray!", "Don't turn me out of doors to wander in the streets\nagain. Let me stay here, and be a servant. Don't send me back to the\nwretched place I came from. Have mercy upon a poor boy, sir!"]

quoteText:
My dear child, you need not be afraid of my deserting you,
unless you give me cause.
subQuotationList: ['My dear child,', 'you need not be afraid of my deserting you,\nunless you give me cause.']
speaker: Mr. Brownlow

quoteText: I never, never will, sir,
subQuotationList: ['I never, never will, sir,']
speaker: Oliver Twist

quoteText:
I hope not, I do not think you ever
will. I have been deceived, before, in the objects whom I have
endeavoured to benefit; but I feel strongly disposed to trust you,
nevertheless; and I am more interested in your behalf than I can well
account for, even to myself. The persons on whom I have bestowed my
dearest love, lie deep in their graves; but, although the happiness and
delight of my life lie buried there too, I have not made a coffin of my
heart, and sealed it up, forever, on my best affections. Deep
affliction has but strengthened and refined them.

quoteText:
Well, well! I only say this, because you have a young heart; and knowing
that I have suffered great pain and sorrow, you will be more careful,
perhaps, not to wound me again. You say you are an orphan, without a
friend in the world; all the inquiries I have been able to make,
confirm the statement. Let me hear your story; where you come from; who
brought you up; and how you got into the company in which I found you.
Speak the truth, and you shall not be friendless while I live.

saw her look towards his infernal red lamp with the pantomime-light.
 Don't go to him,' I called out of the window,  he's an assassin! A

murdering his master. He had had a fever six times; he wasn't
recommended to mercy on that account. Pooh! nonsense!

as them!
subQuotationList: ['Poor fellow!', 'Oh, Bill, such fine young chaps\nas them!']
speaker: Nance

quoteText:
Yes; that's all you women think of, Fine young
chaps! Well, they're as good as dead, so it don't much matter.
subQuotationList: ["Yes; that's all you women think of,", "Fine young\nchaps! Well, they're as good as dead, so it don't much matter."]
speaker: Bill Sikes

quoteText:
Wait a minute! I wouldn't hurry by, if it was you
that was coming out to be hung, the next time eight o'clock struck,
Bill. I'd walk round and round the place till I dropped, if the snow
was on the ground, and I hadn't a shawl to cover me.
subQuotationList:
['Wait a minute!', "I wouldn't hurry by, if it was you
that was coming out to be hung, the next time eight o'clock struck,
Bill. I'd walk round and round the place till I dropped, if the snow
was on the ground, and I hadn't a shawl to cover me."]
speaker: Nance

quoteText:
And what good would that do? Unless you could pitch over a file and twenty yards of good stout
rope, you might as well be walking fifty mile off, or not walking at
all, for all the good it would do me. Come on, and don't stand
preaching there.
subQuotationList:
['And what good would that do?', "Unless you could pitch over a file and twenty yards of good stout
rope, you might as well be walking fifty mile off, or not walking at
all, for all the good it would do me. Come on, and don't stand
preaching there."]
speaker: Bill Sikes

quoteText: All right,
subQuotationList: ['All right,']
speaker: Bill Sikes

quoteText: Anybody here?
subQuotationList: ['Anybody here?']
speaker: Bill Sikes

quoteText: No,
speaker: The Artful Dodger

quoteText: Is the old 'un here?
subQuotationList: ["Is the old 'un here?"]
speaker: Bill Sikes

quoteText:
Yes, and precious down in the mouth he has been.
Won't he be glad to see you? Oh, no!
subQuotationList: ['Yes,', "and precious down in the mouth he has been.\nWon't he be glad to see you? Oh, no!"]
speaker: The Artful Dodger

quoteText:
Let's have a glim, or we shall go breaking our necks, or
treading on the dog. Look after your legs if you do!
subQuotationList: ["Let's have a glim,", 'or we shall go breaking our necks, or\ntreading on the dog. Look after your legs if you do!']
speaker: Bill Sikes
mentionEntitiesList: [[['Bill Sikes', 'Charley Bates', 'Nance', 'Oliver Twist']], [['Bill Sikes', 'Nance', 'Oliver Twist'], ['The Artful Dodger']]]

subQuotationList: ["Stand still a moment, and I'll get you one,"]
speaker: The Artful Dodger

quoteText:
Oh, my wig, my wig! here he is! oh, cry, here he is! Oh, Fagin,
look at him! Fagin, do look at him! I can't bear it; it is such a jolly
game, I can't bear it. Hold me, somebody, while I laugh it out.
subQuotationList: ['Oh, my wig, my wig!', "here he is! oh, cry, here he is! Oh, Fagin,\nlook at him! Fagin, do look at him! I can't bear it; it is such a jolly\ngame, I can't bear it. Hold me, somebody, while I laugh it out."]

quoteText:
Look at his togs, Fagin! Look at his togs!
Superfine cloth, and the heavy swell cut! Oh, my eye, what a game! And
his books, too! Nothing but a gentleman, Fagin!
subQuotationList: ['Look at his togs, Fagin!', 'Look at his togs!\nSuperfine cloth, and the heavy swell cut! Oh, my eye, what a game! And\nhis books, too! Nothing but a gentleman, Fagin!']
speaker: Charley Bates

quoteText:
Delighted to see you looking so well, my dear, The Artful shall give you another suit, my dear,
for fear you should spoil that Sunday one. Why didn't you write, my
dear, and say you were coming? We'd have got something warm for
supper.
subQuotationList:
['Delighted to see you looking so well, my dear,', "The Artful shall give you another suit, my dear,

subQuotationList: ["Hallo, what's that?", "That's mine, Fagin."]
speaker: Bill Sikes

quoteText:
No, no, my dear, Mine, Bill, mine. You shall have the
books.
subQuotationList: ['No, no, my dear,', 'Mine, Bill, mine. You shall have the\nbooks.']
speaker: Fagin

quoteText:
If that ain't mine! mine and Nancy's that is; I'll take the boy back
again.
subQuotationList: ["If that ain't mine!", "mine and Nancy's that is; I'll take the boy back\nagain."]
speaker: Bill Sikes

quoteText: Come! Hand over, will you?
subQuotationList: ['Come! Hand over, will you?']
speaker: Bill Sikes

quoteText: This is hardly fair, Bill; hardly fair, is it, Nancy?
subQuotationList: ['This is hardly fair, Bill; hardly fair, is it, Nancy?']
speaker: Fagin

quoteText:
Fair, or not fair, hand over, I tell you! Do you
think Nancy and me has got nothing else to do with our precious time
but to spend it in scouting arter, and kidnapping, every young boy as
gets grabbed through you? Give it here, you avaricious old skeleton,
give it here!
subQuotationList:
['Fair, or not fair,', 'hand over, I tell you! Do you
think Nancy and me has got nothing else to do with our precious time
but to spend it in scouting arter, and kidnapping, every young boy as
gets grabbed through you? Give it here, you avaricious old skeleton,
give it here!']
speaker: Bill Sikes

quoteText:
That's for our share of the trouble, and not half
enough, neither. You may keep the books, if you're fond of reading. If
you ain't, sell 'em.
subQuotationList: ["That's for our share of the trouble,", "and not half\nenough, neither. You may keep the books, if you're fond of reading. If\nyou ain't, sell 'em."]
speaker: Bill Sikes

quoteText:
They're very pretty, beautiful
writing, isn't is, Oliver?
subQuotationList: ["They're very pretty,", "beautiful\nwriting, isn't is, Oliver?"]
speaker: Charley Bates

quoteText:
They belong to the old gentleman, to the good, kind, old gentleman who took me into his house, and had
me nursed, when I was near dying of the fever. Oh, pray send them back;
send him back the books and money. Keep me here all my life long; but
pray, pray send them back. He'll think I stole them; the old lady: all
of them who were so kind to me: will think I stole them. Oh, do have
mercy upon me, and send them back!
subQuotationList:
['They belong to the old gentleman,', "to the good, kind, old gentleman who took me into his house, and had
me nursed, when I was near dying of the fever. Oh, pray send them back;
send him back the books and money. Keep me here all my life long; but
pray, pray send them back. He'll think I stole them; the old lady: all
of them who were so kind to me: will think I stole them. Oh, do have
mercy upon me, and send them back!"]
speaker: Oliver Twist

quoteText: The boy's right,
subQuotationList: ["The boy's right,"]
speaker: Fagin

quoteText:
You're right, Oliver, you're
right; they _will_ think you have stolen 'em. Ha! ha! it couldn't have happened better, if we had
chosen our time!
subQuotationList: ["You're right, Oliver, you're\nright; they _will_ think you have stolen 'em. Ha! ha!", "it couldn't have happened better, if we had\nchosen our time!"]
speaker: Fagin

quoteText:
Of course it couldn't, I know'd that, directly I see
him coming through Clerkenwell, with the books under his arm. It's all
right enough. They're soft-hearted psalm-singers, or they wouldn't have
taken him in at all; and they'll ask no questions after him, fear they
should be obliged to prosecute, and so get him lagged. He's safe
enough.
subQuotationList:
["Of course it couldn't,", "I know'd that, directly I see
him coming through Clerkenwell, with the books under his arm. It's all

quoteText:
Keep back the dog, Bill! Keep
back the dog; he'll tear the boy to pieces.
subQuotationList: ['Keep back the dog, Bill!', "Keep\nback the dog; he'll tear the boy to pieces."]
speaker: Nance

quoteText:
Serve him right! Stand off from me, or I'll split your head against
the wall.
subQuotationList: ['Serve him right!', "Stand off from me, or I'll split your head against\nthe wall."]
speaker: Bill Sikes

quoteText:
I don't care for that, Bill, I don't care for that, the child shan't be torn down
by the dog, unless you kill me first.
subQuotationList: ["I don't care for that, Bill, I don't care for that,", "the child shan't be torn down\nby the dog, unless you kill me first."]
speaker: Nance

quoteText:
Shan't he! I'll soon do that, if you
don't keep off.
subQuotationList: ["Shan't he!", "I'll soon do that, if you\ndon't keep off."]
speaker: Bill Sikes

quoteText: What's the matter here!
subQuotationList: ["What's the matter here!"]
speaker: Fagin

quoteText: The girl's gone mad, I think,
subQuotationList: ["The girl's gone mad, I think,"]
speaker: Bill Sikes

quoteText: No, she hasn't, no, she hasn't, Fagin; don't think it.
subQuotationList: ["No, she hasn't,", "no, she hasn't, Fagin; don't think it."]
speaker: Nance

quoteText: Then keep quiet, will you?
subQuotationList: ['Then keep quiet, will you?']
speaker: Fagin

quoteText: No, I won't do that, neither, Come! What do you think of that?
subQuotationList: ["No, I won't do that, neither,", 'Come! What do you think of that?']
speaker: Nance

quoteText: So you wanted to get away, my dear, did you? eh?
subQuotationList: ['So you wanted to get away, my dear, did you?', 'eh?']
speaker: Fagin

quoteText:
Wanted to get assistance; called for the police; did you? We'll cure you of that, my young
master.
subQuotationList: ['Wanted to get assistance; called for the police; did you?', "We'll cure you of that, my young\nmaster."]
speaker: Fagin
mentionEntitiesList: [[['Oliver Twist']], [['Charley Bates', 'Bill Sikes', 'Nance', 'Fagin', 'The Artful Dodger'], ['Oliver Twist'], ['Oliver Twist']]]

quoteText:
I won't stand by and see it done, Fagin, You've got
the boy, and what more would you have? Let him be let him be or I shall
put that mark on some of you, that will bring me to the gallows before
my time.
subQuotationList:
["I won't stand by and see it done, Fagin,", "You've got
the boy, and what more would you have? Let him be let him be or I shall
put that mark on some of you, that will bring me to the gallows before
my time."]
speaker: Nance

quoteText:
Why, Nancy! you, you're more clever than ever to-night. Ha! ha! my dear,
you are acting beautifully.
subQuotationList: ['Why, Nancy!', "you, you're more clever than ever to-night. Ha! ha! my dear,\nyou are acting beautifully."]
speaker: Fagin

quoteText:
Am I! Take care I don't overdo it. You will be the
worse for it, Fagin, if I do; and so I tell you in good time to keep
clear of me.
subQuotationList: ['Am I!', "Take care I don't overdo it. You will be the\nworse for it, Fagin, if I do; and so I tell you in good time to keep\nclear of me."]
speaker: Nance

quoteText:
What do you mean by this? what do you mean by it? Burn my body! Do you know
who you are, and what you are?
subQuotationList: ['What do you mean by this?', 'what do you mean by it? Burn my body! Do you know\nwho you are, and what you are?']
speaker: Bill Sikes

quoteText: Oh, yes, I know all about it,
subQuotationList: ['Oh, yes, I know all about it,']
speaker: Nance

quoteText:
Well, then, keep quiet, or I'll quiet you for a
good long time to come.
subQuotationList: ['Well, then, keep quiet,', "or I'll quiet you for a\ngood long time to come."]
speaker: Bill Sikes

quoteText:
You're a nice one, to take up the humane and gen teel side! A pretty
subject for the child, as you call him, to make a friend of!
subQuotationList: ["You're a nice one,", 'to take up the humane and gen teel side! A pretty\nsubject for the child, as you call him, to make a friend of!']
speaker: Bill Sikes

quoteText:
God Almighty help me, I am! and I wish
I had been struck dead in the street, or had changed places with them
we passed so near to-night, before I had lent a hand in bringing him
here. He's a thief, a liar, a devil, all that's bad, from this night
forth. Isn't that enough for the old wretch, without blows?
subQuotationList:
['God Almighty help me, I am!', "and I wish
I had been struck dead in the street, or had changed places with them
we passed so near to-night, before I had lent a hand in bringing him
here. He's a thief, a liar, a devil, all that's bad, from this night
forth. Isn't that enough for the old wretch, without blows?"]
speaker: Nance

quoteText: Come, come, Sikes, we must have civil words; civil words, Bill.
subQuotationList: ['Come, come, Sikes,', 'we must have civil words; civil words, Bill.']
speaker: Fagin

quoteText:
Civil words! Civil words, you villain! Yes, you deserve 'em from me. I thieved for
you when I was a child not half as old as this! I
have been in the same trade, and in the same service, for twelve years
since. Don't you know it? Speak out! Don't you know it?
subQuotationList:
['Civil words!', "Civil words, you villain! Yes, you deserve 'em from me. I thieved for
you when I was a child not half as old as this!", "I
have been in the same trade, and in the same service, for twelve years
since. Don't you know it? Speak out! Don't you know it?"]
speaker: Nance

quoteText:
Well, well, and,
if you have, it's your living!
subQuotationList: ['Well, well,', "and,\nif you have, it's your living!"]
speaker: Fagin

quoteText:
Aye, it is! It is my living; and the
cold, wet, dirty streets are my home; and you're the wretch that drove
me to them long ago, and that'll keep me there, day and night, day and
night, till I die!
subQuotationList:
['Aye, it is!', "It is my living; and the
cold, wet, dirty streets are my home; and you're the wretch that drove
me to them long ago, and that'll keep me there, day and night, day and
night, till I die!"]
speaker: Nance

quoteText: I shall do you a mischief! a mischief worse than that, if you say much more!
subQuotationList: ['I shall do you a mischief!', 'a mischief worse than that, if you say much more!']
speaker: Fagin

quoteText:
She's all right now, She's
uncommon strong in the arms, when she's up in this way.
subQuotationList: ["She's all right now,", "She's\nuncommon strong in the arms, when she's up in this way."]
speaker: Bill Sikes

quoteText:
It's the worst of having to do with women, but they're clever, and we can't get on, in our line,
without 'em. Charley, show Oliver to bed.
subQuotationList: ["It's the worst of having to do with women,", "but they're clever, and we can't get on, in our line,\nwithout 'em. Charley, show Oliver to bed."]
speaker: Fagin
mentionEntitiesList: [[], [['The Artful Dodger', 'Bill Sikes', 'Charley Bates', 'Fagin'], ['Charley Bates'], ['Oliver Twist']]]

quoteText:
I suppose he'd better not wear his best clothes tomorrow, Fagin, had
he?
subQuotationList: ["I suppose he'd better not wear his best clothes tomorrow, Fagin, had\nhe?"]
speaker: Charley Bates

quoteText: Certainly not,
subQuotationList: ['Certainly not,']
speaker: Fagin

quoteText:
Put off the smart ones, and I'll give 'em to Fagin to
take care of. What fun it is!
subQuotationList: ['Put off the smart ones,', "and I'll give 'em to Fagin to\ntake care of. What fun it is!"]
speaker: Charley Bates

quoteText:
Drat that beadle! If it isn't him at this time in the morning! Lauk,
Mr. Bumble, only think of its being you! Well, dear me, it _is_ a
pleasure, this is! Come into the parlour, sir, please.
subQuotationList: ['Drat that beadle!', "If it isn't him at this time in the morning! Lauk,\nMr. Bumble, only think of its being you! Well, dear me, it _is_ a\npleasure, this is! Come into the parlour, sir, please."]
speaker: Mrs. Mann

quoteText:
Mrs. Mann, Mrs. Mann, ma'am, good
morning.
subQuotationList: ['Mrs. Mann,', "Mrs. Mann, ma'am, good\nmorning."]
speaker: Mr. Bumble

quoteText: Well, and good morning to _you_, sir, and hoping you find yourself well, sir!
subQuotationList: ['Well, and good morning to _you_, sir,', 'and hoping you find yourself well, sir!']
speaker: Mrs. Mann

quoteText:
So-so, Mrs. Mann, A porochial life is not a bed
of roses, Mrs. Mann.
subQuotationList: ['So-so, Mrs. Mann,', 'A porochial life is not a bed\nof roses, Mrs. Mann.']
speaker: Mr. Bumble

quoteText: Ah, that it isn't indeed, Mr. Bumble,
subQuotationList: ["Ah, that it isn't indeed, Mr. Bumble,"]
speaker: Mrs. Mann

quoteText:
A porochial life, ma'am, is a life of worrit, and vexation, and hardihood; but
all public characters, as I may say, must suffer prosecution.
subQuotationList: ["A porochial life, ma'am,", 'is a life of worrit, and vexation, and hardihood; but\nall public characters, as I may say, must suffer prosecution.']
speaker: Mr. Bumble

quoteText: Ah! You may well sigh, Mrs. Mann!
subQuotationList: ['Ah! You may well sigh, Mrs. Mann!']
speaker: Mr. Bumble

quoteText: Mrs. Mann, I am going to London.
subQuotationList: ['Mrs. Mann, I am going to London.']
speaker: Mr. Bumble
referringExpression: the public character who repressing a complacent smile by looking sternly at his cocked hat said

quoteText: Lauk, Mr. Bumble!
subQuotationList: ['Lauk, Mr. Bumble!']
speaker: Mrs. Mann

quoteText:
To London, ma'am, whether the Clerkinwell Sessions will not find themselves in the wrong
box before they have done with me.
subQuotationList: ["To London, ma'am,", 'whether the Clerkinwell Sessions will not find themselves in the wrong\nbox before they have done with me.']
speaker: Mr. Bumble

quoteText:
by coach. I and two
paupers, Mrs. Mann! A legal action is a coming on, about a settlement;
and the board has appointed me me, Mrs. Mann to dispose to the matter
before the quarter-sessions at Clerkinwell.

And I very much question,
subQuotationList:
['by coach. I and two
paupers, Mrs. Mann! A legal action is a coming on, about a settlement;
and the board has appointed me me, Mrs. Mann to dispose to the matter
before the quarter-sessions at Clerkinwell.

And I very much question,']
speaker: Mr. Bumble

quoteText: Oh! you mustn't be too hard upon them, sir,
subQuotationList: ["Oh! you mustn't be too hard upon them, sir,"]
speaker: Mrs. Mann

quoteText:
The Clerkinwell Sessions have brought it upon themselves, ma'am, and if the Clerkinwell Sessions find that they
come off rather worse than they expected, the Clerkinwell Sessions have
only themselves to thank.
subQuotationList: ["The Clerkinwell Sessions have brought it upon themselves, ma'am,", 'and if the Clerkinwell Sessions find that they\ncome off rather worse than they expected, the Clerkinwell Sessions have\nonly themselves to thank.']
speaker: Mr. Bumble

quoteText:
You're going by coach, sir? I thought it was always usual to send them
paupers in carts.
subQuotationList: ["You're going by coach, sir? I thought it was always usual to send them\npaupers in carts."]
speaker: Mrs. Mann

quoteText:
That's when they're ill, Mrs. Mann, We put the sick
paupers into open carts in the rainy weather, to prevent their taking
cold.
subQuotationList: ["That's when they're ill, Mrs. Mann,", 'We put the sick\npaupers into open carts in the rainy weather, to prevent their taking\ncold.']
speaker: Mr. Bumble

quoteText: Oh!
speaker: Mrs. Mann

quoteText:
The opposition coach contracts for these two; and takes them cheap, They are both in a very low state, and we find it
would come two pound cheaper to move 'em than to bury 'em that is, if
we can throw 'em upon another parish, which I think we shall be able to
do, if they don't die upon the road to spite us. Ha! ha! ha!
subQuotationList:
['The opposition coach contracts for these two; and takes them cheap,', "They are both in a very low state, and we find it
would come two pound cheaper to move 'em than to bury 'em that is, if
we can throw 'em upon another parish, which I think we shall be able to
do, if they don't die upon the road to spite us. Ha! ha! ha!"]
speaker: Mr. Bumble

We are forgetting business, ma'am, here is your
porochial stipend for the month.
subQuotationList: ["We are forgetting business, ma'am,", 'here is your\nporochial stipend for the month.']
speaker: Mr. Bumble

quoteText:
It's very much blotted, sir, but it's
formal enough, I dare say. Thank you, Mr. Bumble, sir, I am very much
obliged to you, I'm sure.
subQuotationList: ["It's very much blotted, sir,", "but it's\nformal enough, I dare say. Thank you, Mr. Bumble, sir, I am very much\nobliged to you, I'm sure."]
speaker: Mrs. Mann

quoteText:
Bless their dear little hearts! they're
as well as can be, the dears! Of course, except the two that died last
week. And little Dick.
subQuotationList: ['Bless their dear little hearts!', "they're\nas well as can be, the dears! Of course, except the two that died last\nweek. And little Dick."]
speaker: Mrs. Mann

quoteText: Isn't that boy no better?
subQuotationList: ["Isn't that boy no better?"]
speaker: Mr. Bumble

quoteText: He's a ill-conditioned, wicious, bad-disposed porochial child that, Where is he?
subQuotationList: ["He's a ill-conditioned, wicious, bad-disposed porochial child that,", 'Where is he?']
speaker: Mr. Bumble

quoteText: I'll bring him to you in one minute, sir,
subQuotationList: ["I'll bring him to you in one minute, sir,"]
speaker: Mrs. Mann

quoteText:
Here,
you Dick!
subQuotationList: ['Here,\nyou Dick!']
speaker: Mrs. Mann

quoteText: Can't you look at the gentleman, you obstinate boy?
subQuotationList: ["Can't you look at the gentleman, you obstinate boy?"]
speaker: Mrs. Mann

quoteText: What's the matter with you, porochial Dick?
subQuotationList: ["What's the matter with you, porochial Dick?"]
speaker: Mr. Bumble

quoteText: Nothing, sir,
subQuotationList: ['Nothing, sir,']
speaker: Dick

quoteText: I should think not,
subQuotationList: ['I should think not,']
speaker: Mrs. Mann

quoteText: You want for nothing, I'm sure.
subQuotationList: ["You want for nothing, I'm sure."]
speaker: Mr. Bumble

quoteText: I should like
subQuotationList: ['I should like']
speaker: Dick

quoteText:
Hey-day! I suppose you're going to say that
you _do_ want for something, now? Why, you little wretch
subQuotationList: ['Hey-day!', "I suppose you're going to say that\nyou _do_ want for something, now? Why, you little wretch"]
speaker: Mrs. Mann

quoteText: Stop, Mrs. Mann, stop! Like what, sir, eh?
subQuotationList: ['Stop, Mrs. Mann, stop!', 'Like what, sir, eh?']
speaker: Mr. Bumble

quoteText:
I should like, if somebody that can write, would
put a few words down for me on a piece of paper, and fold it up and
seal it, and keep it for me, after I am laid in the ground.
subQuotationList: ['I should like,', 'if somebody that can write, would\nput a few words down for me on a piece of paper, and fold it up and\nseal it, and keep it for me, after I am laid in the ground.']

quoteText: Why, what does the boy mean? What do you mean, sir?
subQuotationList: ['Why, what does the boy mean?', 'What do you mean, sir?']

quoteText:
I should like, to leave my dear love to poor Oliver
Twist; and to let him know how often I have sat by myself and cried to
think of his wandering about in the dark nights with nobody to help
him. And I should like to tell him, that I was glad to
die when I was very young; for, perhaps, if I had lived to be a man,
and had grown old, my little sister who is in Heaven, might forget me,
or be unlike me; and it would be so much happier if we were both
children there together.
subQuotationList:
['I should like,', 'to leave my dear love to poor Oliver
Twist; and to let him know how often I have sat by myself and cried to
think of his wandering about in the dark nights with nobody to help
him. And I should like to tell him,', 'that I was glad to
die when I was very young; for, perhaps, if I had lived to be a man,
and had grown old, my little sister who is in Heaven, might forget me,
or be unlike me; and it would be so much happier if we were both
children there together.']
speaker: Dick
mentionEntitiesList: [[], [['Oliver Twist'], ['Oliver Twist'], ['Oliver Twist'], ['Oliver Twist'], ['Oliver Twist']], [['Dick', 'Oliver Twist']]]

quoteText:
They're all in one story, Mrs. Mann. That out-dacious Oliver had
demogalized them all!
subQuotationList: ["They're all in one story, Mrs. Mann. That out-dacious Oliver had\ndemogalized them all!"]
speaker: Mr. Bumble
referringExpression: Mr Bumble surveyed the little speaker from head to foot with indescribable astonishment and turning to his companion said

quoteText:
I couldn't have believed it, sir I never see such a hardened little
wretch!
subQuotationList: ["I couldn't have believed it, sir", 'I never see such a hardened little\nwretch!']
speaker: Mrs. Mann

quoteText:
Take him away, ma'am! This must be
stated to the board, Mrs. Mann.
subQuotationList: ["Take him away, ma'am!", 'This must be\nstated to the board, Mrs. Mann.']
speaker: Mr. Bumble
mentionEntitiesList: [[['Dick'], ['Mrs. Mann']], [['Mr. Limbkins', 'The Gentleman In The White Waistcoat'], ['Mrs. Mann']]]

quoteText: I hope the gentleman will understand that it isn't my fault, sir?
subQuotationList: ["I hope the gentleman will understand that it isn't my fault, sir?"]
speaker: Mrs. Mann

quoteText:
They shall understand that, ma'am; they shall be acquainted with the
true state of the case, There; take him away, I
can't bear the sight on him.
subQuotationList: ["They shall understand that, ma'am; they shall be acquainted with the\ntrue state of the case,", "There; take him away, I\ncan't bear the sight on him."]
speaker: Mr. Bumble
mentionEntitiesList: [[['Mr. Limbkins', 'The Gentleman In The White Waistcoat'], ['Mrs. Mann'], ['Mr. Limbkins', 'The Gentleman In The White Waistcoat']], [['Dick'], ['Dick']]]

quoteText: Is Mr. Brownlow at home?
subQuotationList: ['Is Mr. Brownlow at home?']
speaker: Mr. Bumble
referringExpression: inquired Mr Bumble of the girl who opened the door

quoteText: I don't know; where do you come from?
subQuotationList: ["I don't know; where do you come from?"]
speaker: The Servant
referringExpression: the girl returned the not uncommon but rather evasive reply of

quoteText:
Come in, come in, I knew we should hear of him.
Poor dear! I knew we should! I was certain of it. Bless his heart! I
said so all along.
subQuotationList: ['Come in, come in,', 'I knew we should hear of him.\nPoor dear! I knew we should! I was certain of it. Bless his heart! I\nsaid so all along.']

subQuotationList: ["A beadle. A parish beadle, or I'll eat my head."]
speaker: Mr. Grimwig
referringExpression: The latter gentleman at once burst into the exclamation

quoteText:
Pray don't interrupt just now, Take a seat, will
you?
subQuotationList: ["Pray don't interrupt just now,", 'Take a seat, will\nyou?']
speaker: Mr. Brownlow

quoteText: Now, sir, you come in consequence of having seen the advertisement?
subQuotationList: ['Now, sir, you come in consequence of having seen the advertisement?']
speaker: Mr. Brownlow
referringExpression: Mr Brownlow moved the lamp so as to obtain an uninterrupted view of the beadles countenance and said

quoteText: Yes, sir,
subQuotationList: ['Yes, sir,']
speaker: Mr. Bumble

quoteText: And you ARE a beadle, are you not?
subQuotationList: ['And you ARE a beadle, are you not?']
speaker: Mr. Grimwig

quoteText: I am a porochial beadle, gentlemen,
subQuotationList: ['I am a porochial beadle, gentlemen,']
speaker: Mr. Bumble

quoteText:
Of course, I knew he was.
A beadle all over!
subQuotationList: ['Of course,', 'I knew he was.\nA beadle all over!']
speaker: Mr. Grimwig
referringExpression: observed Mr Grimwig aside to his friend

quoteText: Do you know where this poor boy is now?
subQuotationList: ['Do you know where this poor boy is now?']
speaker: Mr. Brownlow
referringExpression: Mr Brownlow gently shook his head to impose silence on his friend and resumed

quoteText: No more than nobody,
subQuotationList: ['No more than nobody,']
speaker: Mr. Bumble

quoteText:
Well, what _do_ you know of him? Speak
out, my friend, if you have anything to say. What _do_ you know of
him?
subQuotationList: ['Well, what _do_ you know of him?', 'Speak\nout, my friend, if you have anything to say. What _do_ you know of\nhim?']
speaker: Mr. Brownlow
mentionEntitiesList: [[['Mr. Bumble'], ['Oliver Twist']], [['Mr. Bumble'], ['Mr. Bumble'], ['Mr. Bumble'], ['Oliver Twist']]]

quoteText: You don't happen to know any good of him, do you? You see?
subQuotationList: ["You don't happen to know any good of him, do you?", 'You see?']
speaker: Mr. Grimwig

quoteText:
I fear it is all too true, This is not much for your intelligence; but I
would gladly have given you treble the money, if it had been favourable
to the boy.
subQuotationList: ['I fear it is all too true,', 'This is not much for your intelligence; but I\nwould gladly have given you treble the money, if it had been favourable\nto the boy.']
speaker: Mr. Brownlow

quoteText:
Mrs. Bedwin, that
boy, Oliver, is an imposter.
subQuotationList: ['Mrs. Bedwin,', 'that\nboy, Oliver, is an imposter.']
speaker: Mr. Brownlow

quoteText: It can't be, sir. It cannot be,
subQuotationList: ["It can't be, sir. It cannot be,"]
speaker: Mrs. Bedwin

quoteText:
I tell you he is, What do you mean by
can't be? We have just heard a full account of him from his birth; and
he has been a thorough-paced little villain, all his life.
subQuotationList: ['I tell you he is,', "What do you mean by\ncan't be? We have just heard a full account of him from his birth; and\nhe has been a thorough-paced little villain, all his life."]
speaker: Mr. Brownlow
mentionEntitiesList: [[['Mrs. Bedwin'], ['Oliver Twist']], [['Mrs. Bedwin'], ['Mr. Grimwig', 'Mr. Brownlow'], ['Oliver Twist'], ['Oliver Twist'], ['Oliver Twist'], ['Oliver Twist']]]

quoteText: I never will believe it, sir, Never!
subQuotationList: ['I never will believe it, sir,', 'Never!']
speaker: Mrs. Bedwin

quoteText:
You old women never believe anything but quack-doctors, and lying
story-books, I knew it all along. Why didn't you
take my advise in the beginning; you would if he hadn't had a fever, I
suppose, eh? He was interesting, wasn't he? Interesting! Bah!
subQuotationList:
['You old women never believe anything but quack-doctors, and lying
story-books,', "I knew it all along. Why didn't you
take my advise in the beginning; you would if he hadn't had a fever, I
suppose, eh? He was interesting, wasn't he? Interesting! Bah!"]
speaker: Mr. Grimwig

quoteText:
He was a dear, grateful, gentle child, sir, I know what children are, sir; and have done these forty
years; and people who can't say the same, shouldn't say anything about
them. That's my opinion!
subQuotationList: ['He was a dear, grateful, gentle child, sir,', "I know what children are, sir; and have done these forty\nyears; and people who can't say the same, shouldn't say anything about\nthem. That's my opinion!"]
speaker: Mrs. Bedwin

quoteText:
Silence! Never let me hear the boy's name again. I rang to tell you
that. Never. Never, on any pretence, mind! You may leave the room, Mrs.
Bedwin. Remember! I am in earnest.
subQuotationList: ['Silence!', "Never let me hear the boy's name again. I rang to tell you\nthat. Never. Never, on any pretence, mind! You may leave the room, Mrs.\nBedwin. Remember! I am in earnest."]
speaker: Mr. Brownlow

quoteText: What a pity it is he isn't a prig!
subQuotationList: ["What a pity it is he isn't a prig!"]
speaker: The Artful Dodger
referringExpression: He looked down on Oliver with a thoughtful countenance for a brief space and then raising his head and heaving a gentle sign said half in abstraction and half to Master Bates

quoteText: Ah! he don't know what's good for him.
subQuotationList: ['Ah!', "he don't know what's good for him."]
speaker: Charley Bates

quoteText: I suppose you don't even know what a prig is?
subQuotationList: ["I suppose you don't even know what a prig is?"]
speaker: The Artful Dodger

quoteText: I think I know that,
subQuotationList: ['I think I know that,']
speaker: Oliver Twist

quoteText:
It's a the ; you're
one, are you not?
subQuotationList: ["It's a the ; you're\none, are you not?"]
speaker: Oliver Twist

quoteText: I am, I'd scorn to be anything else.
subQuotationList: ['I am,', "I'd scorn to be anything else."]
speaker: The Artful Dodger

quoteText:
I am, So's Charley. So's Fagin. So's Sikes.
So's Nancy. So's Bet. So we all are, down to the dog. And he's the
downiest one of the lot!
subQuotationList: ['I am,', "So's Charley. So's Fagin. So's Sikes.\nSo's Nancy. So's Bet. So we all are, down to the dog. And he's the\ndowniest one of the lot!"]
speaker: The Artful Dodger
mentionEntitiesList: [[], [['Charley Bates'], ['Fagin'], ['Bill Sikes'], ['Nance'], ['Betsy'], ['Charley Bates', 'Bill Sikes', 'Nance', 'Fagin', 'The Artful Dodger']]]

quoteText: And the least given to peaching,
subQuotationList: ['And the least given to peaching,']
speaker: Charley Bates

quoteText:
He wouldn't so much as bark in a witness-box, for fear of committing
himself; no, not if you tied him up in one, and left him there without
wittles for a fortnight,
subQuotationList: ["He wouldn't so much as bark in a witness-box, for fear of committing\nhimself; no, not if you tied him up in one, and left him there without\nwittles for a fortnight,"]
speaker: The Artful Dodger

quoteText: Not a bit of it,
subQuotationList: ['Not a bit of it,']
speaker: Charley Bates

quoteText:
He's a rum dog. Don't he look fierce at any strange cove that laughs
or sings when he's in company! Won't he growl at
all, when he hears a fiddle playing! And don't he hate other dogs as
ain't of his breed! Oh, no!
subQuotationList:
["He's a rum dog. Don't he look fierce at any strange cove that laughs
or sings when he's in company!", "Won't he growl at
all, when he hears a fiddle playing! And don't he hate other dogs as
ain't of his breed! Oh, no!"]
speaker: The Artful Dodger

quoteText: He's an out-and-out Christian,
subQuotationList: ["He's an out-and-out Christian,"]
speaker: Charley Bates

quoteText:
Well, well, This hasn't go anything to do with young Green
here.
subQuotationList: ['Well, well,', "This hasn't go anything to do with young Green\nhere."]
speaker: The Artful Dodger

quoteText:
No more it has, Why don't you put yourself under
Fagin, Oliver?
subQuotationList: ['No more it has,', "Why don't you put yourself under\nFagin, Oliver?"]
speaker: Charley Bates

quoteText: And make your fortun' out of hand?
subQuotationList: ["And make your fortun' out of hand?"]
speaker: The Artful Dodger

quoteText:
And so be able to retire on your property, and do the gen-teel: as I
mean to, in the very next leap-year but four that ever comes, and the
forty-second Tuesday in Trinity-week,
subQuotationList: ['And so be able to retire on your property, and do the gen-teel: as I\nmean to, in the very next leap-year but four that ever comes, and the\nforty-second Tuesday in Trinity-week,']
speaker: Charley Bates

quoteText:
I don't like it, I wish they would let me
go. I I would rather go.
subQuotationList: ["I don't like it,", 'I wish they would let me\ngo. I I would rather go.']
speaker: Oliver Twist

quoteText: And Fagin would _rather_ not!
subQuotationList: ['And Fagin would _rather_ not!']
speaker: Charley Bates

quoteText:
Go! Why, where's your spirit? Don't you take
any pride out of yourself? Would you go and be dependent on your
friends?
subQuotationList: ['Go!', "Why, where's your spirit? Don't you take\nany pride out of yourself? Would you go and be dependent on your\nfriends?"]
speaker: The Artful Dodger

speaker: Charley Bates

quoteText: _I_ couldn't do it,
subQuotationList: ["_I_ couldn't do it,"]
speaker: The Artful Dodger

quoteText: You can leave your friends, though, and let them be punished for what you did.
subQuotationList: ['You can leave your friends, though,', 'and let them be punished for what you did.']

quoteText:
That, That was all out
of consideration for Fagin, 'cause the traps know that we work
together, and he might have got into trouble if we hadn't made our
lucky; that was the move, wasn't it, Charley?

of consideration for Fagin, 'cause the traps know that we work

Look here! Here's a jolly life! What's the odds where it comes from?
Here, catch hold; there's plenty more where they were took from. You
won't, won't you? Oh, you precious flat!

It's naughty, ain't it, Oliver? He'll come
to be scragged, won't he?

speaker: Charley Bates

quoteText: I don't know what that means,
subQuotationList: ["I don't know what that means,"]
speaker: Oliver Twist

quoteText: Something in this way, old feller,
subQuotationList: ['Something in this way, old feller,']
speaker: Charley Bates

That's what it means, Look how he stares, Jack!

I never did see such prime company as that 'ere boy; he'll be the death
of me, I know he will.
subQuotationList:

I never did see such prime company as that 'ere boy; he'll be the death
of me, I know he will."]

You've been brought up bad, Fagin will make
something of you, though, or you'll be the first he ever had that
turned out unprofitable. You'd better begin at once; for you'll come to
the trade long before you think of it; and you're only losing time,

tickers
subQuotationList:
["You've been brought up bad,", "Fagin will make
something of you, though, or you'll be the first he ever had that
turned out unprofitable. You'd better begin at once; for you'll come to
the trade long before you think of it; and you're only losing time,

What's the good of talking in that way? he
don't know what you mean.
subQuotationList: ["What's the good of talking in that way?", "he\ndon't know what you mean."]

quoteText:
If you don't take pocket-handkechers and watches, some
other cove will; so that the coves that lose 'em will be all the worse,
and you'll be all the worse, too, and nobody half a ha'p'orth the
better, except the chaps wot gets them and you've just as good a right
to them as they have.
subQuotationList:

To be sure, to be sure! It all lies in a nutshell my dear; in a nutshell, take the
Dodger's word for it. Ha! ha! ha! He understands the catechism of his
trade.
subQuotationList: ['To be sure, to be sure!', "It all lies in a nutshell my dear; in a nutshell, take the\nDodger's word for it. Ha! ha! ha! He understands the catechism of his\ntrade."]

quoteText: Where do you think the gentleman has come from, Oliver?
subQuotationList: ['Where do you think the gentleman has come from, Oliver?']
speaker: Fagin

quoteText: I I don't know, sir,
subQuotationList: ["I I don't know, sir,"]
speaker: Oliver Twist

quoteText: Who's that?
subQuotationList: ["Who's that?"]
speaker: Mr. Chitling

quoteText: A young friend of mine, my dear,
subQuotationList: ['A young friend of mine, my dear,']
speaker: Fagin

quoteText:
He's in luck, then, Never mind where I came from, young 'un; you'll find your way there,
soon enough, I'll bet a crown!
subQuotationList: ["He's in luck, then,", "Never mind where I came from, young 'un; you'll find your way there,\nsoon enough, I'll bet a crown!"]
speaker: Mr. Chitling

subQuotationList: ['Only me, Bill; only me, my dear,']
speaker: Fagin

quoteText:
Bring in your body then, Lie down, you stupid brute!
Don't you know the devil when he's got a great-coat on? Well!
subQuotationList: ['Bring in your body then,', "Lie down, you stupid brute!\nDon't you know the devil when he's got a great-coat on?", 'Well!']
speaker: Bill Sikes

quoteText: Well, my dear,
subQuotationList: ['Well, my dear,']
speaker: Fagin

quoteText: Ah! Nancy.
subQuotationList: ['Ah! Nancy.']
speaker: Fagin

quoteText: It is cold, Nancy dear,
subQuotationList: ['It is cold, Nancy dear,']
speaker: Fagin

quoteText: It seems to go right through one,
subQuotationList: ['It seems to go right through one,']
speaker: Fagin

quoteText:
It must be a piercer, if it finds its way through your heart, Give him something to drink, Nancy. Burn my body, make
haste! It's enough to turn a man ill, to see his lean old carcase
shivering in that way, like a ugly ghost just rose from the grave.
subQuotationList: ['It must be a piercer, if it finds its way through your heart,', "Give him something to drink, Nancy. Burn my body, make\nhaste! It's enough to turn a man ill, to see his lean old carcase\nshivering in that way, like a ugly ghost just rose from the grave."]
speaker: Bill Sikes

quoteText: Quite enough, quite, thankye, Bill,
subQuotationList: ['Quite enough, quite, thankye, Bill,']
speaker: Fagin

quoteText: What! You're afraid of our getting the better of you, are you? Ugh!
subQuotationList: ["What! You're afraid of our getting the better of you, are you?", 'Ugh!']
speaker: Bill Sikes

quoteText: There, Now I'm ready.
subQuotationList: ['There,', "Now I'm ready."]
speaker: Bill Sikes

quoteText: For business?
subQuotationList: ['For business?']
speaker: Fagin

quoteText: For business, so say what you've got to say.
subQuotationList: ['For business,', "so say what you've got to say."]
speaker: Bill Sikes

quoteText: About the crib at Chertsey, Bill?
subQuotationList: ['About the crib at Chertsey, Bill?']
speaker: Fagin

quoteText: Yes. Wot about it?
subQuotationList: ['Yes. Wot about it?']
speaker: Bill Sikes

quoteText:
Ah! you know what I mean, my dear, He knows what I
mean, Nancy; don't he?
subQuotationList: ['Ah! you know what I mean, my dear,', "He knows what I\nmean, Nancy; don't he?"]
speaker: Fagin

quoteText:
No, he don't, Or he won't, and that's the same
thing. Speak out, and call things by their right names; don't sit
there, winking and blinking, and talking to me in hints, as if you
warn't the very first that thought about the robbery. Wot d'ye mean?
subQuotationList:
["No, he don't,", "Or he won't, and that's the same
thing. Speak out, and call things by their right names; don't sit
there, winking and blinking, and talking to me in hints, as if you
warn't the very first that thought about the robbery. Wot d'ye mean?"]

Hush, Bill, hush! somebody will hear us, my dear. Somebody
will hear us.
subQuotationList: ['Hush, Bill, hush!', 'somebody will hear us, my dear. Somebody\nwill hear us.']
speaker: Fagin

quoteText: Let 'em hear! I don't care.
subQuotationList: ["Let 'em hear!", "I don't care."]
speaker: Bill Sikes

quoteText:
There, there, It was only my caution,
nothing more. Now, my dear, about that crib at Chertsey; when is it to
be done, Bill, eh? When is it to be done? Such plate, my dear, such
plate!
subQuotationList:
['There, there,', 'It was only my caution,
nothing more. Now, my dear, about that crib at Chertsey; when is it to
be done, Bill, eh? When is it to be done? Such plate, my dear, such
plate!']
speaker: Fagin

quoteText: Not at all,
subQuotationList: ['Not at all,']
speaker: Bill Sikes

quoteText: Not to be done at all!
subQuotationList: ['Not to be done at all!']
speaker: Fagin

No, not at all, At least it can't be a put-up job,
as we expected.
subQuotationList: ['No, not at all,', "At least it can't be a put-up job,\nas we expected."]

subQuotationList: ["Then it hasn't been properly gone about,", "Don't tell me!"]
speaker: Fagin

quoteText:
But I will tell you, Who are you that's not to be
told? I tell you that Toby Crackit has been hanging about the place for
a fortnight, and he can't get one of the servants in line.
subQuotationList: ['But I will tell you,', "Who are you that's not to be\ntold? I tell you that Toby Crackit has been hanging about the place for\na fortnight, and he can't get one of the servants in line."]

quoteText:
Do you mean to tell me, Bill, that neither of the two men in the house can be got
over?
subQuotationList: ['Do you mean to tell me, Bill,', 'that neither of the two men in the house can be got\nover?']

Yes, I do mean to tell you so, The old lady has had
'em these twenty years; and if you were to give 'em five hundred pound,
they wouldn't be in it.
subQuotationList: ['Yes, I do mean to tell you so,', "The old lady has had\n'em these twenty years; and if you were to give 'em five hundred pound,\nthey wouldn't be in it."]
speaker: Bill Sikes

But do you mean to say, my dear, that the
women can't be got over?

quoteText: Not a bit of it,
subQuotationList: ['Not a bit of it,']
speaker: Bill Sikes

quoteText:
Not by flash Toby Crackit? Think what
women are, Bill,
subQuotationList: ['Not by flash Toby Crackit?', 'Think what\nwomen are, Bill,']
speaker: Fagin

quoteText:
No; not even by flash Toby Crackit, He says he's worn
sham whiskers, and a canary waistcoat, the whole blessed time he's been
loitering down there, and it's all of no use.
subQuotationList: ['No; not even by flash Toby Crackit,', "He says he's worn\nsham whiskers, and a canary waistcoat, the whole blessed time he's been\nloitering down there, and it's all of no use."]
speaker: Bill Sikes

quoteText:
He should have tried mustachios and a pair of military trousers, my
dear,
subQuotationList: ['He should have tried mustachios and a pair of military trousers, my\ndear,']
speaker: Fagin

quoteText:
So he did, and they warn't of no more use than the
other plant.
subQuotationList: ['So he did,', "and they warn't of no more use than the\nother plant."]
speaker: Bill Sikes

quoteText:
And yet, it's a
sad thing, my dear, to lose so much when we had set our hearts upon
it.
subQuotationList: ['And yet,', "it's a\nsad thing, my dear, to lose so much when we had set our hearts upon\nit."]

young boy of Ned, the chimbley-sweeper's! He kept him small on purpose,
and let him out by the job. But the father gets lagged; and then the
Juvenile Delinquent Society comes, and takes the boy away from a trade
where he was earning money, teaches him to read and write, and in time
makes a 'prentice of him. And so they go on, so they go on; and, if
they'd got money enough (which it's a Providence they haven't,) we
shouldn't have half a dozen boys left in the whole trade, in a year or
two.

quoteText:
And wot, wot
makes you take so much pains about one chalk-faced kid, when you know
there are fifty boys snoozing about Common Garden every night, as you
might pick and choose from?

quoteText:
Because they're of no use to me, my dear, not worth the taking. Their looks convict 'em when they get
into trouble, and I lose 'em all. With this boy, properly managed, my
dears, I could do what I couldn't with twenty of them. Besides, he has us now if he could
only give us leg-bail again; and he must be in the same boat with us.
Never mind how he came there; it's quite enough for my power over him
that he was in a robbery; that's all I want. Now, how much better this
is, than being obliged to put the poor leetle boy out of the way which
would be dangerous, and we should lose by it besides.
subQuotationList:
["Because they're of no use to me, my dear,", "not worth the taking. Their looks convict 'em when they get
into trouble, and I lose 'em all. With this boy, properly managed, my
dears, I could do what I couldn't with twenty of them. Besides,", "he has us now if he could
only give us leg-bail again; and he must be in the same boat with us.

that he was in a robbery; that's all I want. Now, how much better this
is, than being obliged to put the poor leetle boy out of the way which
would be dangerous, and we should lose by it besides."]

I have saved you from being ill-used once, and I will again, and I do
now, for those who would have fetched you,
if I had not, would have been far more rough than me. I have promised

to yourself and me too, and perhaps be my death. See here! I have borne
all this for you already, as true as God sees me show it.

As near as I know, there isn't anybody as would be asking very

quoteText:
The short and the long of what you mean, is, that if you're crossed by him in
this job you have on hand, you'll prevent his ever telling tales
afterwards, by shooting him through the head, and will take your chance
of swinging for it, as you do for a great many other things in the way
of business, every month of your life.
