speaker: Bill Sikes

quoteText:
Now, young 'un! hard upon seven! you must step out. Come, don't lag behind
already, Lazy-legs!
subQuotationList: ["Now, young 'un!", "hard upon seven! you must step out. Come, don't lag behind\nalready, Lazy-legs!"]
speaker: Bill Sikes

quoteText: Jump up, Is that your boy?
subQuotationList: ['Jump up,', 'Is that your boy?']
speaker: The Driver

quoteText: Yes; he's my boy,
subQuotationList: ["Yes; he's my boy,"]
speaker: Bill Sikes

quoteText: Your father walks rather too quick for you, don't he, my man?
subQuotationList: ["Your father walks rather too quick for you, don't he, my man?"]
speaker: The Driver

quoteText:
Not a bit of it, He's used to it. Here,
take hold of my hand, Ned. In with you!
subQuotationList: ['Not a bit of it,', "He's used to it. Here,\ntake hold of my hand, Ned. In with you!"]
speaker: Bill Sikes

quoteText: Good-bye, boy,
subQuotationList: ['Good-bye, boy,']
speaker: The Driver

quoteText:
He's sulky, he's sulky. A young
dog! Don't mind him.
subQuotationList: ["He's sulky,", "he's sulky. A young\ndog! Don't mind him."]
speaker: Bill Sikes

quoteText:
Not I! It's a fine day,
after all.
subQuotationList: ['Not I!', "It's a fine day,\nafter all."]
speaker: The Driver

quoteText: So, you're going on to Lower Halliford, are you?
subQuotationList: ["So, you're going on to Lower Halliford, are you?"]
speaker: Bill Sikes

quoteText:
Yes, I am, and not slow about it neither. My
horse hasn't got a load behind him going back, as he had coming up in
the mornin'; and he won't be long a-doing of it. Here's luck to him.
Ecod! he's a good 'un!
subQuotationList:
['Yes, I am,', "and not slow about it neither. My
horse hasn't got a load behind him going back, as he had coming up in
the mornin'; and he won't be long a-doing of it. Here's luck to him.
Ecod! he's a good 'un!"]
speaker: The Labouring Man

quoteText: Could you give my boy and me a lift as far as there?
subQuotationList: ['Could you give my boy and me a lift as far as there?']
speaker: Bill Sikes

quoteText: If you're going directly, I can, Are you going to Halliford?
subQuotationList: ["If you're going directly, I can,", 'Are you going to Halliford?']
speaker: The Labouring Man

quoteText: Going on to Shepperton,
subQuotationList: ['Going on to Shepperton,']
speaker: Bill Sikes

quoteText: I'm your man, as far as I go,
subQuotationList: ["I'm your man, as far as I go,"]
speaker: The Labouring Man

quoteText:
Is all paid,
Becky?
subQuotationList: ['Is all paid,\nBecky?']
speaker: The Labouring Man

quoteText: Yes, the other gentleman's paid,
subQuotationList: ["Yes, the other gentleman's paid,"]
speaker: Becky

quoteText: I say! that won't do, you know.
subQuotationList: ['I say!', "that won't do, you know."]
speaker: The Labouring Man

quoteText:
Why not? You're a-going to accommodate us, and wot's
to prevent my standing treat for a pint or so, in return?
subQuotationList: ['Why not?', "You're a-going to accommodate us, and wot's\nto prevent my standing treat for a pint or so, in return?"]
speaker: Bill Sikes

quoteText:
The water! He has brought me
to this lonely place to murder me!
subQuotationList: ['The water!', 'He has brought me\nto this lonely place to murder me!']
speaker: Oliver Twist

quoteText: Hallo!
subQuotationList: ['Hallo!']
speaker: Toby Crackit

quoteText:
Don't make such a row, Show a glim,
Toby.
subQuotationList: ["Don't make such a row,", 'Show a glim,\nToby.']
speaker: Bill Sikes

quoteText: Aha! my pal!
subQuotationList: ['Aha! my pal!']
speaker: Toby Crackit

quoteText:
A glim, Barney, a glim! Show the
gentleman in, Barney; wake up first, if convenient.
subQuotationList: ['A glim, Barney, a glim! Show the\ngentleman in, Barney; wake up first, if convenient.']
speaker: Toby Crackit

quoteText:
Do you hear? There's Bill Sikes in the passage
with nobody to do the civil to him; and you sleeping there, as if you
took laudanum with your meals, and nothing stronger. Are you any
fresher now, or do you want the iron candlestick to wake you
thoroughly?
subQuotationList:
['Do you hear?', "There's Bill Sikes in the passage
with nobody to do the civil to him; and you sleeping there, as if you
took laudanum with your meals, and nothing stronger. Are you any
fresher now, or do you want the iron candlestick to wake you
thoroughly?"]
speaker: Toby Crackit

quoteText:
Bister Sikes! cub
id, sir; cub id.
subQuotationList: ['Bister Sikes!', 'cub\nid, sir; cub id.']
speaker: Barney

quoteText: Here! you get on first, Quicker! or I shall tread upon your heels.
subQuotationList: ['Here! you get on first,', 'Quicker! or I shall tread upon your heels.']
speaker: Bill Sikes

quoteText: Bill, my boy!
subQuotationList: ['Bill, my boy!']
speaker: Toby Crackit

quoteText:
I'm glad to see you. I was almost afraid you'd given it up: in which
case I should have made a personal wentur. Hallo!
subQuotationList: ["I'm glad to see you. I was almost afraid you'd given it up: in which\ncase I should have made a personal wentur. Hallo!"]
speaker: Toby Crackit

quoteText: The boy. Only the boy!
subQuotationList: ['The boy. Only the boy!']
speaker: Bill Sikes

quoteText: Wud of Bister Fagid's lads,
subQuotationList: ["Wud of Bister Fagid's lads,"]
speaker: Barney

quoteText:
Fagin's, eh! Wot an inwalable boy
that'll make, for the old ladies' pockets in chapels! His mug is a
fortin' to him.
subQuotationList: ["Fagin's, eh!", "Wot an inwalable boy\nthat'll make, for the old ladies' pockets in chapels! His mug is a\nfortin' to him."]
speaker: Toby Crackit

quoteText: There there's enough of that,
subQuotationList: ["There there's enough of that,"]
speaker: Bill Sikes

quoteText:
Now, if you'll give us something
to eat and drink while we're waiting, you'll put some heart in us; or
in me, at all events. Sit down by the fire, younker, and rest yourself;
for you'll have to go out with us again to-night, though not very far
off.
subQuotationList:
['Now,', "if you'll give us something
to eat and drink while we're waiting, you'll put some heart in us; or
in me, at all events. Sit down by the fire, younker, and rest yourself;
for you'll have to go out with us again to-night, though not very far
off."]
speaker: Bill Sikes
mentionEntitiesList: [[], [['Toby Crackit'], ['Bill Sikes', 'Oliver Twist'], ['Bill Sikes', 'Oliver Twist'], ['Toby Crackit'], ['Bill Sikes', 'Oliver Twist'], ['Oliver Twist'], ['Oliver Twist'], ['Oliver Twist'], ['Bill Sikes', 'Toby Crackit']]]

quoteText:
Here, Success to the crack! A drain for the boy, Down with
it, innocence.
subQuotationList: ['Here,', 'Success to the crack!', 'A drain for the boy,', 'Down with\nit, innocence.']
speaker: Toby Crackit

quoteText: Indeed, indeed, I
subQuotationList: ['Indeed,', 'indeed, I']
speaker: Oliver Twist

quoteText:
Down with it! Do you think I don't know what's good for
you? Tell him to drink it, Bill.
subQuotationList: ['Down with it!', "Do you think I don't know what's good for\nyou? Tell him to drink it, Bill."]
speaker: Toby Crackit

quoteText:
He had better! Burn my
body, if he isn't more trouble than a whole family of Dodgers. Drink
it, you perwerse imp; drink it!
subQuotationList: ['He had better!', "Burn my\nbody, if he isn't more trouble than a whole family of Dodgers. Drink\nit, you perwerse imp; drink it!"]
speaker: Bill Sikes

quoteText: Barkers for me, Barney,
subQuotationList: ['Barkers for me, Barney,']
speaker: Toby Crackit

quoteText:
Here they are, You
loaded them yourself.
subQuotationList: ['Here they are,', 'You\nloaded them yourself.']
speaker: Barney

quoteText: All right! The persuaders?
subQuotationList: ['All right!', 'The persuaders?']
speaker: Toby Crackit

quoteText: I've got 'em,
subQuotationList: ["I've got 'em,"]
speaker: Bill Sikes

quoteText: Crape, keys, centre-bits, darkies nothing forgotten?
subQuotationList: ['Crape, keys, centre-bits, darkies nothing forgotten?']
speaker: Toby Crackit

quoteText:
All right, Bring them bits of timber,
Barney. That's the time of day.
subQuotationList: ['All right,', "Bring them bits of timber,\nBarney. That's the time of day."]
speaker: Bill Sikes

quoteText: Now then! Take his other hand, Toby, Look out, Barney.
subQuotationList: ['Now then!', 'Take his other hand, Toby,', 'Look out, Barney.']
speaker: Bill Sikes

quoteText:
Slap through the town, there'll be nobody in the
way, to-night, to see us.
subQuotationList: ['Slap through the town,', "there'll be nobody in the\nway, to-night, to see us."]
speaker: Bill Sikes

quoteText: The boy next, Hoist him up; I'll catch hold of him.
subQuotationList: ['The boy next,', "Hoist him up; I'll catch hold of him."]
speaker: Toby Crackit

quoteText: Get up! Get up, or I'll strew your brains upon the grass.
subQuotationList: ['Get up!', "Get up, or I'll strew your brains upon the grass."]
speaker: Bill Sikes

quoteText:
Oh! for God's sake let me go! let me run away and die
in the fields. I will never come near London; never, never! Oh! pray
have mercy on me, and do not make me steal. For the love of all the
bright Angels that rest in Heaven, have mercy upon me!
subQuotationList:
["Oh! for God's sake let me go!", 'let me run away and die
in the fields. I will never come near London; never, never! Oh! pray
have mercy on me, and do not make me steal. For the love of all the
bright Angels that rest in Heaven, have mercy upon me!']
speaker: Oliver Twist

quoteText:
Hush! it won't answer here. Say another word, and
I'll do your business myself with a crack on the head. That makes no
noise, and is quite as certain, and more genteel. Here, Bill, wrench
the shutter open. He's game enough now, I'll engage. I've seen older
hands of his age took the same way, for a minute or two, on a cold
night.
subQuotationList:
['Hush!', "it won't answer here. Say another word, and
I'll do your business myself with a crack on the head. That makes no
noise, and is quite as certain, and more genteel. Here, Bill, wrench
the shutter open. He's game enough now, I'll engage. I've seen older
hands of his age took the same way, for a minute or two, on a cold
night."]
speaker: Toby Crackit

quoteText:
Now listen, you young limb, I'm a
going to put you through there. Take this light; go softly up the steps
straight afore you, and along the little hall, to the street door;
unfasten it, and let us in.
subQuotationList:
['Now listen, you young limb,', "I'm a
going to put you through there. Take this light; go softly up the steps
straight afore you, and along the little hall, to the street door;
unfasten it, and let us in."]
speaker: Bill Sikes

quoteText:
There's a bolt at the top, you won't be able to reach, Stand upon one of the hall chairs. There are three there, Bill,
with a jolly large blue unicorn and gold pitchfork on 'em: which is the
old lady's arms.
subQuotationList: ["There's a bolt at the top, you won't be able to reach,", "Stand upon one of the hall chairs. There are three there, Bill,\nwith a jolly large blue unicorn and gold pitchfork on 'em: which is the\nold lady's arms."]
speaker: Toby Crackit

quoteText:
Keep quiet, can't you? The
room-door is open, is it?
subQuotationList: ["Keep quiet, can't you?", 'The\nroom-door is open, is it?']
speaker: Bill Sikes

quoteText:
Wide, The game of
that is, that they always leave it open with a catch, so that the dog,
who's got a bed in here, may walk up and down the passage when he feels
wakeful. Ha! ha! Barney 'ticed him away to-night. So neat!
subQuotationList:
['Wide,', "The game of
that is, that they always leave it open with a catch, so that the dog,
who's got a bed in here, may walk up and down the passage when he feels
wakeful. Ha! ha! Barney 'ticed him away to-night. So neat!"]
speaker: Toby Crackit

quoteText:
Take this lantern, You see the
stairs afore you?
subQuotationList: ['Take this lantern,', 'You see the\nstairs afore you?']
speaker: Bill Sikes

quoteText: Yes.
speaker: Oliver Twist
referringExpression: Oliver more dead than alive gasped out

quoteText:
It's done in a minute, Directly
I leave go of you, do your work. Hark!
subQuotationList: ["It's done in a minute,", 'Directly\nI leave go of you, do your work. Hark!']
speaker: Bill Sikes

quoteText: What's that?
subQuotationList: ["What's that?"]
speaker: Toby Crackit

quoteText: Nothing, Now!
subQuotationList: ['Nothing,', 'Now!']
speaker: Bill Sikes

quoteText: Come back! Back! back!
subQuotationList: ['Come back!', 'Back! back!']
speaker: Bill Sikes

quoteText:
Clasp your arm tighter, Give me a shawl here. They've hit him. Quick! How the boy
bleeds!
subQuotationList: ['Clasp your arm tighter,', "Give me a shawl here. They've hit him. Quick! How the boy\nbleeds!"]
speaker: Bill Sikes

quoteText:
Well! I'm sure we have all on us a great deal to
be grateful for! A great deal, if we did but know it. Ah!
subQuotationList: ['Well!', "I'm sure we have all on us a great deal to\nbe grateful for! A great deal, if we did but know it. Ah!"]
speaker: Mrs. Corney

quoteText:
Drat the pot! a little stupid thing, that only holds a couple of cups! What
use is it of, to anybody! Except, except
to a poor desolate creature like me. Oh dear! I shall never get another! I shall
never get another like him. Oh, come in with you! Some of the old
women dying, I suppose. They always die when I'm at meals. Don't stand
there, letting the cold air in, don't. What's amiss now, eh?
subQuotationList:
['Drat the pot!', 'a little stupid thing, that only holds a couple of cups! What
use is it of, to anybody! Except,', 'except
to a poor desolate creature like me. Oh dear!', 'I shall never get another!', 'I shall
never get another like him.', 'Oh, come in with you!', "Some of the old
women dying, I suppose. They always die when I'm at meals. Don't stand
there, letting the cold air in, don't. What's amiss now, eh?"]
speaker: Mrs. Corney

quoteText: Nothing, ma'am, nothing,
subQuotationList: ["Nothing, ma'am, nothing,"]
speaker: Mr. Bumble

quoteText:
Dear me! is that Mr.
Bumble?
subQuotationList: ['Dear me!', 'is that Mr.\nBumble?']
speaker: Mrs. Corney

quoteText: At your service, ma'am, Shall I shut the door, ma'am?
subQuotationList: ["At your service, ma'am,", "Shall I shut the door, ma'am?"]
speaker: Mr. Bumble

quoteText: Hard weather, Mr. Bumble,
subQuotationList: ['Hard weather, Mr. Bumble,']
speaker: Mrs. Corney

quoteText:
Hard, indeed, ma'am, Anti-porochial weather
this, ma'am. We have given away, Mrs. Corney, we have given away a
matter of twenty quartern loaves and a cheese and a half, this very
blessed afternoon; and yet them paupers are not contented.
subQuotationList:
["Hard, indeed, ma'am,", "Anti-porochial weather
this, ma'am. We have given away, Mrs. Corney, we have given away a
matter of twenty quartern loaves and a cheese and a half, this very
blessed afternoon; and yet them paupers are not contented."]
speaker: Mr. Bumble

quoteText: Of course not. When would they be, Mr. Bumble?
subQuotationList: ['Of course not. When would they be, Mr. Bumble?']
speaker: Mrs. Corney

quoteText:
When, indeed, ma'am! Why here's one man that,
in consideration of his wife and large family, has a quartern loaf and
a good pound of cheese, full weight. Is he grateful, ma'am? Is he
grateful? Not a copper farthing's worth of it! What does he do, ma'am,
but ask for a few coals; if it's only a pocket handkerchief full, he
says! Coals! What would he do with coals? Toast his cheese with 'em and
then come back for more. That's the way with these people, ma'am; give
'em a apron full of coals to-day, and they'll come back for another,
the day after to-morrow, as brazen as alabaster.
subQuotationList:
["When, indeed, ma'am!", "Why here's one man that,
in consideration of his wife and large family, has a quartern loaf and
a good pound of cheese, full weight. Is he grateful, ma'am? Is he
grateful? Not a copper farthing's worth of it! What does he do, ma'am,
but ask for a few coals; if it's only a pocket handkerchief full, he
says! Coals! What would he do with coals? Toast his cheese with 'em and
then come back for more. That's the way with these people, ma'am; give
'em a apron full of coals to-day, and they'll come back for another,
the day after to-morrow, as brazen as alabaster."]
speaker: Mr. Bumble

quoteText:
I never, see anything like the pitch it's got to.
The day afore yesterday, a man you have been a married woman, ma'am,
and I may mention it to you a man, with hardly a rag upon his back
(here Mrs. Corney looked at the floor), goes to our overseer's door
when he has got company coming to dinner; and says, he must be
relieved, Mrs. Corney. As he wouldn't go away, and shocked the company
very much, our overseer sent him out a pound of potatoes and half a
pint of oatmeal.  My heart!' says the ungrateful villain,  what's the
use of _this_ to me? You might as well give me a pair of iron
spectacles!'  Very good,' says our overseer, taking 'em away again,
 you won't get anything else here.'  Then I'll die in the streets!'
says the vagrant.  Oh no, you won't,' says our overseer.
subQuotationList:
['I never,', "see anything like the pitch it's got to.
The day afore yesterday, a man you have been a married woman, ma'am,
and I may mention it to you a man, with hardly a rag upon his back

when he has got company coming to dinner; and says, he must be

spectacles!'  Very good,' says our overseer, taking 'em away again,
 you won't get anything else here.'  Then I'll die in the streets!'
says the vagrant.  Oh no, you won't,' says our overseer."]
speaker: Mr. Bumble

quoteText: Ha! ha! That was very good! So like Mr. Grannett, wasn't it? Well, Mr. Bumble?
subQuotationList: ["Ha! ha! That was very good! So like Mr. Grannett, wasn't it?", 'Well, Mr. Bumble?']
speaker: Mrs. Corney

quoteText:
Well, ma'am, he went away; and he _did_ die in
the streets. There's a obstinate pauper for you!
subQuotationList: ["Well, ma'am,", "he went away; and he _did_ die in\nthe streets. There's a obstinate pauper for you!"]
speaker: Mr. Bumble

quoteText:
It beats anything I could have believed, But don't you think out-of-door relief a very bad thing,
any way, Mr. Bumble? You're a gentleman of experience, and ought to
know. Come.
subQuotationList: ['It beats anything I could have believed,', "But don't you think out-of-door relief a very bad thing,\nany way, Mr. Bumble? You're a gentleman of experience, and ought to\nknow. Come."]
speaker: Mrs. Corney

quoteText:
Mrs. Corney, out-of-door relief, properly managed:
properly managed, ma'am: is the porochial safeguard. The great
principle of out-of-door relief is, to give the paupers exactly what
they don't want; and then they get tired of coming.
subQuotationList:
['Mrs. Corney,', "out-of-door relief, properly managed:
properly managed, ma'am: is the porochial safeguard. The great
principle of out-of-door relief is, to give the paupers exactly what
they don't want; and then they get tired of coming."]
speaker: Mr. Bumble

quoteText: Dear me! Well, that is a good one, too!
subQuotationList: ['Dear me!', 'Well, that is a good one, too!']
speaker: Mrs. Corney

quoteText:
Yes. Betwixt you and me, ma'am, that's the
great principle; and that's the reason why, if you look at any cases
that get into them owdacious newspapers, you'll always observe that
sick families have been relieved with slices of cheese. That's the rule
now, Mrs. Corney, all over the country. But, however, these are official secrets, ma'am; not
to be spoken of; except, as I may say, among the porochial officers,
such as ourselves. This is the port wine, ma'am, that the board ordered
for the infirmary; real, fresh, genuine port wine; only out of the cask
this forenoon; clear as a bell, and no sediment!
subQuotationList:
["Yes. Betwixt you and me, ma'am,", "that's the
great principle; and that's the reason why, if you look at any cases
that get into them owdacious newspapers, you'll always observe that
sick families have been relieved with slices of cheese. That's the rule
now, Mrs. Corney, all over the country. But, however,", "these are official secrets, ma'am; not
to be spoken of; except, as I may say, among the porochial officers,
such as ourselves. This is the port wine, ma'am, that the board ordered
for the infirmary; real, fresh, genuine port wine; only out of the cask
this forenoon; clear as a bell, and no sediment!"]
speaker: Mr. Bumble
mentionEntitiesList: [[['Mrs. Corney'], ['Mrs. Corney']], [['Mrs. Corney'], ['Mrs. Corney'], ['Mrs. Corney']], [['Mrs. Corney'], ['Mrs. Corney']]]

quoteText: You'll have a very cold walk, Mr. Bumble,
subQuotationList: ["You'll have a very cold walk, Mr. Bumble,"]
speaker: Mrs. Corney

quoteText: It blows, ma'am, enough to cut one's ears off.
subQuotationList: ["It blows, ma'am,", "enough to cut one's ears off."]
speaker: Mr. Bumble

quoteText: Sweet? Mr. Bumble?
subQuotationList: ['Sweet? Mr. Bumble?']
speaker: Mrs. Corney

quoteText: Very sweet, indeed, ma'am,
subQuotationList: ["Very sweet, indeed, ma'am,"]
speaker: Mr. Bumble

quoteText:
You have a cat, ma'am, I see, and kittens
too, I declare!
subQuotationList: ["You have a cat, ma'am, I see,", 'and kittens\ntoo, I declare!']
speaker: Mr. Bumble

quoteText:
I am so fond of them, Mr. Bumble, you can't think, They're _so_ happy, _so_ frolicsome, and _so_ cheerful, that
they are quite companions for me.
subQuotationList: ["I am so fond of them, Mr. Bumble, you can't think,", "They're _so_ happy, _so_ frolicsome, and _so_ cheerful, that\nthey are quite companions for me."]
speaker: Mrs. Corney

quoteText:
Very nice animals, ma'am, so very
domestic.
subQuotationList: ["Very nice animals, ma'am,", 'so very\ndomestic.']
speaker: Mr. Bumble

quoteText:
Oh, yes! so fond of their home
too, that it's quite a pleasure, I'm sure.
subQuotationList: ['Oh, yes!', "so fond of their home\ntoo, that it's quite a pleasure, I'm sure."]
speaker: Mrs. Corney

quoteText:
Mrs. Corney, ma'am, I mean to say this, ma'am; that any cat, or kitten,
that could live with you, ma'am, and _not_ be fond of its home, must be
a ass, ma'am.
subQuotationList: ["Mrs. Corney, ma'am,", "I mean to say this, ma'am; that any cat, or kitten,\nthat could live with you, ma'am, and _not_ be fond of its home, must be\na ass, ma'am."]
speaker: Mr. Bumble
mentionEntitiesList: [[['Mrs. Corney'], ['Mrs. Corney']], [['Mrs. Corney'], ['Mrs. Corney'], ['Mrs. Corney'], ['Mrs. Corney']]]

quoteText: Oh, Mr. Bumble!
subQuotationList: ['Oh, Mr. Bumble!']
speaker: Mrs. Corney

quoteText: It's of no use disguising facts, ma'am, I would drown it myself, with pleasure.
subQuotationList: ["It's of no use disguising facts, ma'am,", 'I would drown it myself, with pleasure.']
speaker: Mr. Bumble

quoteText: Then you're a cruel man, and a very hard-hearted man besides.
subQuotationList: ["Then you're a cruel man,", 'and a very hard-hearted man besides.']
speaker: Mrs. Corney

quoteText:
Hard-hearted, ma'am? Hard? Hard-hearted, Mrs. Corney? are _you_ hard-hearted, Mrs.
Corney?
subQuotationList: ["Hard-hearted, ma'am?", 'Hard?', 'Hard-hearted, Mrs. Corney?', 'are _you_ hard-hearted, Mrs.\nCorney?']
speaker: Mr. Bumble

quoteText:
Dear me! what a very curious question from a
single man. What can you want to know for, Mr. Bumble?
subQuotationList: ['Dear me!', 'what a very curious question from a\nsingle man. What can you want to know for, Mr. Bumble?']
speaker: Mrs. Corney

quoteText:
Mr. Bumble! Mr. Bumble, I shall
scream!
subQuotationList: ['Mr. Bumble!', 'Mr. Bumble, I shall\nscream!']
speaker: Mrs. Corney

quoteText: If you please, mistress, Old Sally is a-going fast.
subQuotationList: ['If you please, mistress,', 'Old Sally is a-going fast.']
speaker: Martha
referringExpression: said a withered old female pauper

quoteText:
Well, what's that to me? I can't keep
her alive, can I?
subQuotationList: ["Well, what's that to me?", "I can't keep\nher alive, can I?"]
speaker: Mrs. Corney

quoteText:
No, no, mistress, nobody can; she's far
beyond the reach of help. I've seen a many people die; little babes and
great strong men; and I know when death's a-coming, well enough. But
she's troubled in her mind: and when the fits are not on her, and
that's not often, for she is dying very hard, she says she has got
something to tell, which you must hear. She'll never die quiet till you
come, mistress.
subQuotationList:
['No, no, mistress,', "nobody can; she's far
beyond the reach of help. I've seen a many people die; little babes and
great strong men; and I know when death's a-coming, well enough. But
she's troubled in her mind: and when the fits are not on her, and
that's not often, for she is dying very hard, she says she has got
something to tell, which you must hear. She'll never die quiet till you
come, mistress."]
speaker: Martha
mentionEntitiesList: [[['Mrs. Corney']], [['Mrs. Thingummy'], ['Mrs. Thingummy'], ['Mrs. Thingummy'], ['Mrs. Thingummy'], ['Mrs. Thingummy'], ['Mrs. Thingummy'], ['Mrs. Thingummy'], ['Mrs. Corney'], ['Mrs. Thingummy'], ['Mrs. Corney'], ['Mrs. Corney']]]

quoteText: Cold night, Mrs. Corney,
subQuotationList: ['Cold night, Mrs. Corney,']
speaker: The Parish Apothecary's Apprentice

quoteText: Very cold, indeed, sir,
subQuotationList: ['Very cold, indeed, sir,']
speaker: Mrs. Corney

quoteText: You should get better coals out of your contractors, these are not at all the sort of thing for a cold night.
subQuotationList: ['You should get better coals out of your contractors,', 'these are not at all the sort of thing for a cold night.']
speaker: The Parish Apothecary's Apprentice

quoteText:
They're the board's choosing, sir, The least
they could do, would be to keep us pretty warm: for our places are hard
enough.
subQuotationList: ["They're the board's choosing, sir,", 'The least\nthey could do, would be to keep us pretty warm: for our places are hard\nenough.']
speaker: Mrs. Corney

quoteText:
Oh! it's all U.P. there, Mrs.
Corney.
subQuotationList: ['Oh!', "it's all U.P. there, Mrs.\nCorney."]
speaker: The Parish Apothecary's Apprentice

quoteText: It is, is it, sir?
subQuotationList: ['It is, is it, sir?']
speaker: Mrs. Corney

quoteText:
If she lasts a couple of hours, I shall be surprised, It's a
break-up of the system altogether. Is she dozing, old lady?
subQuotationList: ['If she lasts a couple of hours, I shall be surprised,', "It's a\nbreak-up of the system altogether. Is she dozing, old lady?"]
speaker: The Parish Apothecary's Apprentice

quoteText: Then perhaps she'll go off in that way, if you don't make a row, Put the light on the floor. She won't see it there.
subQuotationList: ["Then perhaps she'll go off in that way, if you don't make a row,", "Put the light on the floor. She won't see it there."]
speaker: The Parish Apothecary's Apprentice

quoteText: Did she say any more, Anny dear, while I was gone?
subQuotationList: ['Did she say any more, Anny dear, while I was gone?']
speaker: Martha

quoteText:
Not a word, She plucked and tore at her arms for
a little time; but I held her hands, and she soon dropped off. She
hasn't much strength in her, so I easily kept her quiet. I ain't so
weak for an old woman, although I am on parish allowance; no, no!
subQuotationList:
['Not a word,', "She plucked and tore at her arms for
a little time; but I held her hands, and she soon dropped off. She
hasn't much strength in her, so I easily kept her quiet. I ain't so
weak for an old woman, although I am on parish allowance; no, no!"]
speaker: Anny
mentionEntitiesList: [[], [['Mrs. Thingummy'], ['Mrs. Thingummy'], ['Mrs. Thingummy'], ['Mrs. Thingummy'], ['Mrs. Thingummy'], ['Mrs. Thingummy'], ['Mrs. Thingummy']]]

quoteText: Did she drink the hot wine the doctor said she was to have?
subQuotationList: ['Did she drink the hot wine the doctor said she was to have?']
speaker: Martha

quoteText:
I tried to get it down, But her teeth were tight
set, and she clenched the mug so hard that it was as much as I could do
to get it back again. So I drank it; and it did me good!
subQuotationList: ['I tried to get it down,', 'But her teeth were tight\nset, and she clenched the mug so hard that it was as much as I could do\nto get it back again. So I drank it; and it did me good!']
speaker: Anny

quoteText:
I mind the time, when she would have done
the same, and made rare fun of it afterwards.
subQuotationList: ['I mind the time,', 'when she would have done\nthe same, and made rare fun of it afterwards.']
speaker: Martha

quoteText:
Ay, that she would, she had a merry heart. A
many, many, beautiful corpses she laid out, as nice and neat as
waxwork. My old eyes have seen them ay, and those old hands touched
them too; for I have helped her, scores of times.
subQuotationList:
['Ay, that she would,', 'she had a merry heart. A
many, many, beautiful corpses she laid out, as nice and neat as
waxwork. My old eyes have seen them ay, and those old hands touched
them too; for I have helped her, scores of times.']
speaker: Anny

quoteText:
Not long, mistress, We have none of us long to wait for Death. Patience, patience!
He'll be here soon enough for us all.
subQuotationList: ['Not long, mistress,', "We have none of us long to wait for Death. Patience, patience!\nHe'll be here soon enough for us all."]
speaker: Anny

quoteText:
Hold your tongue, you doting idiot! You,
Martha, tell me; has she been in this way before?
subQuotationList: ['Hold your tongue, you doting idiot!', 'You,\nMartha, tell me; has she been in this way before?']
speaker: Mrs. Corney

quoteText: Often,
subQuotationList: ['Often,']
speaker: Martha

quoteText:
But will never be again, that is, she'll never
wake again but once and mind, mistress, that won't be for long!
subQuotationList: ['But will never be again,', "that is, she'll never\nwake again but once and mind, mistress, that won't be for long!"]
speaker: Anny

quoteText:
Long or short, she won't find me here
when she does wake; take care, both of you, how you worry me again for
nothing. It's no part of my duty to see all the old women in the house
die, and I won't that's more. Mind that, you impudent old harridans. If
you make a fool of me again, I'll soon cure you, I warrant you!
subQuotationList:
['Long or short,', "she won't find me here
when she does wake; take care, both of you, how you worry me again for
nothing. It's no part of my duty to see all the old women in the house
die, and I won't that's more. Mind that, you impudent old harridans. If
you make a fool of me again, I'll soon cure you, I warrant you!"]
speaker: Mrs. Corney

quoteText: Who's that?
subQuotationList: ["Who's that?"]
speaker: Mrs. Thingummy

quoteText:
Hush, hush! Lie down, lie
down!
subQuotationList: ['Hush, hush!', 'Lie down, lie\ndown!']
speaker: _unknowable

quoteText:
I'll never lie down again alive! I
_will_ tell her! Come here! Nearer! Let me whisper in your ear. Turn them away, make haste! make haste!
subQuotationList: ["I'll never lie down again alive!", 'I\n_will_ tell her! Come here! Nearer! Let me whisper in your ear.', 'Turn them away,', 'make haste! make haste!']
speaker: Mrs. Thingummy

quoteText:
Now listen to me, In this very room in this
very bed I once nursed a pretty young creetur', that was brought into
the house with her feet cut and bruised with walking, and all soiled
with dust and blood. She gave birth to a boy, and died. Let me
think what was the year again!
subQuotationList:
['Now listen to me,', "In this very room in this
very bed I once nursed a pretty young creetur', that was brought into
the house with her feet cut and bruised with walking, and all soiled
with dust and blood. She gave birth to a boy, and died. Let me
think what was the year again!"]
speaker: Mrs. Thingummy

quoteText: Never mind the year, what about her?
subQuotationList: ['Never mind the year,', 'what about her?']
speaker: Mrs. Corney

quoteText: Ay, what about her? what about I know!
subQuotationList: ['Ay,', 'what about her? what about I know!']
speaker: Mrs. Thingummy

quoteText:
I robbed her, so
I did! She wasn't cold I tell you she wasn't cold, when I stole it!
subQuotationList: ["I robbed her, so\nI did! She wasn't cold I tell you she wasn't cold, when I stole it!"]
speaker: Mrs. Thingummy

quoteText: Stole what, for God's sake?
subQuotationList: ["Stole what, for God's sake?"]
speaker: Mrs. Corney

quoteText:
_It_! The
only thing she had. She wanted clothes to keep her warm, and food to
eat; but she had kept it safe, and had it in her bosom. It was gold, I
tell you! Rich gold, that might have saved her life!
subQuotationList:
['_It_!', 'The
only thing she had. She wanted clothes to keep her warm, and food to
eat; but she had kept it safe, and had it in her bosom. It was gold, I
tell you! Rich gold, that might have saved her life!']
speaker: Mrs. Thingummy
mentionEntitiesList: [[], [['Agnes Fleming'], ['Agnes Fleming'], ['Agnes Fleming'], ['Agnes Fleming'], ['Agnes Fleming'], ['Mrs. Corney'], ['Agnes Fleming']]]

quoteText: Gold! Go on, go on yes what of it? Who was the mother? When was it?
subQuotationList: ['Gold!', 'Go on, go on yes what of it? Who was the mother? When was it?']
speaker: Mrs. Corney

quoteText:
She charged me to keep it safe, and
trusted me as the only woman about her. I stole it in my heart when she
first showed it me hanging round her neck; and the child's death,
perhaps, is on me besides! They would have treated him better, if they
had known it all!
subQuotationList:
['She charged me to keep it safe,', "and
trusted me as the only woman about her. I stole it in my heart when she
first showed it me hanging round her neck; and the child's death,
perhaps, is on me besides! They would have treated him better, if they
had known it all!"]
speaker: Mrs. Thingummy
mentionEntitiesList: [[['Agnes Fleming']], [['Agnes Fleming'], ['Agnes Fleming'], ['Agnes Fleming'], ['Oliver Twist'], ['Oliver Twist']]]

quoteText: Known what? Speak!
subQuotationList: ['Known what?', 'Speak!']
speaker: Mrs. Corney

quoteText:
The boy grew so like his mother, that I could never forget it when I saw his
face. Poor girl! poor girl! She was so young, too! Such a gentle lamb!
Wait; there's more to tell. I have not told you all, have I?
subQuotationList: ['The boy grew so like his mother,', "that I could never forget it when I saw his\nface. Poor girl! poor girl! She was so young, too! Such a gentle lamb!\nWait; there's more to tell. I have not told you all, have I?"]
speaker: Mrs. Thingummy

quoteText:
No, no, Be quick, or it may be
too late!
subQuotationList: ['No, no,', 'Be quick, or it may be\ntoo late!']
speaker: Mrs. Corney

quoteText: The mother,
subQuotationList: ['The mother,']
speaker: Mrs. Thingummy

quoteText:
the mother, when the pains of death first came upon her, whispered in
my ear that if her baby was born alive, and thrived, the day might come
when it would not feel so much disgraced to hear its poor young mother
named.
subQuotationList:
['the mother, when the pains of death first came upon her, whispered in
my ear that if her baby was born alive, and thrived, the day might come
when it would not feel so much disgraced to hear its poor young mother
named.']
speaker: Mrs. Thingummy

quoteText:
she said, folding her thin hands
together,
subQuotationList: ['she said, folding her thin hands\ntogether,']
speaker: Mrs. Thingummy

quoteText: The boy's name?
subQuotationList: ["The boy's name?"]
speaker: Mrs. Corney

quoteText:
They _called_ him Oliver, The gold I
stole was
subQuotationList: ['They _called_ him Oliver,', 'The gold I\nstole was']
speaker: Mrs. Thingummy

quoteText: Yes, yes what?
subQuotationList: ['Yes, yes what?']
speaker: Mrs. Corney

quoteText: Stone dead!
subQuotationList: ['Stone dead!']
speaker: _unknowable
referringExpression: said one of the old women

quoteText: And nothing to tell, after all,
subQuotationList: ['And nothing to tell, after all,']
speaker: Mrs. Corney

quoteText:
That's two doubles and the rub, I never see
such a feller as you, Jack; you win everything. Even when we've good
cards, Charley and I can't make nothing of 'em.
subQuotationList: ["That's two doubles and the rub,", "I never see\nsuch a feller as you, Jack; you win everything. Even when we've good\ncards, Charley and I can't make nothing of 'em."]
speaker: Mr. Chitling
mentionEntitiesList: [[], [['The Artful Dodger'], ['The Artful Dodger'], ['The Artful Dodger'], ['Mr. Chitling', 'Charley Bates'], ['Charley Bates']]]

quoteText:
Matter, Fagin! I wish you had watched the play. Tommy
Chitling hasn't won a point; and I went partners with him against the
Artfull and dumb.
subQuotationList: ['Matter, Fagin!', "I wish you had watched the play. Tommy\nChitling hasn't won a point; and I went partners with him against the\nArtfull and dumb."]
speaker: Charley Bates

quoteText:
Ay, ay! Try 'em again, Tom;
try 'em again.
subQuotationList: ['Ay, ay!', "Try 'em again, Tom;\ntry 'em again."]
speaker: Fagin

quoteText:
No more of it for me, thank 'ee, Fagin, I've
had enough. That 'ere Dodger has such a run of luck that there's no
standing again' him.
subQuotationList: ["No more of it for me, thank 'ee, Fagin,", "I've\nhad enough. That 'ere Dodger has such a run of luck that there's no\nstanding again' him."]
speaker: Mr. Chitling

quoteText:
Ha! ha! my dear, you must get up very early in the
morning, to win against the Dodger.
subQuotationList: ['Ha! ha! my dear,', 'you must get up very early in the\nmorning, to win against the Dodger.']
speaker: Fagin

quoteText:
Morning! you must put your boots on over-night,
and have a telescope at each eye, and a opera-glass between your
shoulders, if you want to come over him.
subQuotationList: ['Morning!', 'you must put your boots on over-night,\nand have a telescope at each eye, and a opera-glass between your\nshoulders, if you want to come over him.']
speaker: Charley Bates

quoteText:
How precious dull you are, Tommy! What
do you think he's thinking of, Fagin?
subQuotationList: ['How precious dull you are, Tommy!', "What\ndo you think he's thinking of, Fagin?"]
speaker: The Artful Dodger
referringExpression: said the Dodger stopping short when there had been a long silence and addressing Mr Chitling

quoteText:
How should I know, my dear? About his losses, maybe; or the little retirement
in the country that he's just left, eh? Ha! ha! Is that it, my dear?
subQuotationList: ['How should I know, my dear?', "About his losses, maybe; or the little retirement\nin the country that he's just left, eh? Ha! ha! Is that it, my dear?"]
speaker: Fagin

quoteText:
Not a bit of it, What do _you_ say,
Charley?
subQuotationList: ['Not a bit of it,', 'What do _you_ say,\nCharley?']
speaker: The Artful Dodger

quoteText:
_I_ should say, that he was
uncommon sweet upon Betsy. See how he's a-blushing! Oh, my eye! here's
a merry-go-rounder! Tommy Chitling's in love! Oh, Fagin, Fagin! what a
spree!
subQuotationList:
['_I_ should say,', "that he was
uncommon sweet upon Betsy. See how he's a-blushing! Oh, my eye! here's
a merry-go-rounder! Tommy Chitling's in love! Oh, Fagin, Fagin! what a
spree!"]
speaker: Charley Bates

quoteText: Never mind him, my dear, Betsy's a fine girl. Stick up to her, Tom. Stick up to her.
subQuotationList: ['Never mind him, my dear,', "Betsy's a fine girl. Stick up to her, Tom. Stick up to her."]
speaker: Fagin

quoteText: What I mean to say, Fagin, is, that that isn't anything to anybody here.
subQuotationList: ['What I mean to say, Fagin,', "is, that that isn't anything to anybody here."]
speaker: Mr. Chitling

quoteText:
No more it is, Charley will talk. Don't mind him,
my dear; don't mind him. Betsy's a fine girl. Do as she bids you, Tom,
and you will make your fortune.
subQuotationList: ['No more it is,', "Charley will talk. Don't mind him,\nmy dear; don't mind him. Betsy's a fine girl. Do as she bids you, Tom,\nand you will make your fortune."]
speaker: Fagin
mentionEntitiesList: [[], [['Charley Bates'], ['Charley Bates'], ['Mr. Chitling'], ['Charley Bates'], ['Betsy'], ['Betsy'], ['Mr. Chitling'], ['Mr. Chitling'], ['Mr. Chitling'], ['Mr. Chitling']]]

quoteText:
So I _do_ do as she bids me, I shouldn't have
been milled, if it hadn't been for her advice. But it turned out a good
job for you; didn't it, Fagin! And what's six weeks of it? It must
come, some time or another, and why not in the winter time when you
don't want to go out a-walking so much; eh, Fagin?
subQuotationList:
['So I _do_ do as she bids me,', "I shouldn't have
been milled, if it hadn't been for her advice. But it turned out a good
job for you; didn't it, Fagin! And what's six weeks of it? It must
come, some time or another, and why not in the winter time when you
don't want to go out a-walking so much; eh, Fagin?"]
speaker: Mr. Chitling

quoteText: Ah, to be sure, my dear,
subQuotationList: ['Ah, to be sure, my dear,']
speaker: Fagin

quoteText: You wouldn't mind it again, Tom, would you, if Bet was all right?
subQuotationList: ["You wouldn't mind it again, Tom, would you,", 'if Bet was all right?']
speaker: The Artful Dodger

quoteText:
I mean to say that I shouldn't, There, now.
Ah! Who'll say as much as that, I should like to know; eh, Fagin?
subQuotationList: ["I mean to say that I shouldn't,", "There, now.\nAh! Who'll say as much as that, I should like to know; eh, Fagin?"]
speaker: Mr. Chitling

quoteText:
Nobody, my dear, not a soul, Tom. I don't know one
of 'em that would do it besides you; not one of 'em, my dear.
subQuotationList: ['Nobody, my dear,', "not a soul, Tom. I don't know one\nof 'em that would do it besides you; not one of 'em, my dear."]
speaker: Fagin

quoteText:
I might have got clear off, if I'd split upon her; mightn't I, Fagin? A word from me would have
done it; wouldn't it, Fagin?
subQuotationList: ["I might have got clear off, if I'd split upon her; mightn't I, Fagin?", "A word from me would have\ndone it; wouldn't it, Fagin?"]
speaker: Mr. Chitling

quoteText: To be sure it would, my dear,
subQuotationList: ['To be sure it would, my dear,']
speaker: Fagin

quoteText: But I didn't blab it; did I, Fagin?
subQuotationList: ["But I didn't blab it; did I, Fagin?"]
speaker: Mr. Chitling

quoteText:
No, no, to be sure, you were too stout-hearted for
that. A deal too stout, my dear!
subQuotationList: ['No, no, to be sure,', 'you were too stout-hearted for\nthat. A deal too stout, my dear!']
speaker: Fagin

quoteText:
Perhaps I was, and if I was, what's to
laugh at, in that; eh, Fagin?
subQuotationList: ['Perhaps I was,', "and if I was, what's to\nlaugh at, in that; eh, Fagin?"]
speaker: Mr. Chitling

quoteText: Hark! I heard the tinkler.
subQuotationList: ['Hark!', 'I heard the tinkler.']
speaker: The Artful Dodger

quoteText: What! alone?
subQuotationList: ['What!', 'alone?']
speaker: Fagin

quoteText: Where is he?
subQuotationList: ['Where is he?']
speaker: Fagin

quoteText:
Yes, bring him down. Hush!
Quiet, Charley! Gently, Tom! Scarce, scarce!
subQuotationList: ['Yes,', 'bring him down. Hush!\nQuiet, Charley! Gently, Tom! Scarce, scarce!']
speaker: Fagin

quoteText:
How are you, Faguey? Pop that
shawl away in my castor, Dodger, so that I may know where to find it
when I cut; that's the time of day! You'll be a fine young cracksman
afore the old file now.
subQuotationList:
['How are you, Faguey?', "Pop that
shawl away in my castor, Dodger, so that I may know where to find it
when I cut; that's the time of day! You'll be a fine young cracksman
afore the old file now."]
speaker: Toby Crackit

quoteText:
See there, Faguey, not a drop of Day and Martin since you know when; not a bubble of
blacking, by Jove! But don't look at me in that way, man. All in good
time. I can't talk about business till I've eat and drank; so produce
the sustainance, and let's have a quiet fill-out for the first time
these three days!
subQuotationList:
['See there, Faguey,', "not a drop of Day and Martin since you know when; not a bubble of
blacking, by Jove! But don't look at me in that way, man. All in good
time. I can't talk about business till I've eat and drank; so produce
the sustainance, and let's have a quiet fill-out for the first time
these three days!"]
speaker: Toby Crackit

quoteText: First and foremost, Faguey,
subQuotationList: ['First and foremost, Faguey,']
speaker: Toby Crackit

quoteText: Yes, yes!
subQuotationList: ['Yes, yes!']
speaker: Fagin

quoteText: First and foremost, Faguey, how's Bill?
subQuotationList: ['First and foremost, Faguey,', "how's Bill?"]
speaker: Toby Crackit

quoteText: What!
subQuotationList: ['What!']
speaker: Fagin

quoteText: Why, you don't mean to say
subQuotationList: ["Why, you don't mean to say"]
speaker: Toby Crackit

quoteText:
Mean! Where are
they? Sikes and the boy! Where are they? Where have they been? Where
are they hiding? Why have they not been here?
subQuotationList: ['Mean!', 'Where are\nthey? Sikes and the boy! Where are they? Where have they been? Where\nare they hiding? Why have they not been here?']
speaker: Fagin
mentionEntitiesList: [[], [['Bill Sikes', 'Oliver Twist'], ['Bill Sikes'], ['Oliver Twist'], ['Bill Sikes', 'Oliver Twist'], ['Bill Sikes', 'Oliver Twist'], ['Bill Sikes', 'Oliver Twist'], ['Bill Sikes', 'Oliver Twist']]]

quoteText: The crack failed,
subQuotationList: ['The crack failed,']
speaker: Toby Crackit

quoteText: I know it, What more?
subQuotationList: ['I know it,', 'What more?']
speaker: Fagin

quoteText:
They fired and hit the boy. We cut over the fields at the back, with
him between us straight as the crow flies through hedge and ditch. They
gave chase. Damme! the whole country was awake, and the dogs upon us.
subQuotationList: ['They fired and hit the boy. We cut over the fields at the back, with\nhim between us straight as the crow flies through hedge and ditch. They\ngave chase. Damme! the whole country was awake, and the dogs upon us.']
speaker: Toby Crackit
mentionEntitiesList: [[['Oliver Twist'], ['Bill Sikes', 'Toby Crackit'], ['Oliver Twist'], ['Bill Sikes', 'Toby Crackit'], ['Bill Sikes', 'Oliver Twist', 'Toby Crackit']]]

quoteText: The boy!
subQuotationList: ['The boy!']
speaker: Fagin

quoteText:
Bill had him on his back, and scudded like the wind. We stopped to
take him between us; his head hung down, and he was cold. They were
close upon our heels; every man for himself, and each from the gallows!
We parted company, and left the youngster lying in a ditch. Alive or
dead, that's all I know about him.
subQuotationList:
["Bill had him on his back, and scudded like the wind. We stopped to
take him between us; his head hung down, and he was cold. They were
close upon our heels; every man for himself, and each from the gallows!
We parted company, and left the youngster lying in a ditch. Alive or
dead, that's all I know about him."]
speaker: Toby Crackit
mentionEntitiesList: [[['Bill Sikes'], ['Oliver Twist'], ['Bill Sikes'], ['Bill Sikes', 'Toby Crackit'], ['Oliver Twist'], ['Bill Sikes', 'Toby Crackit'], ['Oliver Twist'], ['Oliver Twist'], ['Bill Sikes', 'Toby Crackit'], ['Oliver Twist'], ['Oliver Twist']]]

quoteText: Why, the sight of you, Mr. Fagin, would cure the hoptalmy!
subQuotationList: ['Why, the sight of you, Mr. Fagin, would cure the hoptalmy!']
speaker: Mr. Lively

quoteText: The neighbourhood was a little too hot, Lively,
subQuotationList: ['The neighbourhood was a little too hot, Lively,']
speaker: Fagin

quoteText: Well, I've heerd that complaint of it, once or twice before, but it soon cools down again; don't you find it so?
subQuotationList: ["Well, I've heerd that complaint of it, once or twice before,", "but it soon cools down again; don't you find it so?"]
speaker: Mr. Lively

quoteText: At the Cripples?
subQuotationList: ['At the Cripples?']
speaker: Mr. Lively

quoteText:
Let me see, Yes, there's some half-dozen of 'em gone in, that I knows. I don't
think your friend's there.
subQuotationList: ['Let me see,', "Yes, there's some half-dozen of 'em gone in, that I knows. I don't\nthink your friend's there."]
speaker: Mr. Lively

quoteText: Sikes is not, I suppose?

your own B.?
subQuotationList: ['It must have been something, love,', "Won't you tell\nyour own B.?"]
speaker: Mr. Bumble

quoteText:
Not now, one of these days. After we're married,
dear.
subQuotationList: ['Not now,', "one of these days. After we're married,\ndear."]
speaker: Mrs. Corney

quoteText:
After we're married! It wasn't any impudence
from any of them male paupers as
subQuotationList: ["After we're married!", "It wasn't any impudence\nfrom any of them male paupers as"]
speaker: Mr. Bumble

quoteText: No, no, love!
subQuotationList: ['No, no, love!']
speaker: Mrs. Corney

quoteText:
If I thought it was, if I thought as any one
of 'em had dared to lift his wulgar eyes to that lovely countenance
subQuotationList: ['If I thought it was,', "if I thought as any one\nof 'em had dared to lift his wulgar eyes to that lovely countenance"]
speaker: Mr. Bumble

quoteText: They wouldn't have dared to do it, love,
subQuotationList: ["They wouldn't have dared to do it, love,"]
speaker: Mrs. Corney

quoteText:
They had better not! Let me see
any man, porochial or extra-porochial, as would presume to do it; and I
can tell him that he wouldn't do it a second time!
subQuotationList: ['They had better not!', "Let me see\nany man, porochial or extra-porochial, as would presume to do it; and I\ncan tell him that he wouldn't do it a second time!"]
speaker: Mr. Bumble

quoteText:
Here's a delicious fat one, Noah, dear! try him, do;
only this one.
subQuotationList: ["Here's a delicious fat one, Noah, dear!", 'try him, do;\nonly this one.']
speaker: Mrs. Bolter

quoteText:
What a delicious thing is a oyster! What a pity it is, a number of 'em should ever make
you feel uncomfortable; isn't it, Charlotte?
subQuotationList: ['What a delicious thing is a oyster!', "What a pity it is, a number of 'em should ever make\nyou feel uncomfortable; isn't it, Charlotte?"]
speaker: Noah Claypole

quoteText: It's quite a cruelty,
subQuotationList: ["It's quite a cruelty,"]
speaker: Mrs. Bolter

quoteText: So it is, An't yer fond of oysters?
subQuotationList: ['So it is,', "An't yer fond of oysters?"]
speaker: Noah Claypole

quoteText:
Not overmuch, I like to see you eat 'em, Noah
dear, better than eating 'em myself.
subQuotationList: ['Not overmuch,', "I like to see you eat 'em, Noah\ndear, better than eating 'em myself."]
speaker: Mrs. Bolter

quoteText: Lor! how queer!
subQuotationList: ['Lor!', 'how queer!']
speaker: Noah Claypole

quoteText:
Have another, Here's one with such a beautiful,
delicate beard!
subQuotationList: ['Have another,', "Here's one with such a beautiful,\ndelicate beard!"]
speaker: Mrs. Bolter

quoteText:
I can't manage any more, I'm very sorry. Come here,
Charlotte, and I'll kiss yer.
subQuotationList: ["I can't manage any more,", "I'm very sorry. Come here,\nCharlotte, and I'll kiss yer."]
speaker: Noah Claypole

quoteText: What! Say that again, sir. Say it again, you wile, owdacious fellow!
subQuotationList: ['What!', 'Say that again, sir.', 'Say it again, you wile, owdacious fellow!']
speaker: Mr. Bumble

quoteText:
How dare
you mention such a thing, sir? And how dare you encourage him, you
insolent minx? Kiss her! Faugh!
subQuotationList: ['How dare\nyou mention such a thing, sir? And how dare you encourage him, you\ninsolent minx? Kiss her!', 'Faugh!']
speaker: Mr. Bumble
mentionEntitiesList: [[['Noah Claypole'], ['Noah Claypole'], ['Mrs. Bolter'], ['Noah Claypole'], ['Mrs. Bolter'], ['Mrs. Bolter']], []]

quoteText:
I didn't mean to do it! She's always
a-kissing of me, whether I like it, or not.
subQuotationList: ["I didn't mean to do it!", "She's always\na-kissing of me, whether I like it, or not."]
speaker: Noah Claypole

quoteText: Oh, Noah,
subQuotationList: ['Oh, Noah,']
speaker: Mrs. Bolter

quoteText:
Yer are; yer know yer are! She's always a-doin' of
it, Mr. Bumble, sir; she chucks me under the chin, please, sir; and
makes all manner of love!
subQuotationList: ['Yer are; yer know yer are!', "She's always a-doin' of\nit, Mr. Bumble, sir; she chucks me under the chin, please, sir; and\nmakes all manner of love!"]
speaker: Noah Claypole
mentionEntitiesList: [[['Mrs. Bolter'], ['Mrs. Bolter'], ['Mrs. Bolter']], [['Mrs. Bolter'], ['Mr. Bumble'], ['Mr. Bumble'], ['Mrs. Bolter'], ['Mr. Bumble']]]

quoteText:
Silence! Take yourself downstairs, ma'am.
Noah, you shut up the shop; say another word till your master comes
home, at your peril; and, when he does come home, tell him that Mr.
Bumble said he was to send a old woman's shell after breakfast
to-morrow morning. Do you hear sir? Kissing! The sin and wickedness of the lower orders in this
porochial district is frightful! If Parliament don't take their
abominable courses under consideration, this country's ruined, and the
character of the peasantry gone for ever!
subQuotationList:
['Silence!', "Take yourself downstairs, ma'am.
Noah, you shut up the shop; say another word till your master comes
home, at your peril; and, when he does come home, tell him that Mr.

quoteText:
Wolves tear your throats! I wish
I was among some of you; you'd howl the hoarser for it.
subQuotationList: ['Wolves tear your throats!', "I wish\nI was among some of you; you'd howl the hoarser for it."]
speaker: Bill Sikes

quoteText: Stop, you white-livered hound! Stop!
subQuotationList: ['Stop, you white-livered hound!', 'Stop!']
speaker: Bill Sikes

quoteText: Bear a hand with the boy, Come back! Quicker! Don't play booty with me.
subQuotationList: ['Bear a hand with the boy,', 'Come back!', 'Quicker!', "Don't play booty with me."]
speaker: Bill Sikes

quoteText:
It's all up, Bill! drop the kid, and show 'em your
heels.
subQuotationList: ["It's all up, Bill!", "drop the kid, and show 'em your\nheels."]
speaker: Toby Crackit

quoteText:
Ho, ho, there! Pincher!
Neptune! Come here, come here!
subQuotationList: ['Ho, ho, there!', 'Pincher!\nNeptune! Come here, come here!']
speaker: The Tinker

quoteText: My advice, or, leastways, I should say, my _orders_, is, that we 'mediately go home again.
subQuotationList: ['My advice, or, leastways, I should say, my _orders_, is,', "that we 'mediately go home again."]
speaker: Mr. Giles
referringExpression: said the fattest man of the party

quoteText: I am agreeable to anything which is agreeable to Mr. Giles,
subQuotationList: ['I am agreeable to anything which is agreeable to Mr. Giles,']
speaker: Mr. Brittles

quoteText: I shouldn't wish to appear ill-mannered, gentlemen, Mr. Giles ought to know.
subQuotationList: ["I shouldn't wish to appear ill-mannered, gentlemen,", 'Mr. Giles ought to know.']
speaker: The Tinker

quoteText:
Certainly, and whatever Mr. Giles says, it
isn't our place to contradict him. No, no, I know my sitiwation! Thank
my stars, I know my sitiwation.
subQuotationList: ['Certainly,', "and whatever Mr. Giles says, it\nisn't our place to contradict him. No, no, I know my sitiwation! Thank\nmy stars, I know my sitiwation."]
speaker: Mr. Brittles

quoteText: You are afraid, Brittles,
subQuotationList: ['You are afraid, Brittles,']
speaker: Mr. Giles

quoteText: I an't,
subQuotationList: ["I an't,"]
speaker: Mr. Brittles

quoteText: You are,
subQuotationList: ['You are,']
speaker: Mr. Giles

quoteText: You're a falsehood, Mr. Giles,
subQuotationList: ["You're a falsehood, Mr. Giles,"]
speaker: Mr. Brittles

quoteText: You're a lie, Brittles,
subQuotationList: ["You're a lie, Brittles,"]
speaker: Mr. Giles

quoteText: I'll tell you what it is, gentlemen, we're all afraid.
subQuotationList: ["I'll tell you what it is, gentlemen,", "we're all afraid."]
speaker: The Tinker
mentionEntitiesList: [[['Mr. Brittles', 'Mr. Giles'], ['Mr. Brittles', 'Mr. Giles']], [['Mr. Brittles', 'The Tinker', 'Mr. Giles']]]

quoteText: Speak for yourself, sir,
subQuotationList: ['Speak for yourself, sir,']
speaker: Mr. Giles

quoteText:
So I do, It's natural and proper to be afraid,
under such circumstances. I am.
subQuotationList: ['So I do,', "It's natural and proper to be afraid,\nunder such circumstances. I am."]
speaker: The Tinker

quoteText:
So am I, only there's no call to tell a man he is, so
bounceably.
subQuotationList: ['So am I,', "only there's no call to tell a man he is, so\nbounceably."]
speaker: Mr. Brittles

quoteText:
But it's wonderful, what a
man will do, when his blood is up. I should have committed murder I
know I should if we'd caught one of them rascals. I know what it was, it was the gate.
subQuotationList: ["But it's wonderful,", "what a\nman will do, when his blood is up. I should have committed murder I\nknow I should if we'd caught one of them rascals.", 'I know what it was,', 'it was the gate.']
speaker: Mr. Giles

quoteText: I shouldn't wonder if it was,
subQuotationList: ["I shouldn't wonder if it was,"]
speaker: Mr. Brittles

quoteText:
You may depend upon it, that that gate stopped the flow
of the excitement. I felt all mine suddenly going away, as I was
climbing over it.
subQuotationList: ['You may depend upon it,', 'that that gate stopped the flow\nof the excitement. I felt all mine suddenly going away, as I was\nclimbing over it.']
speaker: Mr. Giles

quoteText:
It was about half-past two, or I wouldn't swear that
it mightn't have been a little nearer three, when I woke up, and,
turning round in my bed, as it might be so, (here Mr. Giles turned
round in his chair, and pulled the corner of the table-cloth over him
to imitate bed-clothes,) I fancied I heerd a noise.
subQuotationList:
['It was about half-past two,', "or I wouldn't swear that
it mightn't have been a little nearer three, when I woke up, and,
turning round in my bed, as it might be so, (here Mr. Giles turned
round in his chair, and pulled the corner of the table-cloth over him
to imitate bed-clothes,) I fancied I heerd a noise."]
speaker: Mr. Giles

quoteText: Heerd a noise,
subQuotationList: ['Heerd a noise,']
speaker: Mr. Giles

quoteText:
I says, at first, and was composing myself off to sleep, when I heerd the
noise again, distinct.
subQuotationList: ['I says, at first,', 'and was composing myself off to sleep, when I heerd the\nnoise again, distinct.']
speaker: Mr. Giles

quoteText: What sort of a noise?
subQuotationList: ['What sort of a noise?']
speaker: The Cook

quoteText: A kind of a busting noise,
subQuotationList: ['A kind of a busting noise,']
speaker: Mr. Giles

quoteText: More like the noise of powdering a iron bar on a nutmeg-grater,
subQuotationList: ['More like the noise of powdering a iron bar on a nutmeg-grater,']
speaker: Mr. Brittles

quoteText:
It was, when _you_ heerd it, sir, but, at this
time, it had a busting sound. I turned down the clothes sat up in bed; and listened.
subQuotationList: ['It was, when _you_ heerd it, sir,', 'but, at this\ntime, it had a busting sound. I turned down the clothes', 'sat up in bed; and listened.']
speaker: Mr. Giles

quoteText: Lor!
speaker: _group
referringExpression: The cook and housemaid simultaneously ejaculated

quoteText: I heerd it now, quite apparent,
subQuotationList: ['I heerd it now, quite apparent,']
speaker: Mr. Giles

quoteText:
I
says
subQuotationList: ['I\nsays']
speaker: Mr. Giles

quoteText: I says
subQuotationList: ['I says']
speaker: Mr. Giles

quoteText:
I tossed off the clothes, got softly out of
bed; drew on a pair of
subQuotationList: ['I tossed off the clothes,', 'got softly out of\nbed; drew on a pair of']
speaker: Mr. Giles

quoteText: Ladies present, Mr. Giles,
subQuotationList: ['Ladies present, Mr. Giles,']
speaker: The Tinker

quoteText: Of _shoes_, sir,
subQuotationList: ['Of _shoes_, sir,']
speaker: Mr. Giles

quoteText:
seized the loaded pistol that always goes
upstairs with the plate-basket; and walked on tiptoes to his room.
subQuotationList: ['seized the loaded pistol that always goes\nupstairs with the plate-basket; and walked on tiptoes to his room.']
speaker: Mr. Giles

quoteText: I says, when I had woke him,
subQuotationList: ['I says, when I had woke him,']
speaker: Mr. Giles

quoteText: So you did,
subQuotationList: ['So you did,']
speaker: Mr. Brittles

quoteText: I says,
subQuotationList: ['I says,']
speaker: Mr. Giles

quoteText: _Was_ he frightened?
subQuotationList: ['_Was_ he frightened?']
speaker: The Cook

quoteText:
Not a bit of it, He was as firm ah! pretty near
as firm as I was.
subQuotationList: ['Not a bit of it,', 'He was as firm ah! pretty near\nas firm as I was.']
speaker: Mr. Giles

quoteText: I should have died at once, I'm sure, if it had been me,
subQuotationList: ["I should have died at once, I'm sure, if it had been me,"]
speaker: The Housemaid

quoteText: You're a woman,
subQuotationList: ["You're a woman,"]
speaker: Mr. Brittles

quoteText:
Brittles is right, from a woman, nothing else was to be expected. We, being men, took a
dark lantern that was standing on Brittle's hob, and groped our way
downstairs in the pitch dark, as it might be so. It was a knock, Open the
door, somebody. It seems a strange sort of a thing, a knock coming at such a time in
the morning, but the door must be opened. Do
you hear, somebody?
subQuotationList:
['Brittles is right,', "from a woman, nothing else was to be expected. We, being men, took a
dark lantern that was standing on Brittle's hob, and groped our way
downstairs in the pitch dark, as it might be so.", 'It was a knock,', 'Open the
door, somebody.', 'It seems a strange sort of a thing, a knock coming at such a time in
the morning,', 'but the door must be opened. Do
you hear, somebody?']
speaker: Mr. Giles

quoteText: If Brittles would rather open the door, in the presence of witnesses, I am ready to make one.
subQuotationList: ['If Brittles would rather open the door, in the presence of witnesses,', 'I am ready to make one.']
speaker: Mr. Giles

quoteText: So am I,
subQuotationList: ['So am I,']
speaker: The Tinker

quoteText:
A boy! What's the matter with the eh? Why Brittles look
here don't you know?
subQuotationList: ['A boy!', "What's the matter with the eh? Why Brittles look\nhere don't you know?"]
speaker: Mr. Giles

quoteText:
Here he is! here's one of the thieves, ma'am! Here's a thief, miss!
Wounded, miss! I shot him, miss; and Brittles held the light.
subQuotationList: ['Here he is!', "here's one of the thieves, ma'am! Here's a thief, miss!\nWounded, miss! I shot him, miss; and Brittles held the light."]
speaker: Mr. Giles
addressees: ['Rose Maylie', 'The Housemaid', 'The Cook', 'Mrs. Maylie', 'Mr. Brittles', 'The Tinker']
mentionEntitiesList: [[['Oliver Twist']], [['Mrs. Maylie'], ['Rose Maylie'], ['Rose Maylie'], ['Oliver Twist'], ['Rose Maylie'], ['Mr. Brittles']]]

quoteText: In a lantern, miss,
subQuotationList: ['In a lantern, miss,']
speaker: Mr. Brittles

quoteText: Giles!
subQuotationList: ['Giles!']
speaker: Rose Maylie
referringExpression: whispered the voice from the stairhead

quoteText:
I'm here, miss, Don't be frightened, miss; I
ain't much injured. He didn't make a very desperate resistance, miss! I
was soon too many for him.
subQuotationList: ["I'm here, miss,", "Don't be frightened, miss; I\nain't much injured. He didn't make a very desperate resistance, miss! I\nwas soon too many for him."]
speaker: Mr. Giles

quoteText:
Hush! you frighten my aunt as much as the
thieves did. Is the poor creature much hurt?
subQuotationList: ['Hush!', 'you frighten my aunt as much as the\nthieves did. Is the poor creature much hurt?']
speaker: Rose Maylie

quoteText: Wounded desperate, miss,
subQuotationList: ['Wounded desperate, miss,']
speaker: Mr. Giles

quoteText:
He looks as if he was a-going, miss, Wouldn't you like to come and look at him, miss, in
case he should?
subQuotationList: ['He looks as if he was a-going, miss,', "Wouldn't you like to come and look at him, miss, in\ncase he should?"]
speaker: Mr. Brittles
mentionEntitiesList: [[['Oliver Twist'], ['Oliver Twist'], ['Rose Maylie']], [['Rose Maylie'], ['Oliver Twist'], ['Rose Maylie'], ['Oliver Twist']]]

quoteText:
Hush, pray; there's a good man! Wait quietly only
one instant, while I speak to aunt.
subQuotationList: ["Hush, pray; there's a good man!", 'Wait quietly only\none instant, while I speak to aunt.']
speaker: Rose Maylie

quoteText: But won't you take one look at him, first, miss? Not one little peep, miss?
subQuotationList: ["But won't you take one look at him, first, miss?", 'Not one little peep, miss?']
speaker: Mr. Giles

quoteText:
Not now, for the world, Poor fellow! Oh!
treat him kindly, Giles for my sake!
subQuotationList: ['Not now, for the world,', 'Poor fellow! Oh!\ntreat him kindly, Giles for my sake!']
speaker: Rose Maylie

quoteText: And Brittles has been gone upwards of an hour, has he?
subQuotationList: ['And Brittles has been gone upwards of an hour, has he?']
speaker: Mrs. Maylie

quoteText: An hour and twelve minutes, ma'am,
subQuotationList: ["An hour and twelve minutes, ma'am,"]
speaker: Mr. Giles

quoteText: He is always slow,
subQuotationList: ['He is always slow,']
speaker: Mrs. Maylie

quoteText: Brittles always was a slow boy, ma'am,
subQuotationList: ["Brittles always was a slow boy, ma'am,"]
speaker: Mr. Giles

quoteText: He gets worse instead of better, I think,
subQuotationList: ['He gets worse instead of better, I think,']
speaker: Mrs. Maylie

quoteText:
It is very inexcusable in him if he stops to play with any other
boys,
subQuotationList: ['It is very inexcusable in him if he stops to play with any other\nboys,']
speaker: Rose Maylie

quoteText:
I never heard of such a thing! My dear
Mrs. Maylie bless my soul in the silence of the night, too I _never_
heard of such a thing!
subQuotationList: ['I never heard of such a thing!', 'My dear\nMrs. Maylie bless my soul in the silence of the night, too I _never_\nheard of such a thing!']
speaker: Mr. Losberne

quoteText:
You ought to be dead; positively dead with the fright, Why didn't you send? Bless me, my man should have come in a
minute; and so would I; and my assistant would have been delighted; or
anybody, I'm sure, under such circumstances. Dear, dear! So unexpected!
In the silence of the night, too!
subQuotationList:
['You ought to be dead; positively dead with the fright,', "Why didn't you send? Bless me, my man should have come in a
minute; and so would I; and my assistant would have been delighted; or
anybody, I'm sure, under such circumstances. Dear, dear! So unexpected!
In the silence of the night, too!"]
speaker: Mr. Losberne

quoteText: And you, Miss Rose, I
subQuotationList: ['And you, Miss Rose,', 'I']
speaker: Mr. Losberne

quoteText:
Oh! very much so, indeed, but there is
a poor creature upstairs, whom aunt wishes you to see.
subQuotationList: ['Oh! very much so, indeed,', 'but there is\na poor creature upstairs, whom aunt wishes you to see.']
speaker: Rose Maylie

quoteText:
Ah! to be sure, so there is. That was your
handiwork, Giles, I understand.
subQuotationList: ['Ah! to be sure,', 'so there is. That was your\nhandiwork, Giles, I understand.']
speaker: Mr. Losberne

quoteText:
Honour, eh? well, I don't know; perhaps it's as
honourable to hit a thief in a back kitchen, as to hit your man at
twelve paces. Fancy that he fired in the air, and you've fought a duel,
Giles. Gad, that's true! Where is he? Show me the way.
I'll look in again, as I come down, Mrs. Maylie. That's the little
window that he got in at, eh? Well, I couldn't have believed it! This is a very extraordinary thing, Mrs. Maylie,
subQuotationList:
['Honour, eh?', "well, I don't know; perhaps it's as
honourable to hit a thief in a back kitchen, as to hit your man at
twelve paces. Fancy that he fired in the air, and you've fought a duel,
Giles.", "Gad, that's true!", "Where is he? Show me the way.
I'll look in again, as I come down, Mrs. Maylie. That's the little
window that he got in at, eh? Well, I couldn't have believed it!", 'This is a very extraordinary thing, Mrs. Maylie,']
speaker: Mr. Losberne
mentionEntitiesList: [[], [['Oliver Twist'], ['Mr. Giles'], ['Mr. Giles']], [], [['Oliver Twist'], ['Mrs. Maylie'], ['Oliver Twist']], [['Mrs. Maylie']]]

quoteText: He is not in danger, I hope?
subQuotationList: ['He is not in danger, I hope?']
speaker: Mrs. Maylie

quoteText:
Why, that would _not_ be an extraordinary thing, under the
circumstances, though I don't think he is. Have
you seen the thief?
subQuotationList: ['Why, that would _not_ be an extraordinary thing, under the\ncircumstances,', "though I don't think he is. Have\nyou seen the thief?"]
speaker: Mr. Losberne

quoteText: No,
speaker: Mrs. Maylie

quoteText: Nor heard anything about him?
subQuotationList: ['Nor heard anything about him?']
speaker: Mr. Losberne

quoteText: No.
speaker: Mrs. Maylie

quoteText:
I beg your pardon, ma'am, but I was going to
tell you about him when Doctor Losberne came in.
subQuotationList: ["I beg your pardon, ma'am,", 'but I was going to\ntell you about him when Doctor Losberne came in.']
speaker: Mr. Giles

quoteText:
Rose wished to see the man, but I wouldn't hear of
it.
subQuotationList: ['Rose wished to see the man,', "but I wouldn't hear of\nit."]
speaker: Mrs. Maylie

quoteText:
Humph! There is nothing very alarming in his
appearance. Have you any objection to see him in my presence?
subQuotationList: ['Humph!', 'There is nothing very alarming in his\nappearance. Have you any objection to see him in my presence?']
speaker: Mr. Losberne

quoteText: If it be necessary, certainly not.
subQuotationList: ['If it be necessary,', 'certainly not.']
speaker: Mrs. Maylie

quoteText:
Then I think it is necessary, at all events, I am
quite sure that you would deeply regret not having done so, if you
postponed it. He is perfectly quiet and comfortable now. Allow me Miss
Rose, will you permit me? Not the slightest fear, I pledge you my
honour!
subQuotationList:
['Then I think it is necessary,', 'at all events, I am
quite sure that you would deeply regret not having done so, if you
postponed it. He is perfectly quiet and comfortable now. Allow me Miss
Rose, will you permit me? Not the slightest fear, I pledge you my
honour!']
speaker: Mr. Losberne
mentionEntitiesList: [[], [['Mrs. Maylie'], ['Mrs. Maylie'], ['Oliver Twist'], ['Rose Maylie'], ['Rose Maylie'], ['Rose Maylie']]]

quoteText:
Now, let us hear what you think of him. He has not been
shaved very recently, but he don't look at all ferocious
notwithstanding. Stop, though! Let me first see that he is in visiting
order.
subQuotationList:
['Now,', "let us hear what you think of him. He has not been
shaved very recently, but he don't look at all ferocious
notwithstanding. Stop, though! Let me first see that he is in visiting
order."]
speaker: Mr. Losberne
mentionEntitiesList: [[], [['Mr. Giles', 'Mr. Losberne', 'Rose Maylie', 'Mrs. Maylie'], ['Rose Maylie', 'Mrs. Maylie'], ['Oliver Twist'], ['Oliver Twist'], ['Oliver Twist'], ['Oliver Twist']]]

quoteText:
What can this mean? This poor child can
never have been the pupil of robbers!
subQuotationList: ['What can this mean?', 'This poor child can\nnever have been the pupil of robbers!']
speaker: Mrs. Maylie

quoteText:
Vice, takes up her abode in
many temples; and who can say that a fair outside shell not enshrine
her?
subQuotationList: ['Vice,', 'takes up her abode in\nmany temples; and who can say that a fair outside shell not enshrine\nher?']
speaker: Mr. Losberne

quoteText: But at so early an age!
subQuotationList: ['But at so early an age!']
speaker: Rose Maylie

quoteText:
My dear young lady, crime, like death, is not confined to the old and withered
alone. The youngest and fairest are too often its chosen victims.
subQuotationList: ['My dear young lady,', 'crime, like death, is not confined to the old and withered\nalone. The youngest and fairest are too often its chosen victims.']
speaker: Mr. Losberne

quoteText:
But, can you oh! can you really believe that this delicate boy has
been the voluntary associate of the worst outcasts of society?
subQuotationList: ['But, can you oh! can you really believe that this delicate boy has\nbeen the voluntary associate of the worst outcasts of society?']
speaker: Rose Maylie

quoteText:
But even if he has been wicked, think how young he is;
think that he may never have known a mother's love, or the comfort of a
home; that ill-usage and blows, or the want of bread, may have driven
him to herd with men who have forced him to guilt. Aunt, dear aunt, for
mercy's sake, think of this, before you let them drag this sick child
to a prison, which in any case must be the grave of all his chances of
amendment. Oh! as you love me, and know that I have never felt the want
of parents in your goodness and affection, but that I might have done
so, and might have been equally helpless and unprotected with this poor
child, have pity upon him before it is too late!
subQuotationList:
['But even if he has been wicked,', "think how young he is;
think that he may never have known a mother's love, or the comfort of a
home; that ill-usage and blows, or the want of bread, may have driven
him to herd with men who have forced him to guilt. Aunt, dear aunt, for
mercy's sake, think of this, before you let them drag this sick child
to a prison, which in any case must be the grave of all his chances of
amendment. Oh! as you love me, and know that I have never felt the want
of parents in your goodness and affection, but that I might have done
so, and might have been equally helpless and unprotected with this poor
child, have pity upon him before it is too late!"]
speaker: Rose Maylie
mentionEntitiesList: [[['Oliver Twist']], [['Oliver Twist'], ['Oliver Twist'], ['Oliver Twist'], ['Oliver Twist'], ['Mrs. Maylie'], ['Mrs. Maylie'], ['Mrs. Maylie'], ['Oliver Twist'], ['Oliver Twist'], ['Mrs. Maylie'], ['Mrs. Maylie'], ['Oliver Twist']]]

quoteText: My dear love, do you think I would harm a hair of his head?
subQuotationList: ['My dear love,', 'do you think I would harm a hair of his head?']
speaker: Mrs. Maylie

quoteText: Oh, no!
subQuotationList: ['Oh, no!']
speaker: Rose Maylie

quoteText:
No, surely, my days are drawing to their close:
and may mercy be shown to me as I show it to others! What can I do to
save him, sir?
subQuotationList: ['No, surely,', 'my days are drawing to their close:\nand may mercy be shown to me as I show it to others! What can I do to\nsave him, sir?']
speaker: Mrs. Maylie

quoteText: Let me think, ma'am, let me think.
subQuotationList: ["Let me think, ma'am,", 'let me think.']
speaker: Mr. Losberne

quoteText:
I think if you give me a full and unlimited commission to bully Giles,
and that little boy, Brittles, I can manage it. Giles is a faithful
fellow and an old servant, I know; but you can make it up to him in a
thousand ways, and reward him for being such a good shot besides. You
don't object to that?
subQuotationList:
["I think if you give me a full and unlimited commission to bully Giles,
and that little boy, Brittles, I can manage it. Giles is a faithful
fellow and an old servant, I know; but you can make it up to him in a
thousand ways, and reward him for being such a good shot besides. You
don't object to that?"]
speaker: Mr. Losberne
referringExpression: he at length made a dead halt and spoke
mentionEntitiesList: [[['Mrs. Maylie'], ['Mr. Giles'], ['Mr. Brittles'], ['Mr. Brittles'], ['Mr. Giles'], ['Mrs. Maylie'], ['Mr. Giles'], ['Mr. Giles'], ['Mrs. Maylie']]]

quoteText: Unless there is some other way of preserving the child,
subQuotationList: ['Unless there is some other way of preserving the child,']
speaker: Mrs. Maylie

quoteText: There is no other, No other, take my word for it.
subQuotationList: ['There is no other,', 'No other, take my word for it.']
speaker: Mr. Losberne

quoteText:
Then my aunt invests you with full power, but pray don't be harder upon the poor fellows than is
indispensably necessary.
subQuotationList: ['Then my aunt invests you with full power,', "but pray don't be harder upon the poor fellows than is\nindispensably necessary."]
speaker: Rose Maylie

quoteText:
You seem to think, that everybody is disposed
to be hard-hearted to-day, except yourself, Miss Rose. I only hope, for
the sake of the rising male sex generally, that you may be found in as
vulnerable and soft-hearted a mood by the first eligible young fellow
who appeals to your compassion; and I wish I were a young fellow, that
I might avail myself, on the spot, of such a favourable opportunity for
doing so, as the present.
subQuotationList:
['You seem to think,', 'that everybody is disposed
to be hard-hearted to-day, except yourself, Miss Rose. I only hope, for
the sake of the rising male sex generally, that you may be found in as
vulnerable and soft-hearted a mood by the first eligible young fellow
who appeals to your compassion; and I wish I were a young fellow, that
I might avail myself, on the spot, of such a favourable opportunity for
doing so, as the present.']
speaker: Mr. Losberne

quoteText: You are as great a boy as poor Brittles himself,
subQuotationList: ['You are as great a boy as poor Brittles himself,']
speaker: Rose Maylie

quoteText:
Well, that is no very difficult
matter. But to return to this boy. The great point of our agreement is
yet to come. He will wake in an hour or so, I dare say; and although I
have told that thick-headed constable-fellow downstairs that he musn't
be moved or spoken to, on peril of his life, I think we may converse
with him without danger. Now I make this stipulation that I shall
examine him in your presence, and that, if, from what he says, we
judge, and I can show to the satisfaction of your cool reason, that he
is a real and thorough bad one (which is more than possible), he shall
be left to his fate, without any farther interference on my part, at
all events.
subQuotationList:
['Well,', "that is no very difficult
matter. But to return to this boy. The great point of our agreement is
