speaker: Mr. Losberne
mentionEntitiesList: [[], [['Oliver Twist'], ['The Constable'], ['Oliver Twist'], ['Oliver Twist'], ['Rose Maylie', 'Mr. Losberne', 'Mrs. Maylie'], ['Oliver Twist'], ['Oliver Twist'], ['Oliver Twist'], ['Rose Maylie', 'Mr. Losberne', 'Mrs. Maylie'], ['Oliver Twist'], ['Oliver Twist'], ['Oliver Twist']]]

quoteText: Oh no, aunt!
subQuotationList: ['Oh no, aunt!']
speaker: Rose Maylie

quoteText: Oh yes, aunt! Is is a bargain?
subQuotationList: ['Oh yes, aunt!', 'Is is a bargain?']
speaker: Mr. Losberne

quoteText: He cannot be hardened in vice, It is impossible.
subQuotationList: ['He cannot be hardened in vice,', 'It is impossible.']
speaker: Rose Maylie

quoteText:
Very good, then so much the more reason for
acceding to my proposition.
subQuotationList: ['Very good,', 'then so much the more reason for\nacceding to my proposition.']
speaker: Mr. Losberne

quoteText: Sit still!
subQuotationList: ['Sit still!']
speaker: Mr. Losberne
addressees: ['The Housemaid', 'The Cook', 'Mr. Brittles', 'Mr. Giles', 'The Tinker', 'The Constable']

quoteText:
Thank you, sir, Misses wished some ale to be given
out, sir; and as I felt no ways inclined for my own little room, sir,
and was disposed for company, I am taking mine among 'em here.
subQuotationList: ['Thank you, sir,', "Misses wished some ale to be given\nout, sir; and as I felt no ways inclined for my own little room, sir,\nand was disposed for company, I am taking mine among 'em here."]
speaker: Mr. Giles
addressees: ['The Housemaid', 'Mr. Losberne', 'The Cook', 'Mr. Brittles', 'The Tinker', 'The Constable']

quoteText: How is the patient to-night, sir?
subQuotationList: ['How is the patient to-night, sir?']
speaker: Mr. Giles
addressees: ['The Housemaid', 'Mr. Losberne', 'The Cook', 'Mr. Brittles', 'The Tinker', 'The Constable']

quoteText:
So-so I am afraid you have got yourself into a
scrape there, Mr. Giles.
subQuotationList: ['So-so', 'I am afraid you have got yourself into a\nscrape there, Mr. Giles.']
speaker: Mr. Losberne
addressees: ['The Housemaid', 'The Cook', 'Mr. Brittles', 'Mr. Giles', 'The Tinker', 'The Constable']

quoteText:
I hope you don't mean to say, sir, that
he's going to die. If I thought it, I should never be happy again. I
wouldn't cut a boy off: no, not even Brittles here; not for all the
plate in the county, sir.
subQuotationList:
["I hope you don't mean to say, sir,", "that
he's going to die. If I thought it, I should never be happy again. I
wouldn't cut a boy off: no, not even Brittles here; not for all the
plate in the county, sir."]
speaker: Mr. Giles
addressees: ['The Housemaid', 'Mr. Losberne', 'The Cook', 'Mr. Brittles', 'The Tinker', 'The Constable']

quoteText:
That's not the point, Mr. Giles, are
you a Protestant?
subQuotationList: ["That's not the point,", 'Mr. Giles, are\nyou a Protestant?']
speaker: Mr. Losberne
addressees: ['The Housemaid', 'The Cook', 'Mr. Brittles', 'Mr. Giles', 'The Tinker', 'The Constable']

quoteText: Yes, sir, I hope so,
subQuotationList: ['Yes, sir, I hope so,']
speaker: Mr. Giles
addressees: ['The Housemaid', 'Mr. Losberne', 'The Cook', 'Mr. Brittles', 'The Tinker', 'The Constable']

quoteText: And what are _you_, boy?
subQuotationList: ['And what are _you_, boy?']
speaker: Mr. Losberne
addressees: ['The Housemaid', 'The Cook', 'Mr. Brittles', 'Mr. Giles', 'The Tinker', 'The Constable']

quoteText:
Lord bless me, sir! I'm the
same as Mr. Giles, sir.
subQuotationList: ['Lord bless me, sir!', "I'm the\nsame as Mr. Giles, sir."]
speaker: Mr. Brittles
addressees: ['The Housemaid', 'Mr. Losberne', 'The Cook', 'Mr. Giles', 'The Tinker', 'The Constable']

quoteText:
Then tell me this, both of you, both of you! Are
you going to take upon yourselves to swear, that that boy upstairs is
the boy that was put through the little window last night? Out with it!
Come! We are prepared for you! Pay attention to the reply, constable, will you? Something may come of this before long. It's a simple question of identity, you will observe,
subQuotationList:

you going to take upon yourselves to swear, that that boy upstairs is

Come! We are prepared for you!', 'Pay attention to the reply, constable, will you?', 'Something may come of this before long.', "It's a simple question of identity, you will observe,"]
speaker: Mr. Losberne

quoteText: That's what it is, sir,
subQuotationList: ["That's what it is, sir,"]
speaker: The Constable
addressees: ['The Housemaid', 'Mr. Losberne', 'The Cook', 'Mr. Brittles', 'Mr. Giles', 'The Tinker']

quoteText:
Here's the house broken into, and a couple of men
catch one moment's glimpse of a boy, in the midst of gunpowder smoke,
and in all the distraction of alarm and darkness. Here's a boy comes to
that very same house, next morning, and because he happens to have his
arm tied up, these men lay violent hands upon him by doing which, they
place his life in great danger and swear he is the thief. Now, the
question is, whether these men are justified by the fact; if not, in
what situation do they place themselves?
subQuotationList:
["Here's the house broken into,", "and a couple of men
catch one moment's glimpse of a boy, in the midst of gunpowder smoke,
and in all the distraction of alarm and darkness. Here's a boy comes to

arm tied up, these men lay violent hands upon him by doing which, they
place his life in great danger and swear he is the thief. Now, the
question is, whether these men are justified by the fact; if not, in
what situation do they place themselves?"]
speaker: Mr. Losberne
addressees: ['The Housemaid', 'The Cook', 'Mr. Brittles', 'Mr. Giles', 'The Tinker', 'The Constable']

quoteText:
I ask you again, are you, on your solemn
oaths, able to identify that boy?
subQuotationList: ['I ask you again,', 'are you, on your solemn\noaths, able to identify that boy?']
speaker: Mr. Losberne
addressees: ['The Housemaid', 'The Cook', 'Mr. Brittles', 'Mr. Giles', 'The Tinker', 'The Constable']
mentionEntitiesList: [[['Mr. Brittles', 'Mr. Giles']], [['Mr. Brittles', 'Mr. Giles'], ['Mr. Brittles', 'Mr. Giles'], ['Oliver Twist']]]

quoteText: It's the runners!
subQuotationList: ["It's the runners!"]
speaker: Mr. Brittles
addressees: ['The Housemaid', 'Mr. Losberne', 'The Cook', 'Mr. Giles', 'The Tinker', 'The Constable']

quoteText: The what?
subQuotationList: ['The what?']
speaker: Mr. Losberne
addressees: ['The Housemaid', 'The Cook', 'Mr. Brittles', 'Mr. Giles', 'The Tinker', 'The Constable']

quoteText: The Bow Street officers, sir, me and Mr. Giles sent for 'em this morning.
subQuotationList: ['The Bow Street officers, sir,', "me and Mr. Giles sent for 'em this morning."]
speaker: Mr. Brittles
addressees: ['The Housemaid', 'Mr. Losberne', 'The Cook', 'Mr. Giles', 'The Tinker', 'The Constable']
mentionEntitiesList: [[['Mr. Duff', 'Mr. Blathers'], ['Mr. Losberne']], [['Mr. Giles'], ['Mr. Duff', 'Mr. Blathers']]]

quoteText: What?
subQuotationList: ['What?']
speaker: Mr. Losberne
addressees: ['The Housemaid', 'The Cook', 'Mr. Brittles', 'Mr. Giles', 'The Tinker', 'The Constable']

quoteText:
Yes, I sent a message up by the coachman, and I
only wonder they weren't here before, sir.
subQuotationList: ['Yes,', "I sent a message up by the coachman, and I\nonly wonder they weren't here before, sir."]
speaker: Mr. Brittles
addressees: ['The Housemaid', 'Mr. Losberne', 'The Cook', 'Mr. Giles', 'The Tinker', 'The Constable']

quoteText:
You did, did you? Then confound your slow coaches down here; that's
all,
subQuotationList: ["You did, did you? Then confound your slow coaches down here; that's\nall,"]
speaker: Mr. Losberne
addressees: ['The Housemaid', 'The Cook', 'Mr. Brittles', 'Mr. Giles', 'The Tinker', 'The Constable']

quoteText: Who's that?
subQuotationList: ["Who's that?"]
speaker: Mr. Brittles

quoteText:
Open the door, it's the officers from Bow
Street, as was sent to to-day.
subQuotationList: ['Open the door,', "it's the officers from Bow\nStreet, as was sent to to-day."]
speaker: Mr. Blathers

quoteText:
Just send somebody out to relieve my mate, will you, young man? he's in the gig, a-minding the prad. Have you got a coach
'us here, that you could put it up in, for five or ten minutes?
subQuotationList: ['Just send somebody out to relieve my mate, will you, young man?', "he's in the gig, a-minding the prad. Have you got a coach\n'us here, that you could put it up in, for five or ten minutes?"]
speaker: Mr. Blathers
mentionEntitiesList: [[['Mr. Duff'], ['Mr. Brittles'], ['Mr. Brittles']], [['Mr. Duff'], ['Mr. Brittles'], ['Mr. Brittles']]]

quoteText: Tell your governor that Blathers and Duff is here, will you?
subQuotationList: ['Tell your governor that Blathers and Duff is here, will you?']
speaker: Mr. Blathers

quoteText:
Oh! Good-evening, master. Can I have a word or two with you
in private, if you please?
subQuotationList: ['Oh! Good-evening, master. Can I have a word or two with you\nin private, if you please?']
speaker: Mr. Blathers

quoteText: This is the lady of the house,
subQuotationList: ['This is the lady of the house,']
speaker: Mr. Losberne

quoteText:
Now, with regard to this here robbery, master, What
are the circumstances? I can't say, for certain, till I see the work, of course, but my opinion at once is, I don't mind committing myself to
that extent, that this wasn't done by a yokel; eh, Duff?
subQuotationList: ['Now, with regard to this here robbery, master,', 'What\nare the circumstances?', "I can't say, for certain, till I see the work, of course,", "but my opinion at once is, I don't mind committing myself to\nthat extent, that this wasn't done by a yokel; eh, Duff?"]
speaker: Mr. Blathers

quoteText: Certainly not,
subQuotationList: ['Certainly not,']
speaker: Mr. Duff

quoteText:
And, translating the word yokel for the benefit of the ladies, I
apprehend your meaning to be, that this attempt was not made by a
countryman?
subQuotationList: ['And, translating the word yokel for the benefit of the ladies, I\napprehend your meaning to be, that this attempt was not made by a\ncountryman?']
speaker: Mr. Losberne

quoteText:
That's it, master, This is all about the robbery,
is it?
subQuotationList: ["That's it, master,", 'This is all about the robbery,\nis it?']
speaker: Mr. Blathers

quoteText: All,
speaker: Mr. Losberne

quoteText:
Now, what is this, about this here boy that the servants are a-talking
on?
subQuotationList: ['Now, what is this, about this here boy that the servants are a-talking\non?']
speaker: Mr. Blathers

quoteText:
Nothing at all, One of the frightened servants
chose to take it into his head, that he had something to do with this
attempt to break into the house; but it's nonsense: sheer absurdity.
subQuotationList: ['Nothing at all,', "One of the frightened servants\nchose to take it into his head, that he had something to do with this\nattempt to break into the house; but it's nonsense: sheer absurdity."]
speaker: Mr. Losberne

quoteText: Wery easy disposed of, if it is,
subQuotationList: ['Wery easy disposed of, if it is,']
speaker: Mr. Duff

quoteText:
What he says is quite correct, Who is the boy? What account does he
give of himself? Where did he come from? He didn't drop out of the
clouds, did he, master?
subQuotationList: ['What he says is quite correct,', "Who is the boy? What account does he\ngive of himself? Where did he come from? He didn't drop out of the\nclouds, did he, master?"]
speaker: Mr. Blathers
mentionEntitiesList: [[['Mr. Duff']], [['Oliver Twist'], ['Oliver Twist'], ['Oliver Twist'], ['Oliver Twist'], ['Oliver Twist'], ['Mr. Losberne']]]

quoteText:
Of course not, I know his whole history: but we can talk about that
presently. You would like, first, to see the place where the thieves
made their attempt, I suppose?
subQuotationList: ['Of course not,', 'I know his whole history: but we can talk about that\npresently. You would like, first, to see the place where the thieves\nmade their attempt, I suppose?']
speaker: Mr. Losberne

quoteText:
Certainly, We had better inspect the premises
first, and examine the servants afterwards. That's the usual way of
doing business.
subQuotationList: ['Certainly,', "We had better inspect the premises\nfirst, and examine the servants afterwards. That's the usual way of\ndoing business."]
speaker: Mr. Blathers

quoteText: Upon my word, I hardly know what to do.
subQuotationList: ['Upon my word,', 'I hardly know what to do.']
speaker: Mr. Losberne

quoteText:
Surely, the poor child's story, faithfully repeated to
these men, will be sufficient to exonerate him.
subQuotationList: ['Surely,', "the poor child's story, faithfully repeated to\nthese men, will be sufficient to exonerate him."]
speaker: Rose Maylie

quoteText:
I doubt it, my dear young lady, I
don't think it would exonerate him, either with them, or with legal
functionaries of a higher grade. What is he, after all, they would say?
A runaway. Judged by mere worldly considerations and probabilities, his
story is a very doubtful one.
subQuotationList:
['I doubt it, my dear young lady,', "I
don't think it would exonerate him, either with them, or with legal
functionaries of a higher grade. What is he, after all, they would say?
A runaway. Judged by mere worldly considerations and probabilities, his
story is a very doubtful one."]
speaker: Mr. Losberne
mentionEntitiesList: [[['Rose Maylie']], [['Oliver Twist'], ['Mr. Blathers', 'Mr. Duff'], ['Oliver Twist'], ['Mr. Blathers', 'Mr. Duff'], ['Oliver Twist']]]

quoteText: You believe it, surely?
subQuotationList: ['You believe it, surely?']
speaker: Rose Maylie

quoteText:
_I_ believe it, strange as it is; and perhaps I may be an old fool for
doing so, but I don't think it is exactly the
tale for a practical police-officer, nevertheless.
subQuotationList: ['_I_ believe it, strange as it is; and perhaps I may be an old fool for\ndoing so,', "but I don't think it is exactly the\ntale for a practical police-officer, nevertheless."]
speaker: Mr. Losberne

quoteText: Why not?
subQuotationList: ['Why not?']
speaker: Rose Maylie

quoteText:
Because, my pretty cross-examiner, because,
viewed with their eyes, there are many ugly points about it; he can
only prove the parts that look ill, and none of those that look well.
Confound the fellows, they _will_ have the why and the wherefore, and
will take nothing for granted. On his own showing, you see, he has been
the companion of thieves for some time past; he has been carried to a
police-officer, on a charge of picking a gentleman's pocket; he has
been taken away, forcibly, from that gentleman's house, to a place
which he cannot describe or point out, and of the situation of which he
has not the remotest idea. He is brought down to Chertsey, by men who
seem to have taken a violent fancy to him, whether he will or no; and
is put through a window to rob a house; and then, just at the very
moment when he is going to alarm the inmates, and so do the very thing
that would set him all to rights, there rushes into the way, a
blundering dog of a half-bred butler, and shoots him! As if on purpose
to prevent his doing any good for himself! Don't you see all this?
subQuotationList:
['Because, my pretty cross-examiner,', "because,
viewed with their eyes, there are many ugly points about it; he can

quoteText:
I see it, of course, but still I do not see anything in it, to criminate the
poor child.
subQuotationList: ['I see it, of course,', 'but still I do not see anything in it, to criminate the\npoor child.']
speaker: Rose Maylie

quoteText:
No, of course not! Bless the bright eyes of your
sex! They never see, whether for good or bad, more than one side of any
question; and that is, always, the one which first presents itself to
them.
subQuotationList:
['No,', 'of course not! Bless the bright eyes of your
sex! They never see, whether for good or bad, more than one side of any
question; and that is, always, the one which first presents itself to
them.']
speaker: Mr. Losberne

quoteText:
The more I think of it, the more I see that it will
occasion endless trouble and difficulty if we put these men in
possession of the boy's real story. I am certain it will not be
believed; and even if they can do nothing to him in the end, still the
dragging it forward, and giving publicity to all the doubts that will
be cast upon it, must interfere, materially, with your benevolent plan
of rescuing him from misery.

of rescuing him from misery."]

for these people?

quoteText:
Why, indeed! I would not have had them here,
for the world.
subQuotationList: ['Why, indeed!', 'I would not have had them here,\nfor the world.']
speaker: Mrs. Maylie

quoteText:
All I know is, that we must try and carry it off with a bold
face. The object is a good one, and that must be our excuse. The boy
has strong symptoms of fever upon him, and is in no condition to be
talked to any more; that's one comfort. We must make the best of it;
and if bad be the best, it is no fault of ours. Come in!

Well, master, This

subQuotationList: ['We call it a put-up robbery, ladies,', 'when the servants is in it.']

quoteText: Nobody suspected them, in this case,
subQuotationList: ['Nobody suspected them, in this case,']

quoteText:
Wery likely not, ma'am, but they might have been
in it, for all that.

speaker: Mr. Blathers

quoteText: More likely on that wery account,
subQuotationList: ['More likely on that wery account,']
speaker: Mr. Duff

quoteText: We find it was a town hand, for the style of work is first-rate.
subQuotationList: ['We find it was a town hand,', 'for the style of work is first-rate.']
speaker: Mr. Blathers

quoteText: Wery pretty indeed it is,
subQuotationList: ['Wery pretty indeed it is,']
speaker: Mr. Duff

quoteText:
There was two of 'em in it, and they had a boy
with 'em; that's plain from the size of the window. That's all to be
said at present. We'll see this lad that you've got upstairs at once,
if you please.

with 'em; that's plain from the size of the window. That's all to be
said at present. We'll see this lad that you've got upstairs at once,

Oh! to be sure! You shall have it
immediately, if you will.
subQuotationList: ['Oh! to be sure!', 'You shall have it\nimmediately, if you will.']

quoteText:
Why, thank you, miss! it's dry work, this sort of duty. Anythink that's handy,
miss; don't put yourself out of the way, on our accounts.

speaker: Mr. Blathers

quoteText: What shall it be?
subQuotationList: ['What shall it be?']
speaker: Mr. Losberne

quoteText:
A little drop of spirits, master, if it's all the same, It's a cold ride from London, ma'am; and I always find that
spirits comes home warmer to the feelings.
subQuotationList: ["A little drop of spirits, master, if it's all the same,", "It's a cold ride from London, ma'am; and I always find that\nspirits comes home warmer to the feelings."]
speaker: Mr. Blathers

quoteText:
Ah! I have seen a good many pieces
of business like this, in my time, ladies.
subQuotationList: ['Ah!', 'I have seen a good many pieces\nof business like this, in my time, ladies.']
speaker: Mr. Blathers

quoteText: That crack down in the back lane at Edmonton, Blathers,
subQuotationList: ['That crack down in the back lane at Edmonton, Blathers,']
speaker: Mr. Duff

quoteText: That was something in this way, warn't it? that was done by Conkey Chickweed, that was.
subQuotationList: ["That was something in this way, warn't it?", 'that was done by Conkey Chickweed, that was.']
speaker: Mr. Blathers

quoteText:
You always gave that to him It was the Family Pet, I
tell you. Conkey hadn't any more to do with it than I had.
subQuotationList: ['You always gave that to him', "It was the Family Pet, I\ntell you. Conkey hadn't any more to do with it than I had."]
speaker: Mr. Duff

quoteText:
Get out! I know better. Do you mind that time
when Conkey was robbed of his money, though? What a start that was!
Better than any novel-book _I_ ever see!
subQuotationList: ['Get out!', 'I know better. Do you mind that time\nwhen Conkey was robbed of his money, though? What a start that was!\nBetter than any novel-book _I_ ever see!']
speaker: Mr. Blathers

quoteText: What was that?
subQuotationList: ['What was that?']
speaker: Rose Maylie

quoteText:
It was a robbery, miss, that hardly anybody would have been down
upon, This here Conkey Chickweed
subQuotationList: ['It was a robbery, miss, that hardly anybody would have been down\nupon,', 'This here Conkey Chickweed']
speaker: Mr. Blathers

quoteText: Conkey means Nosey, ma'am,
subQuotationList: ["Conkey means Nosey, ma'am,"]
speaker: Mr. Duff

quoteText: Of course the lady knows that, don't she?
subQuotationList: ["Of course the lady knows that, don't she?"]
speaker: Mr. Blathers

quoteText:
Always interrupting, you are, partner! This here Conkey Chickweed,
miss, kept a public-house over Battlebridge way, and he had a cellar,
where a good many young lords went to see cock-fighting, and
badger-drawing, and that; and a wery intellectual manner the sports was
conducted in, for I've seen 'em off'en. He warn't one of the family, at
that time; and one night he was robbed of three hundred and
twenty-seven guineas in a canvas bag, that was stole out of his bedroom
in the dead of night, by a tall man with a black patch over his eye,
who had concealed himself under the bed, and after committing the
robbery, jumped slap out of window: which was only a story high. He was
wery quick about it. But Conkey was quick, too; for he fired a
blunderbuss arter him, and roused the neighbourhood. They set up a
hue-and-cry, directly, and when they came to look about 'em, found that
Conkey had hit the robber; for there was traces of blood, all the way
to some palings a good distance off; and there they lost 'em. However,
he had made off with the blunt; and, consequently, the name of Mr.
Chickweed, licensed witler, appeared in the Gazette among the other
bankrupts; and all manner of benefits and subscriptions, and I don't
know what all, was got up for the poor man, who was in a wery low state
of mind about his loss, and went up and down the streets, for three or
four days, a pulling his hair off in such a desperate manner that many
people was afraid he might be going to make away with himself. One day
he came up to the office, all in a hurry, and had a private interview
with the magistrate, who, after a deal of talk, rings the bell, and
orders Jem Spyers in (Jem was a active officer), and tells him to go
and assist Mr. Chickweed in apprehending the man as robbed his house. said Chickweed, says Spyers. says the poor man; Spyers no sooner heard this,
than he put some clean linen and a comb, in his pocket, in case he
should have to stop a day or two; and away he goes, and sets himself
down at one of the public-house windows behind the little red curtain,
with his hat on, all ready to bolt out, at a moment's notice. He was
smoking his pipe here, late at night, when all of a sudden Chickweed
roars out, Jem Spyers dashes out; and
there he sees Chickweed, a-tearing down the street full cry. Away goes
Spyers; on goes Chickweed; round turns the people; everybody roars out, and Chickweed himself keeps on shouting, all the time, like
mad. Spyers loses sight of him a minute as he turns a corner; shoots
round; sees a little crowd; dives in; says
Chickweed, It was a remarkable occurrence, but
he warn't to be seen nowhere, so they went back to the public-house.
Next morning, Spyers took his old place, and looked out, from behind
the curtain, for a tall man with a black patch over his eye, till his
own two eyes ached again. At last, he couldn't help shutting 'em, to
ease 'em a minute; and the very moment he did so, he hears Chickweed
a-roaring out, Off he starts once more, with Chickweed
half-way down the street ahead of him; and after twice as long a run as
the yesterday's one, the man's lost again! This was done, once or twice
more, till one-half the neighbours gave out that Mr. Chickweed had been
robbed by the devil, who was playing tricks with him arterwards; and
the other half, that poor Mr. Chickweed had gone mad with grief.

quoteText: What did Jem Spyers say?
subQuotationList: ['What did Jem Spyers say?']
speaker: Mr. Losberne

quoteText: Jem Spyers,
subQuotationList: ['Jem Spyers,']
speaker: Mr. Blathers

quoteText:
for a long time said nothing at
all, and listened to everything without seeming to, which showed he
understood his business. But, one morning, he walked into the bar, and
taking out his snuffbox, says said Chickweed. said Spyers, offering him a pinch of
snuff, So he had; and a
good bit of money he had made by it, too; and nobody would never have
found it out, if he hadn't been so precious anxious to keep up
appearances!

quoteText:
Very curious, indeed, Now, if you please, you
can walk upstairs.
subQuotationList: ['Very curious, indeed,', 'Now, if you please, you\ncan walk upstairs.']
speaker: Mr. Losberne

quoteText: If _you_ please, sir,
subQuotationList: ['If _you_ please, sir,']
speaker: Mr. Blathers

quoteText:
This, this is the lad, who, being accidently wounded by a
spring-gun in some boyish trespass on Mr. What-d' ye-call-him's
grounds, at the back here, comes to the house for assistance this
morning, and is immediately laid hold of and maltreated, by that
ingenious gentleman with the candle in his hand: who has placed his
life in considerable danger, as I can professionally certify.
subQuotationList:
['This,', "this is the lad, who, being accidently wounded by a
spring-gun in some boyish trespass on Mr. What-d' ye-call-him's
grounds, at the back here, comes to the house for assistance this
morning, and is immediately laid hold of and maltreated, by that
ingenious gentleman with the candle in his hand: who has placed his
life in considerable danger, as I can professionally certify."]
speaker: Mr. Losberne

quoteText: You don't mean to deny that, I suppose?
subQuotationList: ["You don't mean to deny that, I suppose?"]
speaker: Mr. Losberne

quoteText:
It was all done for the for the best, sir, I am sure
I thought it was the boy, or I wouldn't have meddled with him. I am not
of an inhuman disposition, sir.
subQuotationList: ['It was all done for the for the best, sir,', "I am sure\nI thought it was the boy, or I wouldn't have meddled with him. I am not\nof an inhuman disposition, sir."]
speaker: Mr. Giles

quoteText: Thought it was what boy?
subQuotationList: ['Thought it was what boy?']
speaker: Mr. Blathers

quoteText:
The housebreaker's boy, sir! They they certainly had
a boy.
subQuotationList: ["The housebreaker's boy, sir!", 'They they certainly had\na boy.']
speaker: Mr. Giles
mentionEntitiesList: [[['Oliver Twist']], [['Bill Sikes', 'Toby Crackit'], ['Bill Sikes', 'Toby Crackit'], ['Oliver Twist']]]

quoteText: Well? Do you think so now?
subQuotationList: ['Well? Do you think so now?']
speaker: Mr. Blathers

quoteText: Think what, now?
subQuotationList: ['Think what, now?']
speaker: Mr. Giles

quoteText: Think it's the same boy, Stupid-head?
subQuotationList: ["Think it's the same boy, Stupid-head?"]
speaker: Mr. Blathers

quoteText: I don't know; I really don't know, I couldn't swear to him.
subQuotationList: ["I don't know; I really don't know,", "I couldn't swear to him."]
speaker: Mr. Giles

quoteText: What do you think?
subQuotationList: ['What do you think?']
speaker: Mr. Blathers

quoteText:
I don't know what to think, I don't think it is
the boy; indeed, I'm almost certain that it isn't. You know it can't
be.
subQuotationList: ["I don't know what to think,", "I don't think it is\nthe boy; indeed, I'm almost certain that it isn't. You know it can't\nbe."]
speaker: Mr. Giles

quoteText: Has this man been a-drinking, sir?
subQuotationList: ['Has this man been a-drinking, sir?']
speaker: Mr. Blathers
referringExpression: inquired Blathers turning to the doctor

quoteText: What a precious muddle-headed chap you are!
subQuotationList: ['What a precious muddle-headed chap you are!']
speaker: Mr. Duff

quoteText:
Poor fellow! you shall have many opportunities of serving us, if you will. We
are going into the country, and my aunt intends that you shall
accompany us. The quiet place, the pure air, and all the pleasure and
beauties of spring, will restore you in a few days. We will employ you
in a hundred ways, when you can bear the trouble.
subQuotationList:
['Poor fellow!', 'you shall have many opportunities of serving us, if you will. We
are going into the country, and my aunt intends that you shall
accompany us. The quiet place, the pure air, and all the pleasure and
beauties of spring, will restore you in a few days. We will employ you
in a hundred ways, when you can bear the trouble.']
speaker: Rose Maylie
mentionEntitiesList: [[], [['Oliver Twist'], ['Rose Maylie', 'Mrs. Maylie'], ['Oliver Twist'], ['Rose Maylie', 'Mrs. Maylie'], ['Mrs. Maylie'], ['Oliver Twist'], ['Rose Maylie', 'Mrs. Maylie'], ['Oliver Twist'], ['Rose Maylie', 'Mrs. Maylie'], ['Oliver Twist'], ['Oliver Twist']]]

quoteText:
The trouble! Oh! dear lady, if I could but work for
you; if I could only give you pleasure by watering your flowers, or
watching your birds, or running up and down the whole day long, to make
you happy; what would I give to do it!
subQuotationList:
['The trouble!', 'Oh! dear lady, if I could but work for
you; if I could only give you pleasure by watering your flowers, or
watching your birds, or running up and down the whole day long, to make
you happy; what would I give to do it!']
speaker: Oliver Twist
mentionEntitiesList: [[], [['Rose Maylie'], ['Rose Maylie'], ['Rose Maylie'], ['Rose Maylie'], ['Rose Maylie'], ['Rose Maylie']]]

quoteText:
You shall give nothing at all, for, as I
told you before, we shall employ you in a hundred ways; and if you only
take half the trouble to please us, that you promise now, you will make
me very happy indeed.
subQuotationList:
['You shall give nothing at all,', 'for, as I
told you before, we shall employ you in a hundred ways; and if you only
take half the trouble to please us, that you promise now, you will make
me very happy indeed.']
speaker: Rose Maylie
mentionEntitiesList: [[['Oliver Twist']], [['Oliver Twist'], ['Rose Maylie', 'Mrs. Maylie'], ['Oliver Twist'], ['Oliver Twist'], ['Rose Maylie', 'Mrs. Maylie'], ['Oliver Twist'], ['Oliver Twist']]]

quoteText: Happy, ma'am! how kind of you to say so!
subQuotationList: ["Happy, ma'am!", 'how kind of you to say so!']
speaker: Oliver Twist

quoteText: You will make me happier than I can tell you,
subQuotationList: ['You will make me happier than I can tell you,']
speaker: Rose Maylie

quoteText:
To think that my dear good aunt should have been the means of rescuing
any one from such sad misery as you have described to us, would be an
unspeakable pleasure to me; but to know that the object of her goodness
and compassion was sincerely grateful and attached, in consequence,
would delight me, more than you can well imagine. Do you understand
me?
subQuotationList:
['To think that my dear good aunt should have been the means of rescuing
any one from such sad misery as you have described to us, would be an
unspeakable pleasure to me; but to know that the object of her goodness
and compassion was sincerely grateful and attached, in consequence,
would delight me, more than you can well imagine. Do you understand
me?']
speaker: Rose Maylie
mentionEntitiesList: [[['Mrs. Maylie'], ['Oliver Twist'], ['Rose Maylie', 'Mrs. Maylie'], ['Oliver Twist'], ['Oliver Twist']]]

quoteText:
Oh yes, ma'am, yes! but I was thinking that
I am ungrateful now.
subQuotationList: ["Oh yes, ma'am, yes!", 'but I was thinking that\nI am ungrateful now.']
speaker: Oliver Twist

quoteText: To whom?
subQuotationList: ['To whom?']
speaker: Rose Maylie

quoteText:
To the kind gentleman, and the dear old nurse, who took so much care
of me before, If they knew how happy I am, they
would be pleased, I am sure.
subQuotationList: ['To the kind gentleman, and the dear old nurse, who took so much care\nof me before,', 'If they knew how happy I am, they\nwould be pleased, I am sure.']
speaker: Oliver Twist
mentionEntitiesList: [[['Mr. Brownlow'], ['Mrs. Bedwin']], [['Mr. Brownlow', 'Mrs. Bedwin'], ['Mr. Brownlow', 'Mrs. Bedwin']]]

quoteText:
I am sure they would, and Mr.
Losberne has already been kind enough to promise that when you are well
enough to bear the journey, he will carry you to see them.
subQuotationList: ['I am sure they would,', 'and Mr.\nLosberne has already been kind enough to promise that when you are well\nenough to bear the journey, he will carry you to see them.']
speaker: Rose Maylie
mentionEntitiesList: [[['Mr. Brownlow', 'Mrs. Bedwin']], [['Mr. Losberne'], ['Oliver Twist'], ['Oliver Twist'], ['Mr. Brownlow', 'Mrs. Bedwin']]]

quoteText:
Has he, ma'am? I
don't know what I shall do for joy when I see their kind faces once
again!
subQuotationList: ["Has he, ma'am?", "I\ndon't know what I shall do for joy when I see their kind faces once\nagain!"]
speaker: Oliver Twist

quoteText: What's the matter with the boy? Do you see anything hear anything feel anything eh?
subQuotationList: ["What's the matter with the boy?", 'Do you see anything hear anything feel anything eh?']
speaker: Mr. Losberne

quoteText:
That, sir, That
house!
subQuotationList: ['That, sir,', 'That\nhouse!']
speaker: Oliver Twist

quoteText: Yes; well, what of it? Stop coachman. Pull up here, What of the house, my man; eh?
subQuotationList: ['Yes; well, what of it? Stop coachman. Pull up here,', 'What of the house, my man; eh?']
speaker: Mr. Losberne

quoteText: The thieves the house they took me to!
subQuotationList: ['The thieves the house they took me to!']
speaker: Oliver Twist

quoteText: The devil it is! Hallo, there! let me out!
subQuotationList: ['The devil it is!', 'Hallo, there! let me out!']
speaker: Mr. Losberne

quoteText: Halloa? What's the matter here?
subQuotationList: ['Halloa?', "What's the matter here?"]
speaker: The Hump-backed Man
referringExpression: said a little ugly humpbacked man

quoteText: Matter! A good deal. Robbery is the matter.
subQuotationList: ['Matter!', 'A good deal. Robbery is the matter.']
speaker: Mr. Losberne

quoteText: There'll be Murder the matter, too, if you don't take your hands off. Do you hear me?
subQuotationList: ["There'll be Murder the matter, too,", "if you don't take your hands off. Do you hear me?"]
speaker: The Hump-backed Man

quoteText:
I hear you, Where's confound the fellow, what's his rascally name Sikes; that's
it. Where's Sikes, you thief?
subQuotationList: ['I hear you,', "Where's confound the fellow, what's his rascally name Sikes; that's\nit. Where's Sikes, you thief?"]
speaker: Mr. Losberne
mentionEntitiesList: [[['The Hump-backed Man']], [['Bill Sikes'], ['Bill Sikes'], ['Bill Sikes'], ['The Hump-backed Man']]]

quoteText:
Now! what do
you mean by coming into my house, in this violent way? Do you want to
rob me, or to murder me? Which is it?
subQuotationList: ['Now!', 'what do\nyou mean by coming into my house, in this violent way? Do you want to\nrob me, or to murder me? Which is it?']
speaker: The Hump-backed Man

quoteText:
Did you ever know a man come out to do either, in a chariot and pair,
you ridiculous old vampire?
subQuotationList: ['Did you ever know a man come out to do either, in a chariot and pair,\nyou ridiculous old vampire?']
speaker: Mr. Losberne

quoteText:
What do you want, then? Will you take
yourself off, before I do you a mischief? Curse you!
subQuotationList: ['What do you want, then?', 'Will you take\nyourself off, before I do you a mischief? Curse you!']
speaker: The Hump-backed Man

quoteText: As soon as I think proper, I shall find you out, some day, my friend.
subQuotationList: ['As soon as I think proper,', 'I shall find you out, some day, my friend.']
speaker: Mr. Losberne

quoteText:
Will you? If you ever want me, I'm
here. I haven't lived here mad and all alone, for five-and-twenty
years, to be scared by you. You shall pay for this; you shall pay for
this.
subQuotationList:
['Will you?', "If you ever want me, I'm
here. I haven't lived here mad and all alone, for five-and-twenty
years, to be scared by you. You shall pay for this; you shall pay for
this."]
speaker: The Hump-backed Man

quoteText: Stupid enough, this,
subQuotationList: ['Stupid enough, this,']
speaker: Mr. Losberne

quoteText:
the boy must
have made a mistake. Here! Put that in your pocket, and shut yourself
up again.
subQuotationList: ['the boy must\nhave made a mistake. Here! Put that in your pocket, and shut yourself\nup again.']
speaker: Mr. Losberne

quoteText:
I am an ass! Did you know
that before, Oliver?
subQuotationList: ['I am an ass!', 'Did you know\nthat before, Oliver?']
speaker: Mr. Losberne

quoteText: No, sir.
subQuotationList: ['No, sir.']
speaker: Oliver Twist

quoteText: Then don't forget it another time.
subQuotationList: ["Then don't forget it another time."]
speaker: Mr. Losberne

quoteText:
An ass, Even if it had been the right place, and the right fellows
had been there, what could I have done, single-handed? And if I had had
assistance, I see no good that I should have done, except leading to my
own exposure, and an unavoidable statement of the manner in which I
have hushed up this business. That would have served me right, though.
I am always involving myself in some scrape or other, by acting on
impulse. It might have done me good.
subQuotationList:
['An ass,', 'Even if it had been the right place, and the right fellows
had been there, what could I have done, single-handed? And if I had had
assistance, I see no good that I should have done, except leading to my
own exposure, and an unavoidable statement of the manner in which I
have hushed up this business. That would have served me right, though.
I am always involving myself in some scrape or other, by acting on

speaker: Mr. Losberne

quoteText: Now, my boy, which house is it?
subQuotationList: ['Now, my boy, which house is it?']
speaker: Mr. Losberne

quoteText:
That! That! The
white house. Oh! make haste! Pray make haste! I feel as if I should
die: it makes me tremble so.
subQuotationList: ['That! That!', 'The\nwhite house. Oh! make haste! Pray make haste! I feel as if I should\ndie: it makes me tremble so.']
speaker: Oliver Twist

quoteText:
Come, come! You
will see them directly, and they will be overjoyed to find you safe and
well.
subQuotationList: ['Come, come!', 'You\nwill see them directly, and they will be overjoyed to find you safe and\nwell.']
speaker: Mr. Losberne
mentionEntitiesList: [[], [['Oliver Twist'], ['Mr. Brownlow', 'Mrs. Bedwin'], ['Mr. Brownlow', 'Mrs. Bedwin'], ['Oliver Twist']]]

quoteText:
Oh! I hope so! They were so good to me; so very, very
good to me.
subQuotationList: ['Oh! I hope so!', 'They were so good to me; so very, very\ngood to me.']
speaker: Oliver Twist

quoteText: Knock at the next door,
subQuotationList: ['Knock at the next door,']
speaker: Mr. Losberne

quoteText:
What has become of Mr. Brownlow, who used to live in the
adjoining house, do you know?
subQuotationList: ['What has become of Mr. Brownlow, who used to live in the\nadjoining house, do you know?']
speaker: Mr. Losberne

quoteText: Has his housekeeper gone too?
subQuotationList: ['Has his housekeeper gone too?']
speaker: Mr. Losberne

quoteText:
Yes, sir The old gentleman, the housekeeper,
and a gentleman who was a friend of Mr. Brownlow's, all went together.
subQuotationList: ['Yes, sir', "The old gentleman, the housekeeper,\nand a gentleman who was a friend of Mr. Brownlow's, all went together."]
speaker: The Neighbours' Servant
mentionTextsList: [[], ['The old gentleman', 'the housekeeper', "a gentleman who was a friend of Mr. Brownlow's"]]

quoteText:
Then turn towards home again, and
don't stop to bait the horses, till you get out of this confounded
London!
subQuotationList: ['Then turn towards home again,', "and\ndon't stop to bait the horses, till you get out of this confounded\nLondon!"]
speaker: Mr. Losberne

quoteText:
The book-stall keeper, sir? I know the way there. See
him, pray, sir! Do see him!
subQuotationList: ['The book-stall keeper, sir?', 'I know the way there. See\nhim, pray, sir! Do see him!']
speaker: Oliver Twist
mentionEntitiesList: [[['The Book-stall Keeper'], ['Mr. Losberne']], [['The Book-stall Keeper'], ['Mr. Losberne'], ['The Book-stall Keeper']]]

quoteText:
My poor boy, this is disappointment enough for one day, Quite enough for both of us. If we go to the book-stall
keeper's, we shall certainly find that he is dead, or has set his house
on fire, or run away. No; home again straight!
subQuotationList: ['My poor boy, this is disappointment enough for one day,', "Quite enough for both of us. If we go to the book-stall\nkeeper's, we shall certainly find that he is dead, or has set his house\non fire, or run away. No; home again straight!"]
speaker: Mr. Losberne
mentionEntitiesList: [[['Oliver Twist']], [['Oliver Twist', 'Mr. Losberne'], ['Oliver Twist', 'Mr. Losberne'], ['The Book-stall Keeper'], ['Oliver Twist', 'Mr. Losberne'], ['The Book-stall Keeper'], ['The Book-stall Keeper']]]

quoteText: Rose, my dear!
subQuotationList: ['Rose, my dear!']
speaker: Mrs. Maylie

quoteText: Rose, my love! What is this? In tears! My dear child, what distresses you?
subQuotationList: ['Rose, my love!', 'What is this? In tears! My dear child, what distresses you?']
speaker: Mrs. Maylie

quoteText:
Nothing, aunt; nothing, I don't know what it
is; I can't describe it; but I feel
subQuotationList: ['Nothing, aunt; nothing,', "I don't know what it\nis; I can't describe it; but I feel"]
speaker: Rose Maylie

quoteText: Not ill, my love?
subQuotationList: ['Not ill, my love?']
speaker: Mrs. Maylie

quoteText:
No, no! Oh, not ill! I shall be better
presently. Close the window, pray!
subQuotationList: ['No, no! Oh, not ill!', 'I shall be better\npresently. Close the window, pray!']
speaker: Rose Maylie

quoteText:
My child! I never
saw you so before.
subQuotationList: ['My child!', 'I never\nsaw you so before.']
speaker: Mrs. Maylie

quoteText:
I would not alarm you if I could avoid it, but indeed
I have tried very hard, and cannot help this. I fear I _am_ ill, aunt.
subQuotationList: ['I would not alarm you if I could avoid it,', 'but indeed\nI have tried very hard, and cannot help this. I fear I _am_ ill, aunt.']
speaker: Rose Maylie

quoteText:
I hope, that nothing is the
matter? She don't look well to-night, but
subQuotationList: ['I hope,', "that nothing is the\nmatter? She don't look well to-night, but"]
speaker: Oliver Twist

quoteText:
I hope not, Oliver. I have been very happy with her for some years:
too happy, perhaps. It may be time that I should meet with some
misfortune; but I hope it is not this.
subQuotationList: ['I hope not, Oliver. I have been very happy with her for some years:\ntoo happy, perhaps. It may be time that I should meet with some\nmisfortune; but I hope it is not this.']
speaker: Mrs. Maylie

quoteText: What?
subQuotationList: ['What?']
speaker: Oliver Twist

quoteText:
The heavy blow, of losing the dear girl who has
so long been my comfort and happiness.
subQuotationList: ['The heavy blow,', 'of losing the dear girl who has\nso long been my comfort and happiness.']
speaker: Mrs. Maylie
mentionTextsList: [[], ['the dear girl who has\nso long been my comfort and happiness']]

quoteText: Oh! God forbid!
subQuotationList: ['Oh! God forbid!']
speaker: Oliver Twist

quoteText: Amen to that, my child!
subQuotationList: ['Amen to that, my child!']
speaker: Mrs. Maylie

quoteText:
Surely there is no danger of anything so dreadful? Two
hours ago, she was quite well.
subQuotationList: ['Surely there is no danger of anything so dreadful?', 'Two\nhours ago, she was quite well.']
speaker: Oliver Twist

quoteText:
She is very ill now, and will be worse, I am
sure. My dear, dear Rose! Oh, what shall I do without her!
subQuotationList: ['She is very ill now,', 'and will be worse, I am\nsure. My dear, dear Rose! Oh, what shall I do without her!']
speaker: Mrs. Maylie

quoteText:
And consider, ma'am, Oh! consider how
young and good she is, and what pleasure and comfort she gives to all
about her. I am sure certain quite certain that, for your sake, who are
so good yourself; and for her own; and for the sake of all she makes so
happy; she will not die. Heaven will never let her die so young.
subQuotationList:
["And consider, ma'am,", 'Oh! consider how
young and good she is, and what pleasure and comfort she gives to all
about her. I am sure certain quite certain that, for your sake, who are
so good yourself; and for her own; and for the sake of all she makes so
happy; she will not die. Heaven will never let her die so young.']
speaker: Oliver Twist
mentionEntitiesList: [[['Mrs. Maylie']], [['Rose Maylie'], ['Rose Maylie'], ['Rose Maylie'], ['Mrs. Maylie'], ['Rose Maylie'], ['Rose Maylie'], ['Rose Maylie'], ['Rose Maylie']]]

quoteText:
Hush! You think
like a child, poor boy. But you teach me my duty, notwithstanding. I
had forgotten it for a moment, Oliver, but I hope I may be pardoned,
for I am old, and have seen enough of illness and death to know the
agony of separation from the objects of our love. I have seen enough,
too, to know that it is not always the youngest and best who are spared
to those that love them; but this should give us comfort in our sorrow;
for Heaven is just; and such things teach us, impressively, that there
is a brighter world than this; and that the passage to it is speedy.
God's will be done! I love her; and He knows how well! We must be active, Oliver, and not give way to useless grief, this letter must be sent, with all possible expedition, to
Mr. Losberne. It must be carried to the market-town: which is not more
than four miles off, by the footpath across the field: and thence
dispatched, by an express on horseback, straight to Chertsey. The
people at the inn will undertake to do this: and I can trust to you to
see it done, I know. Here is another letter, but
whether to send it now, or wait until I see how Rose goes on, I
scarcely know. I would not forward it, unless I feared the worst.
subQuotationList:
['Hush!', "You think
like a child, poor boy. But you teach me my duty, notwithstanding. I

for I am old, and have seen enough of illness and death to know the

to those that love them; but this should give us comfort in our sorrow;
for Heaven is just; and such things teach us, impressively, that there
is a brighter world than this; and that the passage to it is speedy.
God's will be done! I love her; and He knows how well!", 'We must be active, Oliver, and not give way to useless grief,', 'this letter must be sent, with all possible expedition, to
Mr. Losberne. It must be carried to the market-town: which is not more
than four miles off, by the footpath across the field: and thence
dispatched, by an express on horseback, straight to Chertsey. The
people at the inn will undertake to do this: and I can trust to you to
see it done, I know.', 'Here is another letter,', 'but
whether to send it now, or wait until I see how Rose goes on, I
scarcely know. I would not forward it, unless I feared the worst.']
speaker: Mrs. Maylie
mentionEntitiesList: [[], [['Rose Maylie']], [['Oliver Twist', 'Mrs. Maylie'], ['Oliver Twist']], [['Mr. Losberne'], ['Oliver Twist']], [], [['Rose Maylie']]]

quoteText: Is it for Chertsey, too, ma'am?
subQuotationList: ["Is it for Chertsey, too, ma'am?"]
speaker: Oliver Twist

quoteText: No,
speaker: Mrs. Maylie

quoteText: Shall it go, ma'am?
subQuotationList: ["Shall it go, ma'am?"]
speaker: Oliver Twist

quoteText:
I think not, I will wait until
to-morrow.
subQuotationList: ['I think not,', 'I will wait until\nto-morrow.']
speaker: Mrs. Maylie

quoteText: Hah! What the devil's this?
subQuotationList: ['Hah!', "What the devil's this?"]
speaker: Monks

quoteText:
I beg your pardon, sir, I was in a great hurry to get
home, and didn't see you were coming.
subQuotationList: ['I beg your pardon, sir,', "I was in a great hurry to get\nhome, and didn't see you were coming."]
speaker: Oliver Twist

quoteText:
Death! Who would have thought it! Grind him to ashes! He'd start
up from a stone coffin, to come in my way!
subQuotationList: ['Death!', "Who would have thought it! Grind him to ashes! He'd start\nup from a stone coffin, to come in my way!"]
speaker: Monks

quoteText: I am sorry, I hope I have not hurt you!
subQuotationList: ['I am sorry,', 'I hope I have not hurt you!']
speaker: Oliver Twist

quoteText:
Rot you! if I had only had the courage to say the word, I might
have been free of you in a night. Curses on your head, and black death
on your heart, you imp! What are you doing here?
subQuotationList: ['Rot you!', 'if I had only had the courage to say the word, I might\nhave been free of you in a night. Curses on your head, and black death\non your heart, you imp! What are you doing here?']
speaker: Monks
mentionEntitiesList: [[['Oliver Twist']], [['Oliver Twist'], ['Oliver Twist'], ['Oliver Twist'], ['Oliver Twist'], ['Oliver Twist']]]

quoteText:
In fact, it would be little short of
a miracle, if she recovered.
subQuotationList: ['In fact,', 'it would be little short of\na miracle, if she recovered.']
speaker: The Medical Practitioner

quoteText:
It is hard, so young; so much
beloved; but there is very little hope.
subQuotationList: ['It is hard,', 'so young; so much\nbeloved; but there is very little hope.']
speaker: Mr. Losberne

quoteText:
What of Rose? Tell me at once! I can bear it;
anything but suspense! Oh, tell me! in the name of Heaven!
subQuotationList: ['What of Rose?', 'Tell me at once! I can bear it;\nanything but suspense! Oh, tell me! in the name of Heaven!']
speaker: Mrs. Maylie

quoteText:
You must compose yourself, Be calm,
my dear ma'am, pray.
subQuotationList: ['You must compose yourself,', "Be calm,\nmy dear ma'am, pray."]
speaker: Mr. Losberne

quoteText: Let me go, in God's name! My dear child! She is dead! She is dying!
subQuotationList: ["Let me go, in God's name! My dear child! She is dead! She is dying!"]
speaker: Mrs. Maylie

quoteText:
No! As He is good and merciful, she
will live to bless us all, for years to come.
subQuotationList: ['No!', 'As He is good and merciful, she\nwill live to bless us all, for years to come.']
speaker: Mr. Losberne

quoteText:
Here! Oliver, what's the news? Miss Rose! Master
O-li-ver!
subQuotationList: ['Here!', "Oliver, what's the news? Miss Rose! Master\nO-li-ver!"]
speaker: Mr. Giles

quoteText: Is it you, Giles?
subQuotationList: ['Is it you, Giles?']
speaker: Oliver Twist

quoteText: In a word! Better or worse?
subQuotationList: ['In a word!', 'Better or worse?']
speaker: Harry Maylie

quoteText: Better much better!
subQuotationList: ['Better much better!']
speaker: Oliver Twist

quoteText: Thank Heaven! You are sure?
subQuotationList: ['Thank Heaven!', 'You are sure?']
speaker: Harry Maylie

quoteText:
Quite, sir, The change took place only a few hours
ago; and Mr. Losberne says, that all danger is at an end.
subQuotationList: ['Quite, sir,', 'The change took place only a few hours\nago; and Mr. Losberne says, that all danger is at an end.']
speaker: Oliver Twist

quoteText:
You are quite certain? There is no possibility of any mistake on your
part, my boy, is there? Do not deceive me, by awakening hopes that are not to be fulfilled.
subQuotationList: ['You are quite certain? There is no possibility of any mistake on your\npart, my boy, is there?', 'Do not deceive me, by awakening hopes that are not to be fulfilled.']
speaker: Harry Maylie

quoteText:
I would not for the world, sir, Indeed you may
believe me. Mr. Losberne's words were, that she would live to bless us
all for many years to come. I heard him say so.
subQuotationList: ['I would not for the world, sir,', "Indeed you may\nbelieve me. Mr. Losberne's words were, that she would live to bless us\nall for many years to come. I heard him say so."]
speaker: Oliver Twist

quoteText:
I think you had better go on to my mother's in the chaise, Giles, I would rather walk slowly on, so as to gain a little time
before I see her. You can say I am coming.
subQuotationList: ["I think you had better go on to my mother's in the chaise, Giles,", 'I would rather walk slowly on, so as to gain a little time\nbefore I see her. You can say I am coming.']
speaker: Harry Maylie

quoteText:
I beg your pardon, Mr. Harry, but if you would leave
the postboy to say that, I should be very much obliged to you. It
wouldn't be proper for the maids to see me in this state, sir; I should
never have any more authority with them if they did.
subQuotationList:
['I beg your pardon, Mr. Harry,', "but if you would leave
the postboy to say that, I should be very much obliged to you. It
wouldn't be proper for the maids to see me in this state, sir; I should
never have any more authority with them if they did."]
speaker: Mr. Giles
mentionEntitiesList: [[['Harry Maylie'], ['Harry Maylie']], [['Harry Maylie'], ['Harry Maylie'], ['Harry Maylie'], ['The Cook', 'The Housemaid'], ['The Cook', 'The Housemaid']]]

quoteText:
Well, you can do as you like. Let
him go on with the luggage, if you wish it, and do you follow with us.
Only first exchange that nightcap for some more appropriate covering,
or we shall be taken for madmen.
subQuotationList:
['Well,', 'you can do as you like. Let
him go on with the luggage, if you wish it, and do you follow with us.
Only first exchange that nightcap for some more appropriate covering,
or we shall be taken for madmen.']
speaker: Harry Maylie
mentionEntitiesList: [[], [['Mr. Giles'], ['Mr. Giles'], ['Mr. Giles'], ['Mr. Giles'], ['Harry Maylie'], ['Harry Maylie', 'Mr. Giles']]]

quoteText: Mother! why did you not write before?
subQuotationList: ['Mother!', 'why did you not write before?']
speaker: Harry Maylie

quoteText:
I did, but, on reflection, I determined to keep
back the letter until I had heard Mr. Losberne's opinion.
subQuotationList: ['I did,', "but, on reflection, I determined to keep\nback the letter until I had heard Mr. Losberne's opinion."]
speaker: Mrs. Maylie

quoteText:
But why, why run the chance of that occurring
which so nearly happened? If Rose had I cannot utter that word now if
this illness had terminated differently, how could you ever have
forgiven yourself! How could I ever have know happiness again!
subQuotationList:
['But why,', 'why run the chance of that occurring
which so nearly happened? If Rose had I cannot utter that word now if
this illness had terminated differently, how could you ever have
forgiven yourself! How could I ever have know happiness again!']
speaker: Harry Maylie

quoteText:
If that _had_ been the case, Harry, I fear your
happiness would have been effectually blighted, and that your arrival
here, a day sooner or a day later, would have been of very, very little
import.
subQuotationList:
['If that _had_ been the case, Harry,', 'I fear your
happiness would have been effectually blighted, and that your arrival
here, a day sooner or a day later, would have been of very, very little
import.']
speaker: Mrs. Maylie

quoteText:
And who can wonder if it be so, mother? or
why should I say, _if_? It is it is you know it, mother you must know
it!
subQuotationList: ['And who can wonder if it be so, mother?', 'or\nwhy should I say, _if_? It is it is you know it, mother you must know\nit!']
speaker: Harry Maylie

quoteText:
I know that she deserves the best and purest love the heart of man can
offer, I know that the devotion and affection of
her nature require no ordinary return, but one that shall be deep and
lasting. If I did not feel this, and know, besides, that a changed
behaviour in one she loved would break her heart, I should not feel my
task so difficult of performance, or have to encounter so many
struggles in my own bosom, when I take what seems to me to be the
strict line of duty.
subQuotationList:
['I know that she deserves the best and purest love the heart of man can
offer,', 'I know that the devotion and affection of
her nature require no ordinary return, but one that shall be deep and
lasting. If I did not feel this, and know, besides, that a changed
behaviour in one she loved would break her heart, I should not feel my
task so difficult of performance, or have to encounter so many
struggles in my own bosom, when I take what seems to me to be the
strict line of duty.']
speaker: Mrs. Maylie

quoteText:
This is unkind, mother, Do you still suppose that I am a
boy ignorant of my own mind, and mistaking the impulses of my own
soul?
subQuotationList: ['This is unkind, mother,', 'Do you still suppose that I am a\nboy ignorant of my own mind, and mistaking the impulses of my own\nsoul?']
speaker: Harry Maylie

quoteText:
I think, my dear son, that youth has many generous impulses which do not last; and
that among them are some, which, being gratified, become only the more
fleeting. Above all, I think that if an enthusiastic, ardent, and ambitious man marry a
wife on whose name there is a stain, which, though it originate in no
fault of hers, may be visited by cold and sordid people upon her, and
upon his children also: and, in exact proportion to his success in the
world, be cast in his teeth, and made the subject of sneers against
him: he may, no matter how generous and good his nature, one day repent
of the connection he formed in early life. And she may have the pain of
knowing that he does so.
subQuotationList:
['I think, my dear son,', 'that youth has many generous impulses which do not last; and
that among them are some, which, being gratified, become only the more
fleeting. Above all, I think', 'that if an enthusiastic, ardent, and ambitious man marry a
wife on whose name there is a stain, which, though it originate in no
fault of hers, may be visited by cold and sordid people upon her, and
upon his children also: and, in exact proportion to his success in the
world, be cast in his teeth, and made the subject of sneers against
him: he may, no matter how generous and good his nature, one day repent
of the connection he formed in early life. And she may have the pain of
knowing that he does so.']
speaker: Mrs. Maylie

quoteText:
Mother, he would be a selfish
brute, unworthy alike of the name of man and of the woman you describe,
who acted thus.
subQuotationList: ['Mother,', 'he would be a selfish\nbrute, unworthy alike of the name of man and of the woman you describe,\nwho acted thus.']
speaker: Harry Maylie

quoteText: You think so now, Harry,
subQuotationList: ['You think so now, Harry,']
speaker: Mrs. Maylie

quoteText:
And ever will! The mental agony I have suffered,
during the last two days, wrings from me the avowal to you of a passion
which, as you well know, is not one of yesterday, nor one I have
lightly formed. On Rose, sweet, gentle girl! my heart is set, as firmly
as ever heart of man was set on woman. I have no thought, no view, no
hope in life, beyond her; and if you oppose me in this great stake, you
take my peace and happiness in your hands, and cast them to the wind.
Mother, think better of this, and of me, and do not disregard the
happiness of which you seem to think so little.
subQuotationList:
['And ever will!', 'The mental agony I have suffered,
during the last two days, wrings from me the avowal to you of a passion
which, as you well know, is not one of yesterday, nor one I have
lightly formed. On Rose, sweet, gentle girl! my heart is set, as firmly
as ever heart of man was set on woman. I have no thought, no view, no
hope in life, beyond her; and if you oppose me in this great stake, you
take my peace and happiness in your hands, and cast them to the wind.
Mother, think better of this, and of me, and do not disregard the
happiness of which you seem to think so little.']
speaker: Harry Maylie
mentionEntitiesList: [[], [['Mrs. Maylie'], ['Mrs. Maylie'], ['Rose Maylie'], ['Mrs. Maylie'], ['Mrs. Maylie'], ['Mrs. Maylie'], ['Mrs. Maylie']]]

quoteText:
Harry, it is because I think so much of warm and
sensitive hearts, that I would spare them from being wounded. But we
have said enough, and more than enough, on this matter, just now.
subQuotationList: ['Harry,', 'it is because I think so much of warm and\nsensitive hearts, that I would spare them from being wounded. But we\nhave said enough, and more than enough, on this matter, just now.']
speaker: Mrs. Maylie

quoteText:
Let it rest with Rose, then, You will not press
these overstrained opinions of yours, so far, as to throw any obstacle
in my way?
subQuotationList: ['Let it rest with Rose, then,', 'You will not press\nthese overstrained opinions of yours, so far, as to throw any obstacle\nin my way?']
speaker: Harry Maylie

quoteText: I will not, but I would have you consider
subQuotationList: ['I will not,', 'but I would have you consider']
speaker: Mrs. Maylie

quoteText:
I _have_ considered! Mother, I have
considered, years and years. I have considered, ever since I have been
capable of serious reflection. My feelings remain unchanged, as they
ever will; and why should I suffer the pain of a delay in giving them
vent, which can be productive of no earthly good? No! Before I leave
this place, Rose shall hear me.
subQuotationList:
['I _have_ considered!', 'Mother, I have
considered, years and years. I have considered, ever since I have been
capable of serious reflection. My feelings remain unchanged, as they
ever will; and why should I suffer the pain of a delay in giving them
vent, which can be productive of no earthly good? No! Before I leave
this place, Rose shall hear me.']
speaker: Harry Maylie

quoteText: She shall,
subQuotationList: ['She shall,']
speaker: Mrs. Maylie

quoteText:
There is something in your manner, which would almost imply that she
will hear me coldly, mother,
subQuotationList: ['There is something in your manner, which would almost imply that she\nwill hear me coldly, mother,']
speaker: Harry Maylie

quoteText: Not coldly, far from it.
subQuotationList: ['Not coldly,', 'far from it.']
speaker: Mrs. Maylie

quoteText: How then? She has formed no other attachment?
subQuotationList: ['How then?', 'She has formed no other attachment?']
speaker: Harry Maylie

quoteText:
No, indeed, you have, or I mistake, too strong a
hold on her affections already. What I would say, is this. Before you
stake your all on this chance; before you suffer yourself to be carried
to the highest point of hope; reflect for a few moments, my dear child,
on Rose's history, and consider what effect the knowledge of her
doubtful birth may have on her decision: devoted as she is to us, with
all the intensity of her noble mind, and with that perfect sacrifice of
self which, in all matters, great or trifling, has always been her
characteristic.
subQuotationList:
['No, indeed,', 'you have, or I mistake, too strong a
hold on her affections already. What I would say,', "is this. Before you
stake your all on this chance; before you suffer yourself to be carried

characteristic."]
speaker: Mrs. Maylie

quoteText: What do you mean?
subQuotationList: ['What do you mean?']
speaker: Harry Maylie

quoteText:
That I leave you to discover, I must go back to
her. God bless you!
subQuotationList: ['That I leave you to discover,', 'I must go back to\nher. God bless you!']
speaker: Mrs. Maylie

quoteText: I shall see you again to-night?
subQuotationList: ['I shall see you again to-night?']
speaker: Harry Maylie

quoteText: By and by, when I leave Rose.
subQuotationList: ['By and by,', 'when I leave Rose.']
speaker: Mrs. Maylie

quoteText: You will tell her I am here?
subQuotationList: ['You will tell her I am here?']
speaker: Harry Maylie

quoteText: Of course,
subQuotationList: ['Of course,']
speaker: Mrs. Maylie

quoteText:
And say how anxious I have been, and how much I have suffered, and how
I long to see her. You will not refuse to do this, mother?
subQuotationList: ['And say how anxious I have been, and how much I have suffered, and how\nI long to see her. You will not refuse to do this, mother?']
speaker: Harry Maylie

quoteText: No, I will tell her all.
subQuotationList: ['No,', 'I will tell her all.']
speaker: Mrs. Maylie

quoteText: Have you shot anything particular, lately, Giles?
subQuotationList: ['Have you shot anything particular, lately, Giles?']
speaker: Mr. Losberne

quoteText: Nothing particular, sir,
subQuotationList: ['Nothing particular, sir,']
speaker: Mr. Giles

quoteText: Nor catching any thieves, nor identifying any house-breakers?
subQuotationList: ['Nor catching any thieves, nor identifying any house-breakers?']
speaker: Mr. Losberne

quoteText: None at all, sir,
subQuotationList: ['None at all, sir,']
speaker: Mr. Giles

quoteText:
Well, I am sorry to hear it, because you do that
sort of thing admirably. Pray, how is Brittles?
subQuotationList: ['Well,', 'I am sorry to hear it, because you do that\nsort of thing admirably. Pray, how is Brittles?']
speaker: Mr. Losberne

quoteText: The boy is very well, sir, and sends his respectful duty, sir.
subQuotationList: ['The boy is very well, sir,', 'and sends his respectful duty, sir.']
speaker: Mr. Giles

quoteText:
That's well, Seeing you here, reminds me, Mr.
Giles, that on the day before that on which I was called away so
hurriedly, I executed, at the request of your good mistress, a small
commission in your favour. Just step into this corner a moment, will
you?
subQuotationList:
["That's well,", 'Seeing you here, reminds me, Mr.
Giles, that on the day before that on which I was called away so
hurriedly, I executed, at the request of your good mistress, a small

speaker: Mr. Losberne

quoteText:
Hush, my dear! it is he, sure
enough. Come away.
subQuotationList: ['Hush, my dear!', 'it is he, sure\nenough. Come away.']
speaker: Fagin

quoteText:
He! could I mistake him, think you?
If a crowd of ghosts were to put themselves into his exact shape, and
he stood amongst them, there is something that would tell me how to
point him out. If you buried him fifty feet deep, and took me across
his grave, I fancy I should know, if there wasn't a mark above it, that
he lay buried there?

subQuotationList: ['What direction did he take?']

quoteText:
That, I
missed them in an instant.

quoteText:
Then, they are in the ditch! Follow! And keep as near
me, as you can.

quoteText: It must have been a dream, Oliver,
subQuotationList: ['It must have been a dream, Oliver,']
speaker: Harry Maylie

quoteText:
Oh no, indeed, sir, I saw him too plainly
for that. I saw them both, as plainly as I see you now.
subQuotationList: ['Oh no, indeed, sir,', 'I saw him too plainly\nfor that. I saw them both, as plainly as I see you now.']
speaker: Oliver Twist

quoteText: Who was the other?
subQuotationList: ['Who was the other?']
speaker: _group

quoteText:
The very same man I told you of, who came so suddenly upon me at the
inn, We had our eyes fixed full upon each other; and I
could swear to him.
subQuotationList: ['The very same man I told you of, who came so suddenly upon me at the\ninn,', 'We had our eyes fixed full upon each other; and I\ncould swear to him.']
speaker: Oliver Twist

quoteText: They took this way? are you sure?
subQuotationList: ['They took this way?', 'are you sure?']
speaker: Harry Maylie

quoteText:
As I am that the men were at the window, The tall man leaped over, just there; and the Jew, running
a few paces to the right, crept through that gap.
subQuotationList: ['As I am that the men were at the window,', 'The tall man leaped over, just there; and the Jew, running\na few paces to the right, crept through that gap.']
speaker: Oliver Twist

quoteText: This is strange!
subQuotationList: ['This is strange!']
speaker: Harry Maylie

quoteText:
Strange? Blathers and Duff, themselves, could
make nothing of it.
subQuotationList: ['Strange?', 'Blathers and Duff, themselves, could\nmake nothing of it.']
speaker: Mr. Losberne

quoteText:
A few a very few will suffice, Rose, What I shall have to say, has already presented
itself to your mind; the most cherished hopes of my heart are not
unknown to you, though from my lips you have not heard them stated.
subQuotationList: ['A few a very few will suffice, Rose,', 'What I shall have to say, has already presented\nitself to your mind; the most cherished hopes of my heart are not\nunknown to you, though from my lips you have not heard them stated.']
speaker: Harry Maylie

quoteText: I I ought to have left here, before,
subQuotationList: ['I I ought to have left here, before,']
speaker: Harry Maylie

quoteText:
You should, indeed, Forgive me for saying so, but I
wish you had.
subQuotationList: ['You should, indeed,', 'Forgive me for saying so, but I\nwish you had.']
speaker: Rose Maylie

quoteText:
I was brought here, by the most dreadful and agonising of all
apprehensions, the fear of losing the one dear
being on whom my every wish and hope are fixed. You had been dying;
trembling between earth and heaven. We know that when the young, the
beautiful, and good, are visited with sickness, their pure spirits
insensibly turn towards their bright home of lasting rest; we know,
Heaven help us! that the best and fairest of our kind, too often fade
in blooming.
subQuotationList:
['I was brought here, by the most dreadful and agonising of all
apprehensions,', 'the fear of losing the one dear
being on whom my every wish and hope are fixed. You had been dying;
trembling between earth and heaven. We know that when the young, the
beautiful, and good, are visited with sickness, their pure spirits
insensibly turn towards their bright home of lasting rest; we know,
Heaven help us! that the best and fairest of our kind, too often fade
in blooming.']
speaker: Harry Maylie

quoteText:
A creature, a creature as
fair and innocent of guile as one of God's own angels, fluttered
between life and death. Oh! who could hope, when the distant world to
which she was akin, half opened to her view, that she would return to
the sorrow and calamity of this! Rose, Rose, to know that you were
passing away like some soft shadow, which a light from above, casts
upon the earth; to have no hope that you would be spared to those who
linger here; hardly to know a reason why you should be; to feel that
you belonged to that bright sphere whither so many of the fairest and
the best have winged their early flight; and yet to pray, amid all
these consolations, that you might be restored to those who loved
you these were distractions almost too great to bear. They were mine,
by day and night; and with them, came such a rushing torrent of fears,
and apprehensions, and selfish regrets, lest you should die, and never
know how devotedly I loved you, as almost bore down sense and reason in
its course. You recovered. Day by day, and almost hour by hour, some
drop of health came back, and mingling with the spent and feeble stream
of life which circulated languidly within you, swelled it again to a
high and rushing tide. I have watched you change almost from death, to
life, with eyes that turned blind with their eagerness and deep
affection. Do not tell me that you wish I had lost this; for it has
softened my heart to all mankind.

speaker: Harry Maylie

quoteText:
I did not mean that, I only wish you had left
here, that you might have turned to high and noble pursuits again; to
pursuits well worthy of you.
subQuotationList: ['I did not mean that,', 'I only wish you had left\nhere, that you might have turned to high and noble pursuits again; to\npursuits well worthy of you.']
speaker: Rose Maylie

quoteText:
There is no pursuit more worthy of me: more worthy of the highest
nature that exists: than the struggle to win such a heart as yours, Rose, my own dear Rose! For
years for years I have loved you; hoping to win my way to fame, and
then come proudly home and tell you it had been pursued only for you to
share; thinking, in my daydreams, how I would remind you, in that happy
moment, of the many silent tokens I had given of a boy's attachment,
and claim your hand, as in redemption of some old mute contract that
had been sealed between us! That time has not arrived; but here, with
not fame won, and no young vision realised, I offer you the heart so
long your own, and stake my all upon the words with which you greet the
offer.
subQuotationList:
['There is no pursuit more worthy of me: more worthy of the highest
nature that exists: than the struggle to win such a heart as yours,', "Rose, my own dear Rose! For
years for years I have loved you; hoping to win my way to fame, and
then come proudly home and tell you it had been pursued only for you to
share; thinking, in my daydreams, how I would remind you, in that happy
moment, of the many silent tokens I had given of a boy's attachment,
and claim your hand, as in redemption of some old mute contract that
had been sealed between us! That time has not arrived; but here, with
not fame won, and no young vision realised, I offer you the heart so
long your own, and stake my all upon the words with which you greet the
offer."]
speaker: Harry Maylie
mentionEntitiesList: [[], [['Rose Maylie'], ['Rose Maylie'], ['Rose Maylie'], ['Rose Maylie'], ['Rose Maylie'], ['Rose Maylie'], ['Rose Maylie'], ['Rose Maylie', 'Harry Maylie'], ['Rose Maylie'], ['Rose Maylie'], ['Rose Maylie']]]

quoteText:
Your behaviour has ever been kind and noble. As you believe that I am not
insensible or ungrateful, so hear my answer.
subQuotationList: ['Your behaviour has ever been kind and noble.', 'As you believe that I am not\ninsensible or ungrateful, so hear my answer.']
speaker: Rose Maylie

quoteText: It is, that I may endeavour to deserve you; it is, dear Rose?
subQuotationList: ['It is, that I may endeavour to deserve you; it is, dear Rose?']
speaker: Harry Maylie

quoteText:
It is, that you must endeavour to forget me; not as
your old and dearly-attached companion, for that would wound me deeply;
but, as the object of your love. Look into the world; think how many
hearts you would be proud to gain, are there. Confide some other
passion to me, if you will; I will be the truest, warmest, and most
faithful friend you have.
subQuotationList:
['It is,', 'that you must endeavour to forget me; not as
your old and dearly-attached companion, for that would wound me deeply;
but, as the object of your love. Look into the world; think how many
hearts you would be proud to gain, are there. Confide some other
passion to me, if you will; I will be the truest, warmest, and most
faithful friend you have.']
speaker: Rose Maylie
mentionEntitiesList: [[], [['Harry Maylie'], ['Harry Maylie'], ['Harry Maylie'], ['Harry Maylie'], ['Harry Maylie'], ['Harry Maylie']]]

quoteText:
And your reasons, Rose, your
reasons for this decision?
subQuotationList: ['And your reasons, Rose,', 'your\nreasons for this decision?']
speaker: Harry Maylie

quoteText:
You have a right to know them, You can say nothing to
alter my resolution. It is a duty that I must perform. I owe it, alike
to others, and to myself.
subQuotationList: ['You have a right to know them,', 'You can say nothing to\nalter my resolution. It is a duty that I must perform. I owe it, alike\nto others, and to myself.']
speaker: Rose Maylie

quoteText: To yourself?
subQuotationList: ['To yourself?']
speaker: Harry Maylie

quoteText:
Yes, Harry. I owe it to myself, that I, a friendless, portionless,
girl, with a blight upon my name, should not give your friends reason
to suspect that I had sordidly yielded to your first passion, and
fastened myself, a clog, on all your hopes and projects. I owe it to
you and yours, to prevent you from opposing, in the warmth of your
generous nature, this great obstacle to your progress in the world.
subQuotationList:
['Yes, Harry. I owe it to myself, that I, a friendless, portionless,
girl, with a blight upon my name, should not give your friends reason
to suspect that I had sordidly yielded to your first passion, and
fastened myself, a clog, on all your hopes and projects. I owe it to
you and yours, to prevent you from opposing, in the warmth of your
generous nature, this great obstacle to your progress in the world.']
speaker: Rose Maylie
mentionEntitiesList: [[['Harry Maylie'], ['Harry Maylie'], ['Harry Maylie'], ['Harry Maylie'], ['Harry Maylie'], ['Harry Maylie'], ['Harry Maylie'], ['Harry Maylie']]]

quoteText: If your inclinations chime with your sense of duty
subQuotationList: ['If your inclinations chime with your sense of duty']
speaker: Harry Maylie

quoteText: They do not,
subQuotationList: ['They do not,']
speaker: Rose Maylie

quoteText:
Then you return my love? Say but that, dear Rose; say
but that; and soften the bitterness of this hard disappointment!
subQuotationList: ['Then you return my love?', 'Say but that, dear Rose; say\nbut that; and soften the bitterness of this hard disappointment!']
speaker: Harry Maylie

quoteText: If I could have done so, without doing heavy wrong to him I loved, I could have
subQuotationList: ['If I could have done so, without doing heavy wrong to him I loved,', 'I could have']
speaker: Rose Maylie

quoteText:
Have received this declaration very differently? Do not
conceal that from me, at least, Rose.
subQuotationList: ['Have received this declaration very differently?', 'Do not\nconceal that from me, at least, Rose.']
speaker: Harry Maylie

quoteText:
I could, Stay! why
should we prolong this painful interview? Most painful to me, and yet
productive of lasting happiness, notwithstanding; for it _will_ be
happiness to know that I once held the high place in your regard which
I now occupy, and every triumph you achieve in life will animate me
with new fortitude and firmness. Farewell, Harry! As we have met
to-day, we meet no more; but in other relations than those in which
this conversation have placed us, we may be long and happily entwined;
and may every blessing that the prayers of a true and earnest heart can
call down from the source of all truth and sincerity, cheer and prosper
you!
subQuotationList:
['I could,', 'Stay!', 'why
should we prolong this painful interview? Most painful to me, and yet
productive of lasting happiness, notwithstanding; for it _will_ be

speaker: Rose Maylie
