quoteText:
Another word, Rose, Your reason in your own words. From
your own lips, let me hear it!
subQuotationList: ['Another word, Rose,', 'Your reason in your own words. From\nyour own lips, let me hear it!']
speaker: Harry Maylie

quoteText:
The prospect before you, is a brilliant one.
All the honours to which great talents and powerful connections can
help men in public life, are in store for you. But those connections
are proud; and I will neither mingle with such as may hold in scorn the
mother who gave me life; nor bring disgrace or failure on the son of
her who has so well supplied that mother's place. In a word, there
is a stain upon my name, which the world visits on innocent heads. I
will carry it into no blood but my own; and the reproach shall rest
alone on me.
subQuotationList:
['The prospect before you,', "is a brilliant one.
All the honours to which great talents and powerful connections can
help men in public life, are in store for you. But those connections
are proud; and I will neither mingle with such as may hold in scorn the
mother who gave me life; nor bring disgrace or failure on the son of
her who has so well supplied that mother's place. In a word,", 'there
is a stain upon my name, which the world visits on innocent heads. I
will carry it into no blood but my own; and the reproach shall rest
alone on me.']
speaker: Rose Maylie
mentionTextsList: [['you'], ['you', "the son of\nher who has so well supplied that mother's place"], []]

quoteText:
One word more, Rose. Dearest Rose! one more! If I had been less less fortunate, the world would
call it if some obscure and peaceful life had been my destiny if I had
been poor, sick, helpless would you have turned from me then? Or has my
probable advancement to riches and honour, given this scruple birth?
subQuotationList:
['One word more, Rose. Dearest Rose! one more!', 'If I had been less less fortunate, the world would
call it if some obscure and peaceful life had been my destiny if I had
been poor, sick, helpless would you have turned from me then? Or has my
probable advancement to riches and honour, given this scruple birth?']
speaker: Harry Maylie

quoteText:
Do not press me to reply, The question does not
arise, and never will. It is unfair, almost unkind, to urge it.
subQuotationList: ['Do not press me to reply,', 'The question does not\narise, and never will. It is unfair, almost unkind, to urge it.']
speaker: Rose Maylie

quoteText:
If your answer be what I almost dare to hope it is, it will shed a gleam of happiness upon my lonely way, and light the
path before me. It is not an idle thing to do so much, by the utterance
of a few brief words, for one who loves you beyond all else. Oh, Rose:
in the name of my ardent and enduring attachment; in the name of all I
have suffered for you, and all you doom me to undergo; answer me this
one question!
subQuotationList:
['If your answer be what I almost dare to hope it is,', 'it will shed a gleam of happiness upon my lonely way, and light the
path before me. It is not an idle thing to do so much, by the utterance
of a few brief words, for one who loves you beyond all else. Oh, Rose:
in the name of my ardent and enduring attachment; in the name of all I
have suffered for you, and all you doom me to undergo; answer me this
one question!']
speaker: Harry Maylie

quoteText:
Then, if your lot had been differently cast, if you
had been even a little, but not so far, above me; if I could have been
a help and comfort to you in any humble scene of peace and retirement,
and not a blot and drawback in ambitious and distinguished crowds; I
should have been spared this trial. I have every reason to be happy,
very happy, now; but then, Harry, I own I should have been happier.
subQuotationList:
['Then, if your lot had been differently cast,', 'if you
had been even a little, but not so far, above me; if I could have been
a help and comfort to you in any humble scene of peace and retirement,
and not a blot and drawback in ambitious and distinguished crowds; I
should have been spared this trial. I have every reason to be happy,
very happy, now; but then, Harry, I own I should have been happier.']
speaker: Rose Maylie

quoteText: I cannot help this weakness, and it makes my purpose stronger, I must leave you now, indeed.
subQuotationList: ['I cannot help this weakness, and it makes my purpose stronger,', 'I must leave you now, indeed.']
speaker: Rose Maylie

quoteText:
I ask one promise, Once, and only once more, say within
a year, but it may be much sooner, I may speak to you again on this
subject, for the last time.
subQuotationList: ['I ask one promise,', 'Once, and only once more, say within\na year, but it may be much sooner, I may speak to you again on this\nsubject, for the last time.']
speaker: Harry Maylie

quoteText: Not to press me to alter my right determination, it will be useless.
subQuotationList: ['Not to press me to alter my right determination,', 'it will be useless.']
speaker: Rose Maylie

quoteText:
No, to hear you repeat it, if you will finally repeat
it! I will lay at your feet, whatever of station of fortune I may
possess; and if you still adhere to your present resolution, will not
seek, by word or act, to change it.
subQuotationList:
['No,', 'to hear you repeat it, if you will finally repeat
it! I will lay at your feet, whatever of station of fortune I may
possess; and if you still adhere to your present resolution, will not
seek, by word or act, to change it.']
speaker: Harry Maylie

quoteText:
Then let it be so, it is but one pang the more, and
by that time I may be enabled to bear it better.
subQuotationList: ['Then let it be so,', 'it is but one pang the more, and\nby that time I may be enabled to bear it better.']
speaker: Rose Maylie

subQuotationList: ['And so you are resolved to be my travelling companion this morning;\neh?', 'Why, you are not in the same mind or intention two\nhalf-hours together!']
speaker: Mr. Losberne

quoteText: You will tell me a different tale one of these days,
subQuotationList: ['You will tell me a different tale one of these days,']
speaker: Harry Maylie

quoteText:
I hope I may have good cause to do so, though
I confess I don't think I shall. But yesterday morning you had made up
your mind, in a great hurry, to stay here, and to accompany your
mother, like a dutiful son, to the sea-side. Before noon, you announce
that you are going to do me the honour of accompanying me as far as I
go, on your road to London. And at night, you urge me, with great
mystery, to start before the ladies are stirring; the consequence of
which is, that young Oliver here is pinned down to his breakfast when
he ought to be ranging the meadows after botanical phenomena of all
kinds. Too bad, isn't it, Oliver?

I confess I don't think I shall. But yesterday morning you had made up

that you are going to do me the honour of accompanying me as far as I

mystery, to start before the ladies are stirring; the consequence of
which is, that young Oliver here is pinned down to his breakfast when
he ought to be ranging the meadows after botanical phenomena of all
kinds. Too bad, isn't it, Oliver?"]

quoteText:
The great nobs, under which designation, I presume,
you include my most stately uncle, have not communicated with me at
all, since I have been here; nor, at this time of the year, is it
likely that anything would occur to render necessary my immediate
attendance among them.
subQuotationList:

quoteText:
Well, you are a queer fellow. But of course they
will get you into parliament at the election before Christmas, and
these sudden shiftings and changes are no bad preparation for political
life. There's something in that. Good training is always desirable,
whether the race be for place, cup, or sweepstakes.

quoteText:
Something that was taken from her, Something that she
wore. Something that
subQuotationList: ['Something that was taken from her,', 'Something that she\nwore. Something that']
speaker: Monks

quoteText:
You had better bid, I have heard enough,
already, to assure me that you are the man I ought to talk to.
subQuotationList: ['You had better bid,', 'I have heard enough,\nalready, to assure me that you are the man I ought to talk to.']
speaker: Mrs. Corney

quoteText: What's it worth to you?
subQuotationList: ["What's it worth to you?"]
speaker: Mrs. Corney

quoteText:
It may be nothing; it may be twenty pounds, Speak
out, and let me know which.
subQuotationList: ['It may be nothing; it may be twenty pounds,', 'Speak\nout, and let me know which.']
speaker: Monks

quoteText:
Add five pounds to the sum you have named; give me five-and-twenty
pounds in gold, and I'll tell you all I know. Not
before.
subQuotationList: ['Add five pounds to the sum you have named; give me five-and-twenty\npounds in gold,', "and I'll tell you all I know. Not\nbefore."]
speaker: Mrs. Corney

quoteText: Five-and-twenty pounds!
subQuotationList: ['Five-and-twenty pounds!']
speaker: Monks

quoteText:
I spoke as plainly as I could, It's not a large
sum, either.
subQuotationList: ['I spoke as plainly as I could,', "It's not a large\nsum, either."]
speaker: Mrs. Corney

quoteText:
Not a large sum for a paltry secret, that may be nothing when it's
told! and which has been lying dead for
twelve years past or more!
subQuotationList: ["Not a large sum for a paltry secret, that may be nothing when it's\ntold!", 'and which has been lying dead for\ntwelve years past or more!']
speaker: Monks

quoteText:
Such matters keep well, and, like good wine, often double their value
in course of time, As to lying dead, there are those who
will lie dead for twelve thousand years to come, or twelve million, for
anything you or I know, who will tell strange tales at last!
subQuotationList:
['Such matters keep well, and, like good wine, often double their value
in course of time,', 'As to lying dead, there are those who
will lie dead for twelve thousand years to come, or twelve million, for
anything you or I know, who will tell strange tales at last!']
speaker: Mrs. Corney

quoteText: What if I pay it for nothing?
subQuotationList: ['What if I pay it for nothing?']
speaker: Monks

quoteText:
You can easily take it away again, I am but a
woman; alone here; and unprotected.
subQuotationList: ['You can easily take it away again,', 'I am but a\nwoman; alone here; and unprotected.']
speaker: Mrs. Corney

quoteText:
Not alone, my dear, nor unprotected, neither, _I_ am here, my dear. And besides, Mr. Monks is too
much of a gentleman to attempt any violence on porochial persons. Mr.
Monks is aware that I am not a young man, my dear, and also that I am a
little run to seed, as I may say; but he has heerd: I say I have no
doubt Mr. Monks has heerd, my dear: that I am a very determined
officer, with very uncommon strength, if I'm once roused. I only want a
little rousing; that's all.
subQuotationList:
['Not alone, my dear, nor unprotected, neither,', '_I_ am here, my dear. And besides,', "Mr. Monks is too
much of a gentleman to attempt any violence on porochial persons. Mr.
Monks is aware that I am not a young man, my dear, and also that I am a
little run to seed, as I may say; but he has heerd: I say I have no
doubt Mr. Monks has heerd, my dear: that I am a very determined
officer, with very uncommon strength, if I'm once roused. I only want a
little rousing; that's all."]
speaker: Mr. Bumble

quoteText:
You are a fool, and had better hold your
tongue.
subQuotationList: ['You are a fool,', 'and had better hold your\ntongue.']
speaker: Mrs. Corney

quoteText:
He had better have cut it out, before he came, if he can't speak in a
lower tone, So! He's your husband, eh?
subQuotationList: ["He had better have cut it out, before he came, if he can't speak in a\nlower tone,", "So! He's your husband, eh?"]
speaker: Monks

quoteText: He my husband!
subQuotationList: ['He my husband!']
speaker: Mrs. Corney

quoteText:
I thought as much, when you came in, So much
the better; I have less hesitation in dealing with two people, when I
find that there's only one will between them. I'm in earnest. See
here!
subQuotationList:
['I thought as much, when you came in,', "So much
the better; I have less hesitation in dealing with two people, when I
find that there's only one will between them. I'm in earnest. See
here!"]
speaker: Monks

quoteText:
Now, gather them up; and when this cursed peal of thunder,
which I feel is coming up to break over the house-top, is gone, let's
hear your story.
subQuotationList: ['Now,', "gather them up; and when this cursed peal of thunder,\nwhich I feel is coming up to break over the house-top, is gone, let's\nhear your story."]
speaker: Monks

quoteText: When this woman, that we called old Sally, died, she and I were alone.
subQuotationList: ['When this woman, that we called old Sally, died,', 'she and I were alone.']
speaker: Mrs. Corney

quoteText:
Was there no one by? No
sick wretch or idiot in some other bed? No one who could hear, and
might, by possibility, understand?
subQuotationList: ['Was there no one by?', 'No\nsick wretch or idiot in some other bed? No one who could hear, and\nmight, by possibility, understand?']
speaker: Monks

quoteText:
Not a soul, we were alone. _I_ stood alone beside
the body when death came over it.
subQuotationList: ['Not a soul,', 'we were alone. _I_ stood alone beside\nthe body when death came over it.']
speaker: Mrs. Corney

quoteText: Good, Go on.
subQuotationList: ['Good,', 'Go on.']
speaker: Monks

quoteText:
She spoke of a young creature, who had brought a
child into the world some years before; not merely in the same room,
but in the same bed, in which she then lay dying.
subQuotationList: ['She spoke of a young creature,', 'who had brought a\nchild into the world some years before; not merely in the same room,\nbut in the same bed, in which she then lay dying.']
speaker: Mrs. Corney

quoteText: Ay? Blood! How things come about!
subQuotationList: ['Ay?', 'Blood! How things come about!']
speaker: Monks

quoteText:
The child was the one you named to him last night, the mother this nurse had
robbed.
subQuotationList: ['The child was the one you named to him last night,', 'the mother this nurse had\nrobbed.']
speaker: Mrs. Corney

quoteText: In life?
subQuotationList: ['In life?']
speaker: Monks

quoteText:
In death, She
stole from the corpse, when it had hardly turned to one, that which the
dead mother had prayed her, with her last breath, to keep for the
infant's sake.
subQuotationList:
['In death,', "She
stole from the corpse, when it had hardly turned to one, that which the
dead mother had prayed her, with her last breath, to keep for the
infant's sake."]
speaker: Mrs. Corney

quoteText:
She sold it, did she sell it?
Where? When? To whom? How long before?
subQuotationList: ['She sold it,', 'did she sell it?\nWhere? When? To whom? How long before?']
speaker: Monks

quoteText: As she told me, with great difficulty, that she had done this, she fell back and died.
subQuotationList: ['As she told me, with great difficulty, that she had done this,', 'she fell back and died.']
speaker: Mrs. Corney

quoteText:
Without saying more? It's a lie! I'll not be
played with. She said more. I'll tear the life out of you both, but
I'll know what it was.
subQuotationList: ['Without saying more?', "It's a lie! I'll not be\nplayed with. She said more. I'll tear the life out of you both, but\nI'll know what it was."]
speaker: Monks

quoteText:
She didn't utter another word, but she clutched my gown, violently, with one hand, which
was partly closed; and when I saw that she was dead, and so removed the
hand by force, I found it clasped a scrap of dirty paper.
subQuotationList: ["She didn't utter another word,", 'but she clutched my gown, violently, with one hand, which\nwas partly closed; and when I saw that she was dead, and so removed the\nhand by force, I found it clasped a scrap of dirty paper.']
speaker: Mrs. Corney

quoteText: Which contained
subQuotationList: ['Which contained']
speaker: Monks

quoteText: Nothing, it was a pawnbroker's duplicate.
subQuotationList: ['Nothing,', "it was a pawnbroker's duplicate."]
speaker: Mrs. Corney

quoteText: For what?
subQuotationList: ['For what?']
speaker: Monks

quoteText:
In good time I'll tell you. I judge that she had
kept the trinket, for some time, in the hope of turning it to better
account; and then had pawned it; and had saved or scraped together
money to pay the pawnbroker's interest year by year, and prevent its
running out; so that if anything came of it, it could still be
redeemed. Nothing had come of it; and, as I tell you, she died with the
scrap of paper, all worn and tattered, in her hand. The time was out in
two days; I thought something might one day come of it too; and so
redeemed the pledge.
subQuotationList:
["In good time I'll tell you.", "I judge that she had
kept the trinket, for some time, in the hope of turning it to better
account; and then had pawned it; and had saved or scraped together
money to pay the pawnbroker's interest year by year, and prevent its
running out; so that if anything came of it, it could still be
redeemed. Nothing had come of it; and, as I tell you, she died with the
scrap of paper, all worn and tattered, in her hand. The time was out in
two days; I thought something might one day come of it too; and so
redeemed the pledge."]
speaker: Mrs. Corney

quoteText: Where is it now?
subQuotationList: ['Where is it now?']
speaker: Monks

quoteText: _There_,
subQuotationList: ['_There_,']
speaker: Mrs. Corney

quoteText:
It has the word  Agnes' engraved on the inside, There is a blank left for the surname; and then follows the date;
which is within a year before the child was born. I found out that.
subQuotationList: ["It has the word  Agnes' engraved on the inside,", 'There is a blank left for the surname; and then follows the date;\nwhich is within a year before the child was born. I found out that.']
speaker: Mrs. Corney

quoteText: And this is all?
subQuotationList: ['And this is all?']
speaker: Monks

quoteText: All,
speaker: Mrs. Corney

quoteText:
I know nothing of the story, beyond what I can guess at, and I want to know
nothing; for it's safer not. But I may ask you two questions, may I?
subQuotationList: ['I know nothing of the story, beyond what I can guess at,', "and I want to know\nnothing; for it's safer not. But I may ask you two questions, may I?"]
speaker: Mrs. Corney

quoteText:
You may ask, but whether I
answer or not is another question.
subQuotationList: ['You may ask,', 'but whether I\nanswer or not is another question.']
speaker: Monks

quoteText: Which makes three,
subQuotationList: ['Which makes three,']
speaker: Mr. Bumble

quoteText: Is that what you expected to get from me?
subQuotationList: ['Is that what you expected to get from me?']
speaker: Mrs. Corney

quoteText: It is, The other question?
subQuotationList: ['It is,', 'The other question?']
speaker: Monks

quoteText: What do you propose to do with it? Can it be used against me?
subQuotationList: ['What do you propose to do with it? Can it be used against me?']
speaker: Mrs. Corney

quoteText:
Never, nor against me either. See here! But don't
move a step forward, or your life is not worth a bulrush.
subQuotationList: ['Never,', "nor against me either. See here! But don't\nmove a step forward, or your life is not worth a bulrush."]
speaker: Monks

quoteText:
Look down, Don't
fear me. I could have let you down, quietly enough, when you were
seated over it, if that had been my game. If you flung a man's body down there, where would it be to-morrow
morning?
subQuotationList:
['Look down,', "Don't
fear me. I could have let you down, quietly enough, when you were
seated over it, if that had been my game.", "If you flung a man's body down there, where would it be to-morrow
morning?"]
speaker: Monks

quoteText: Twelve miles down the river, and cut to pieces besides,
subQuotationList: ['Twelve miles down the river, and cut to pieces besides,']
speaker: Mr. Bumble

quoteText:
There! If the sea ever gives up its dead, as books
say it will, it will keep its gold and silver to itself, and that trash
among it. We have nothing more to say, and may break up our pleasant
party.
subQuotationList:
['There!', 'If the sea ever gives up its dead, as books
say it will, it will keep its gold and silver to itself, and that trash
among it. We have nothing more to say, and may break up our pleasant
party.']
speaker: Monks

quoteText: By all means,
subQuotationList: ['By all means,']
speaker: Mr. Bumble

quoteText: You'll keep a quiet tongue in your head, will you? I am not afraid of your wife.
subQuotationList: ["You'll keep a quiet tongue in your head, will you?", 'I am not afraid of your wife.']
speaker: Monks

quoteText:
You may depend upon me, young man, On
everybody's account, young man; on my own, you know, Mr. Monks.
subQuotationList: ['You may depend upon me, young man,', "On\neverybody's account, young man; on my own, you know, Mr. Monks."]
speaker: Mr. Bumble

quoteText:
I am glad, for your sake, to hear it, Light your
lantern! And get away from here as fast as you can.
subQuotationList: ['I am glad, for your sake, to hear it,', 'Light your\nlantern! And get away from here as fast as you can.']
speaker: Monks

quoteText: Not long gone seven, How do you feel to-night, Bill?
subQuotationList: ['Not long gone seven,', 'How do you feel to-night, Bill?']
speaker: Nance

quoteText:
As weak as water, Here; lend us a hand, and let me get off this thundering
bed anyhow.
subQuotationList: ['As weak as water,', 'Here; lend us a hand, and let me get off this thundering\nbed anyhow.']
speaker: Bill Sikes

quoteText:
Whining are you? Come! Don't stand snivelling there. If
you can't do anything better than that, cut off altogether. D'ye hear
me?
subQuotationList: ['Whining are you?', "Come! Don't stand snivelling there. If\nyou can't do anything better than that, cut off altogether. D'ye hear\nme?"]
speaker: Bill Sikes

quoteText: I hear you, What fancy have you got in your head now?
subQuotationList: ['I hear you,', 'What fancy have you got in your head now?']
speaker: Nance

quoteText: Oh! you've thought better of it, have you? All the better for you, you have.
subQuotationList: ["Oh! you've thought better of it, have you?", 'All the better for you, you have.']
speaker: Bill Sikes

quoteText: Why, you don't mean to say, you'd be hard upon me to-night, Bill,
subQuotationList: ["Why, you don't mean to say, you'd be hard upon me to-night, Bill,"]
speaker: Nance

quoteText: No! Why not?
subQuotationList: ['No!', 'Why not?']
speaker: Bill Sikes

quoteText:
Such a number of nights, such a number of nights as I've been patient with you,
nursing and caring for you, as if you had been a child: and this the
first that I've seen you like yourself; you wouldn't have served me as
you did just now, if you'd thought of that, would you? Come, come; say
you wouldn't.
subQuotationList:
['Such a number of nights,', "such a number of nights as I've been patient with you,
nursing and caring for you, as if you had been a child: and this the
first that I've seen you like yourself; you wouldn't have served me as
you did just now, if you'd thought of that, would you? Come, come; say
you wouldn't."]
speaker: Nance
mentionEntitiesList: [[], [['Bill Sikes'], ['Bill Sikes'], ['Bill Sikes'], ['Bill Sikes'], ['Bill Sikes'], ['Bill Sikes'], ['Bill Sikes'], ['Bill Sikes'], ['Bill Sikes'], ['Bill Sikes']]]

quoteText:
Well, then, I wouldn't. Why, damme, now, the
girls's whining again!
subQuotationList: ['Well, then,', "I wouldn't. Why, damme, now, the\ngirls's whining again!"]
speaker: Bill Sikes

quoteText:
It's nothing, Don't
you seem to mind me. It'll soon be over.
subQuotationList: ["It's nothing,", "Don't\nyou seem to mind me. It'll soon be over."]
speaker: Nance

quoteText:
What'll be over? What foolery
are you up to, now, again? Get up and bustle about, and don't come over
me with your woman's nonsense.
subQuotationList: ["What'll be over?", "What foolery\nare you up to, now, again? Get up and bustle about, and don't come over\nme with your woman's nonsense."]
speaker: Bill Sikes

quoteText: What's the matter here, my dear?
subQuotationList: ["What's the matter here, my dear?"]
speaker: Fagin

quoteText:
Lend a hand to the girl, can't you? Don't
stand chattering and grinning at me!
subQuotationList: ["Lend a hand to the girl, can't you?", "Don't\nstand chattering and grinning at me!"]
speaker: Bill Sikes

quoteText:
Give her a whiff of fresh air with the bellows, Charley, and you slap her hands, Fagin, while Bill undoes the
petticuts.
subQuotationList: ['Give her a whiff of fresh air with the bellows, Charley,', 'and you slap her hands, Fagin, while Bill undoes the\npetticuts.']
speaker: The Artful Dodger

quoteText: Why, what evil wind has blowed you here?
subQuotationList: ['Why, what evil wind has blowed you here?']
speaker: Bill Sikes

quoteText:
No evil wind at all, my dear, for evil winds blow nobody any good; and
I've brought something good with me, that you'll be glad to see.
Dodger, my dear, open the bundle; and give Bill the little trifles that
we spent all our money on, this morning.
subQuotationList:
["No evil wind at all, my dear, for evil winds blow nobody any good; and
I've brought something good with me, that you'll be glad to see.
Dodger, my dear, open the bundle; and give Bill the little trifles that
we spent all our money on, this morning."]
speaker: Fagin
mentionEntitiesList: [[['Bill Sikes'], ['Bill Sikes'], ['The Artful Dodger'], ['The Artful Dodger'], ['Bill Sikes'], ['The Artful Dodger', 'Charley Bates', 'Fagin']]]

quoteText:
Sitch a rabbit pie, Bill, sitch delicate creeturs, with sitch tender
limbs, Bill, that the wery bones melt in your mouth, and there's no
occasion to pick 'em; half a pound of seven and six-penny green, so
precious strong that if you mix it with biling water, it'll go nigh to
blow the lid of the tea-pot off; a pound and a half of moist sugar that
the niggers didn't work at all at, afore they got it up to sitch a
pitch of goodness, oh no! Two half-quartern brans; pound of best fresh;
piece of double Glo'ster; and, to wind up all, some of the richest sort
you ever lushed!
subQuotationList:
['Sitch a rabbit pie, Bill,', "sitch delicate creeturs, with sitch tender
limbs, Bill, that the wery bones melt in your mouth, and there's no
occasion to pick 'em; half a pound of seven and six-penny green, so
precious strong that if you mix it with biling water, it'll go nigh to
blow the lid of the tea-pot off; a pound and a half of moist sugar that
the niggers didn't work at all at, afore they got it up to sitch a
pitch of goodness, oh no! Two half-quartern brans; pound of best fresh;
piece of double Glo'ster; and, to wind up all, some of the richest sort
you ever lushed!"]
speaker: Charley Bates

quoteText:
Ah! You'll
do, Bill; you'll do now.
subQuotationList: ['Ah!', "You'll\ndo, Bill; you'll do now."]
speaker: Fagin

quoteText:
Do! I might have been done for, twenty times
over, afore you'd have done anything to help me. What do you mean by
leaving a man in this state, three weeks and more, you false-hearted
wagabond?
subQuotationList:
['Do!', "I might have been done for, twenty times
over, afore you'd have done anything to help me. What do you mean by
leaving a man in this state, three weeks and more, you false-hearted
wagabond?"]
speaker: Bill Sikes

quoteText:
Only hear him, boys! And us
come to bring him all these beau-ti-ful things.
subQuotationList: ['Only hear him, boys!', 'And us\ncome to bring him all these beau-ti-ful things.']
speaker: Fagin
mentionEntitiesList: [[['Bill Sikes'], ['Charley Bates', 'The Artful Dodger']], [['The Artful Dodger', 'Charley Bates', 'Fagin'], ['Bill Sikes']]]

quoteText:
The things is well enough in their way, but what have you got to say for
yourself, why you should leave me here, down in the mouth, health,
blunt, and everything else; and take no more notice of me, all this
mortal time, than if I was that 'ere dog. Drive him down, Charley!
subQuotationList:
['The things is well enough in their way,', "but what have you got to say for
yourself, why you should leave me here, down in the mouth, health,
blunt, and everything else; and take no more notice of me, all this
mortal time, than if I was that 'ere dog. Drive him down, Charley!"]
speaker: Bill Sikes

quoteText:
I never see such a jolly dog as that, Smelling the grub like a old lady a going to market! He'd
make his fortun' on the stage that dog would, and rewive the drayma
besides.
subQuotationList: ['I never see such a jolly dog as that,', "Smelling the grub like a old lady a going to market! He'd\nmake his fortun' on the stage that dog would, and rewive the drayma\nbesides."]
speaker: Charley Bates

quoteText:
Hold your din, What have you got to say for yourself, you withered
old fence, eh?
subQuotationList: ['Hold your din,', 'What have you got to say for yourself, you withered\nold fence, eh?']
speaker: Bill Sikes

quoteText: I was away from London, a week and more, my dear, on a plant,
subQuotationList: ['I was away from London, a week and more, my dear, on a plant,']
speaker: Fagin

quoteText:
And what about the other fortnight? What about the
other fortnight that you've left me lying here, like a sick rat in his
hole?
subQuotationList: ['And what about the other fortnight?', "What about the\nother fortnight that you've left me lying here, like a sick rat in his\nhole?"]
speaker: Bill Sikes

quoteText:
I couldn't help it, Bill. I can't go into a long explanation before
company; but I couldn't help it, upon my honour.
subQuotationList: ["I couldn't help it, Bill. I can't go into a long explanation before\ncompany; but I couldn't help it, upon my honour."]
speaker: Fagin

quoteText:
Upon your what? Here! Cut me
off a piece of that pie, one of you boys, to take the taste of that out
of my mouth, or it'll choke me dead.
subQuotationList: ['Upon your what?', "Here! Cut me\noff a piece of that pie, one of you boys, to take the taste of that out\nof my mouth, or it'll choke me dead."]
speaker: Bill Sikes

quoteText:
Don't be out of temper, my dear, I have
never forgot you, Bill; never once.
subQuotationList: ["Don't be out of temper, my dear,", 'I have\nnever forgot you, Bill; never once.']
speaker: Fagin

quoteText:
No! I'll pound it that you han't, You've been scheming and plotting away, every hour that I have laid
shivering and burning here; and Bill was to do this; and Bill was to do
that; and Bill was to do it all, dirt cheap, as soon as he got well:
and was quite poor enough for your work. If it hadn't been for the
girl, I might have died.
subQuotationList:
["No! I'll pound it that you han't,", "You've been scheming and plotting away, every hour that I have laid
shivering and burning here; and Bill was to do this; and Bill was to do
that; and Bill was to do it all, dirt cheap, as soon as he got well:
and was quite poor enough for your work. If it hadn't been for the
girl, I might have died."]
speaker: Bill Sikes

quoteText:
There now, Bill, If it hadn't been for the girl! Who but poor ould Fagin was the means
of your having such a handy girl about you?
subQuotationList: ['There now, Bill,', "If it hadn't been for the girl! Who but poor ould Fagin was the means\nof your having such a handy girl about you?"]
speaker: Fagin

quoteText:
He says true enough there! Let
him be; let him be.
subQuotationList: ['He says true enough there!', 'Let\nhim be; let him be.']
speaker: Nance

quoteText:
It's all very well, but I must have some blunt from
you to-night.
subQuotationList: ["It's all very well,", 'but I must have some blunt from\nyou to-night.']
speaker: Bill Sikes

quoteText: I haven't a piece of coin about me,
subQuotationList: ["I haven't a piece of coin about me,"]
speaker: Fagin

quoteText:
Then you've got lots at home, and I must have some
from there.
subQuotationList: ["Then you've got lots at home,", 'and I must have some\nfrom there.']
speaker: Bill Sikes

quoteText: Lots! I haven't so much as would
subQuotationList: ['Lots!', "I haven't so much as would"]
speaker: Fagin

quoteText:
I don't know how much you've got, and I dare say you hardly know
yourself, as it would take a pretty long time to count it, but I must have some to-night; and that's flat.
subQuotationList: ["I don't know how much you've got, and I dare say you hardly know\nyourself, as it would take a pretty long time to count it,", "but I must have some to-night; and that's flat."]
speaker: Bill Sikes

quoteText:
Well, well, I'll send the Artful round
presently.
subQuotationList: ['Well, well,', "I'll send the Artful round\npresently."]
speaker: Fagin

quoteText:
You won't do nothing of the kind, The Artful's a
deal too artful, and would forget to come, or lose his way, or get
dodged by traps and so be perwented, or anything for an excuse, if you
put him up to it. Nancy shall go to the ken and fetch it, to make all
sure; and I'll lie down and have a snooze while she's gone.
subQuotationList:

old Fagin's on the night he went out from the house in Pentonville.

quoteText:
I, lady! I am the infamous creature you have heard
of, that lives among the thieves, and that never from the first moment
I can recollect my eyes and senses opening on London streets have known
any better life, or kinder words than they have given me, so help me
God! Do not mind shrinking openly from me, lady. I am younger than you
would think, to look at me, but I am well used to it. The poorest women
fall back, as I make my way along the crowded pavement.

were never in the midst of cold and hunger, and riot and drunkenness,
and and something worse than all as I have been from my cradle. I may
use the word, for the alley and the gutter were mine, as they will be
my deathbed.

They laughed, and talked of his success in
doing this; and Monks, talking on about the boy, and getting very wild,
said that though he had got the young devil's money safely now, he'd
rather have had it the other way; for, what a game it would have been
to have brought down the boast of the father's will, by driving him
through every jail in town, and then hauling him up for some capital
felony which Fagin could easily manage, after having made a good profit
of him besides.

quoteText:
You do not mean, to tell me that this
was said in earnest?
subQuotationList: ['You do not mean,', 'to tell me that this\nwas said in earnest?']
speaker: Rose Maylie

quoteText:
He spoke in hard and angry earnest, if a man ever did, He is an earnest man when his hatred is up. I
know many who do worse things; but I'd rather listen to them all a
dozen times, than to that Monks once. It is growing late, and I have to
reach home without suspicion of having been on such an errand as this.
I must get back quickly.
subQuotationList:
['He spoke in hard and angry earnest, if a man ever did,', "He is an earnest man when his hatred is up. I
know many who do worse things; but I'd rather listen to them all a
dozen times, than to that Monks once. It is growing late, and I have to
reach home without suspicion of having been on such an errand as this.
I must get back quickly."]
speaker: Nance

quoteText:
But what can I do? To what use can I turn this
communication without you? Back! Why do you wish to return to
companions you paint in such terrible colors? If you repeat this
information to a gentleman whom I can summon in an instant from the
next room, you can be consigned to some place of safety without half an
hour's delay.
subQuotationList:
['But what can I do?', "To what use can I turn this
communication without you? Back! Why do you wish to return to
companions you paint in such terrible colors? If you repeat this
information to a gentleman whom I can summon in an instant from the
next room, you can be consigned to some place of safety without half an
hour's delay."]
speaker: Rose Maylie

quoteText:
I wish to go back, I must go back, because how can I
tell such things to an innocent lady like you? because among the men I
have told you of, there is one: the most desperate among them all; that
I can't leave: no, not even to be saved from the life I am leading
now.
subQuotationList:
['I wish to go back,', "I must go back, because how can I
tell such things to an innocent lady like you? because among the men I
have told you of, there is one: the most desperate among them all; that
I can't leave: no, not even to be saved from the life I am leading
now."]
speaker: Nance
mentionEntitiesList: [[], [['Rose Maylie'], ['Rose Maylie'], ['Bill Sikes'], ['Bill Sikes', 'Charley Bates', 'Fagin', 'The Artful Dodger']]]

quoteText:
Your having interfered in this dear boy's behalf before, your coming here, at so great a risk, to tell me what you have heard;
your manner, which convinces me of the truth of what you say; your
evident contrition, and sense of shame; all lead me to believe that you
might yet be reclaimed. Oh! do not turn a deaf ear to the
entreaties of one of your own sex; the first the first, I do believe,
who ever appealed to you in the voice of pity and compassion. Do hear
my words, and let me save you yet, for better things.
subQuotationList:
["Your having interfered in this dear boy's behalf before,", 'your coming here, at so great a risk, to tell me what you have heard;
your manner, which convinces me of the truth of what you say; your
evident contrition, and sense of shame; all lead me to believe that you
might yet be reclaimed. Oh!', 'do not turn a deaf ear to the
entreaties of one of your own sex; the first the first, I do believe,
who ever appealed to you in the voice of pity and compassion. Do hear
my words, and let me save you yet, for better things.']
speaker: Rose Maylie

quoteText:
Lady, dear, sweet, angel lady,
you _are_ the first that ever blessed me with such words as these, and
if I had heard them years ago, they might have turned me from a life of
sin and sorrow; but it is too late, it is too late!
subQuotationList:
['Lady,', 'dear, sweet, angel lady,
you _are_ the first that ever blessed me with such words as these, and
if I had heard them years ago, they might have turned me from a life of
sin and sorrow; but it is too late, it is too late!']
speaker: Nance

quoteText: It is never too late, for penitence and atonement.
subQuotationList: ['It is never too late,', 'for penitence and atonement.']
speaker: Rose Maylie

quoteText:
It is, I cannot leave
him now! I could not be his death.
subQuotationList: ['It is,', 'I cannot leave\nhim now! I could not be his death.']
speaker: Nance

quoteText: Why should you be?
subQuotationList: ['Why should you be?']
speaker: Rose Maylie

quoteText:
Nothing could save him, If I told others what I have
told you, and led to their being taken, he would be sure to die. He is
the boldest, and has been so cruel!
subQuotationList: ['Nothing could save him,', 'If I told others what I have\ntold you, and led to their being taken, he would be sure to die. He is\nthe boldest, and has been so cruel!']
speaker: Nance
mentionEntitiesList: [[['Bill Sikes']], [['Rose Maylie'], ['Bill Sikes', 'Charley Bates', 'Fagin', 'The Artful Dodger'], ['Bill Sikes'], ['Bill Sikes']]]

quoteText:
Is it possible, that for such a man as this, you can
resign every future hope, and the certainty of immediate rescue? It is
madness.
subQuotationList: ['Is it possible,', 'that for such a man as this, you can\nresign every future hope, and the certainty of immediate rescue? It is\nmadness.']
speaker: Rose Maylie

quoteText:
I don't know what it is, I only know that it is
so, and not with me alone, but with hundreds of others as bad and
wretched as myself. I must go back. Whether it is God's wrath for the
wrong I have done, I do not know; but I am drawn back to him through
every suffering and ill usage; and I should be, I believe, if I knew
that I was to die by his hand at last.
subQuotationList:
["I don't know what it is,", "I only know that it is
so, and not with me alone, but with hundreds of others as bad and
wretched as myself. I must go back. Whether it is God's wrath for the
wrong I have done, I do not know; but I am drawn back to him through
every suffering and ill usage; and I should be, I believe, if I knew
that I was to die by his hand at last."]
speaker: Nance

quoteText:
What am I to do? I should not let you depart from me
thus.
subQuotationList: ['What am I to do?', 'I should not let you depart from me\nthus.']
speaker: Rose Maylie

quoteText:
You should, lady, and I know you will, You will not stop my going because I have trusted in your goodness,
and forced no promise from you, as I might have done.
subQuotationList: ['You should, lady, and I know you will,', 'You will not stop my going because I have trusted in your goodness,\nand forced no promise from you, as I might have done.']
speaker: Nance
mentionEntitiesList: [[['Rose Maylie'], ['Rose Maylie'], ['Rose Maylie']], [['Rose Maylie'], ['Rose Maylie'], ['Rose Maylie']]]

quoteText:
Of what use, then, is the communication you have made? This mystery must be investigated, or how will its disclosure to me,
benefit Oliver, whom you are anxious to serve?
subQuotationList: ['Of what use, then, is the communication you have made?', 'This mystery must be investigated, or how will its disclosure to me,\nbenefit Oliver, whom you are anxious to serve?']
speaker: Rose Maylie

quoteText:
You must have some kind gentleman about you that will hear it as a
secret, and advise you what to do,
subQuotationList: ['You must have some kind gentleman about you that will hear it as a\nsecret, and advise you what to do,']
speaker: Nance

quoteText:
But where can I find you again when it is necessary? I
do not seek to know where these dreadful people live, but where will
you be walking or passing at any settled period from this time?
subQuotationList: ['But where can I find you again when it is necessary?', 'I\ndo not seek to know where these dreadful people live, but where will\nyou be walking or passing at any settled period from this time?']
speaker: Rose Maylie

quoteText:
Will you promise me that you will have my secret strictly kept, and
come alone, or with the only other person that knows it; and that I
shall not be watched or followed?
subQuotationList: ['Will you promise me that you will have my secret strictly kept, and\ncome alone, or with the only other person that knows it; and that I\nshall not be watched or followed?']
speaker: Nance

quoteText: I promise you solemnly,
subQuotationList: ['I promise you solemnly,']
speaker: Rose Maylie

quoteText:
Every Sunday night, from eleven until the clock strikes twelve, I will walk on London Bridge if I am
alive.
subQuotationList: ['Every Sunday night, from eleven until the clock strikes twelve,', 'I will walk on London Bridge if I am\nalive.']
speaker: Nance

quoteText:
Stay another moment, Think once again on your own condition, and the
opportunity you have of escaping from it. You have a claim on me: not
only as the voluntary bearer of this intelligence, but as a woman lost
almost beyond redemption. Will you return to this gang of robbers, and
to this man, when a word can save you? What fascination is it that can
take you back, and make you cling to wickedness and misery? Oh! is
there no chord in your heart that I can touch! Is there nothing left,
to which I can appeal against this terrible infatuation!
subQuotationList:
['Stay another moment,', 'Think once again on your own condition, and the
opportunity you have of escaping from it. You have a claim on me: not
only as the voluntary bearer of this intelligence, but as a woman lost
almost beyond redemption. Will you return to this gang of robbers, and
to this man, when a word can save you? What fascination is it that can
take you back, and make you cling to wickedness and misery? Oh! is
there no chord in your heart that I can touch! Is there nothing left,
to which I can appeal against this terrible infatuation!']
speaker: Rose Maylie

quoteText:
When ladies as young, and good, and beautiful as you are, give away your hearts, love will carry you all
lengths even such as you, who have home, friends, other admirers,
everything, to fill them. When such as I, who have no certain roof but
the coffinlid, and no friend in sickness or death but the hospital
nurse, set our rotten hearts on any man, and let him fill the place
that has been a blank through all our wretched lives, who can hope to
cure us? Pity us, lady pity us for having only one feeling of the woman
left, and for having that turned, by a heavy judgment, from a comfort
and a pride, into a new means of violence and suffering.
subQuotationList:
['When ladies as young, and good, and beautiful as you are,', 'give away your hearts, love will carry you all
lengths even such as you, who have home, friends, other admirers,
everything, to fill them. When such as I, who have no certain roof but
the coffinlid, and no friend in sickness or death but the hospital
nurse, set our rotten hearts on any man, and let him fill the place
that has been a blank through all our wretched lives, who can hope to
cure us? Pity us, lady pity us for having only one feeling of the woman
left, and for having that turned, by a heavy judgment, from a comfort
and a pride, into a new means of violence and suffering.']
speaker: Nance

quoteText:
You will, take some money from me, which
may enable you to live without dishonesty at all events until we meet
again?
subQuotationList: ['You will,', 'take some money from me, which\nmay enable you to live without dishonesty at all events until we meet\nagain?']
speaker: Rose Maylie

quoteText: Not a penny,
subQuotationList: ['Not a penny,']
speaker: Nance

quoteText: Do not close your heart against all my efforts to help you, I wish to serve you indeed.
subQuotationList: ['Do not close your heart against all my efforts to help you,', 'I wish to serve you indeed.']
speaker: Rose Maylie

quoteText:
You would serve me best, lady, if you could take my life at once; for I have felt more grief to think
of what I am, to-night, than I ever did before, and it would be
something not to die in the hell in which I have lived. God bless you,
sweet lady, and send as much happiness on your head as I have brought
shame on mine!
subQuotationList:
['You would serve me best, lady,', 'if you could take my life at once; for I have felt more grief to think
of what I am, to-night, than I ever did before, and it would be
something not to die in the hell in which I have lived. God bless you,
sweet lady, and send as much happiness on your head as I have brought
shame on mine!']
speaker: Nance
mentionEntitiesList: [[['Rose Maylie'], ['Rose Maylie']], [['Rose Maylie'], ['Rose Maylie'], ['Rose Maylie'], ['Rose Maylie']]]

quoteText:
If it be painful to him, to come back here, how painful
it will be to me! But perhaps he will not come; he may write, or he may
come himself, and studiously abstain from meeting me he did when he
went away. I hardly thought he would; but it was better for us both.
subQuotationList:
['If it be painful to him,', 'to come back here, how painful
it will be to me! But perhaps he will not come; he may write, or he may
come himself, and studiously abstain from meeting me he did when he
went away. I hardly thought he would; but it was better for us both.']
speaker: Rose Maylie
mentionEntitiesList: [[['Harry Maylie']], [['Harry Maylie'], ['Harry Maylie'], ['Harry Maylie'], ['Harry Maylie'], ['Harry Maylie'], ['Harry Maylie'], ['Harry Maylie'], ['Harry Maylie', 'Rose Maylie']]]

quoteText: What makes you look so flurried?
subQuotationList: ['What makes you look so flurried?']
speaker: Rose Maylie

quoteText:
I hardly know how; I feel as if I should be choked, Oh dear! To think that I should see him at last, and you should be
able to know that I have told you the truth!
subQuotationList: ['I hardly know how; I feel as if I should be choked,', 'Oh dear! To think that I should see him at last, and you should be\nable to know that I have told you the truth!']
speaker: Oliver Twist

quoteText: I never thought you had told us anything but the truth, But what is this? of whom do you speak?
subQuotationList: ['I never thought you had told us anything but the truth,', 'But what is this? of whom do you speak?']
speaker: Rose Maylie

quoteText:
I have seen the gentleman, the gentleman who was so good to me Mr. Brownlow, that we
have so often talked about.
subQuotationList: ['I have seen the gentleman,', 'the gentleman who was so good to me Mr. Brownlow, that we\nhave so often talked about.']
speaker: Oliver Twist

quoteText: Where?
subQuotationList: ['Where?']
speaker: Rose Maylie

quoteText:
Getting out of a coach, and going into a house. I didn't speak to him I couldn't speak to him,
for he didn't see me, and I trembled so, that I was not able to go up
to him. But Giles asked, for me, whether he lived there, and they said
he did. Look here, here it is;
here's where he lives I'm going there directly! Oh, dear me, dear me!
What shall I do when I come to see him and hear him speak again!
subQuotationList:
['Getting out of a coach,', "and going into a house. I didn't speak to him I couldn't speak to him,
for he didn't see me, and I trembled so, that I was not able to go up
to him. But Giles asked, for me, whether he lived there, and they said
he did. Look here,", "here it is;
here's where he lives I'm going there directly! Oh, dear me, dear me!
What shall I do when I come to see him and hear him speak again!"]
speaker: Oliver Twist
mentionEntitiesList: [[], [['Mr. Brownlow'], ['Mr. Brownlow'], ['Mr. Brownlow'], ['Mr. Brownlow'], ['Mr. Giles'], ['Mr. Brownlow'], ['Mr. Brownlow']], [['Mr. Brownlow'], ['Mr. Brownlow'], ['Mr. Brownlow']]]

quoteText:
Quick! Tell them to fetch a hackney-coach, and be ready to
go with me. I will take you there directly, without a minute's loss of
time. I will only tell my aunt that we are going out for an hour, and
be ready as soon as you are.
subQuotationList:
['Quick!', "Tell them to fetch a hackney-coach, and be ready to
go with me. I will take you there directly, without a minute's loss of
time. I will only tell my aunt that we are going out for an hour, and
be ready as soon as you are."]
speaker: Rose Maylie

quoteText:
Dear me, I beg your pardon, young lady I imagined it was
some importunate person who I beg you will excuse me. Be seated, pray.
subQuotationList: ['Dear me,', 'I beg your pardon, young lady I imagined it was\nsome importunate person who I beg you will excuse me. Be seated, pray.']
speaker: Mr. Brownlow

quoteText: Mr. Brownlow, I believe, sir?
subQuotationList: ['Mr. Brownlow, I believe, sir?']
speaker: Rose Maylie

quoteText:
That is my name, This is my friend, Mr.
Grimwig. Grimwig, will you leave us for a few minutes?
subQuotationList: ['That is my name,', 'This is my friend, Mr.\nGrimwig. Grimwig, will you leave us for a few minutes?']
speaker: Mr. Brownlow

quoteText:
I believe, that at this period of our
interview, I need not give that gentleman the trouble of going away. If
I am correctly informed, he is cognizant of the business on which I
wish to speak to you.
subQuotationList:
['I believe,', 'that at this period of our
interview, I need not give that gentleman the trouble of going away. If
I am correctly informed, he is cognizant of the business on which I
wish to speak to you.']
speaker: Rose Maylie

quoteText:
I shall surprise you very much, I have no doubt, but you once showed great benevolence and goodness to a
very dear young friend of mine, and I am sure you will take an interest
in hearing of him again.
subQuotationList: ['I shall surprise you very much, I have no doubt,', 'but you once showed great benevolence and goodness to a\nvery dear young friend of mine, and I am sure you will take an interest\nin hearing of him again.']
speaker: Rose Maylie

quoteText: Indeed!
subQuotationList: ['Indeed!']
speaker: Mr. Brownlow

quoteText: Oliver Twist you knew him as,
subQuotationList: ['Oliver Twist you knew him as,']
speaker: Rose Maylie

quoteText:
Do me the favour, my dear young lady, to leave entirely out of the
question that goodness and benevolence of which you speak, and of which
nobody else knows anything; and if you have it in your power to produce
any evidence which will alter the unfavourable opinion I was once
induced to entertain of that poor child, in Heaven's name put me in
possession of it.
subQuotationList:
["Do me the favour, my dear young lady, to leave entirely out of the
question that goodness and benevolence of which you speak, and of which
nobody else knows anything; and if you have it in your power to produce
any evidence which will alter the unfavourable opinion I was once
induced to entertain of that poor child, in Heaven's name put me in
possession of it."]
speaker: Mr. Brownlow
referringExpression: He drew his chair nearer to Miss Maylies and said

quoteText: A bad one! I'll eat my head if he is not a bad one,
subQuotationList: ["A bad one! I'll eat my head if he is not a bad one,"]
speaker: Mr. Grimwig

quoteText:
He is a child of a noble nature and a warm heart, and that Power which has thought fit to try him beyond his
years, has planted in his breast affections and feelings which would do
honour to many who have numbered his days six times over.
subQuotationList: ['He is a child of a noble nature and a warm heart,', 'and that Power which has thought fit to try him beyond his\nyears, has planted in his breast affections and feelings which would do\nhonour to many who have numbered his days six times over.']
speaker: Rose Maylie

quoteText:
I'm only sixty-one, And,
as the devil's in it if this Oliver is not twelve years old at least, I
don't see the application of that remark.
subQuotationList: ["I'm only sixty-one,", "And,\nas the devil's in it if this Oliver is not twelve years old at least, I\ndon't see the application of that remark."]
speaker: Mr. Grimwig

quoteText:
Do not heed my friend, Miss Maylie, he does not
mean what he says.
subQuotationList: ['Do not heed my friend, Miss Maylie,', 'he does not\nmean what he says.']
speaker: Mr. Brownlow

quoteText: Yes, he does,
subQuotationList: ['Yes, he does,']
speaker: Mr. Grimwig

quoteText: No, he does not,
subQuotationList: ['No, he does not,']
speaker: Mr. Brownlow

quoteText: He'll eat his head, if he doesn't,
subQuotationList: ["He'll eat his head, if he doesn't,"]
speaker: Mr. Grimwig

quoteText: He would deserve to have it knocked off, if he does,
subQuotationList: ['He would deserve to have it knocked off, if he does,']
speaker: Mr. Brownlow

quoteText: And he'd uncommonly like to see any man offer to do it,
subQuotationList: ["And he'd uncommonly like to see any man offer to do it,"]
speaker: Mr. Grimwig

quoteText:
Now, Miss Maylie, to return to the subject in
which your humanity is so much interested. Will you let me know what
intelligence you have of this poor child: allowing me to promise that I
exhausted every means in my power of discovering him, and that since I
have been absent from this country, my first impression that he had
imposed upon me, and had been persuaded by his former associates to rob
me, has been considerably shaken.
subQuotationList:
['Now, Miss Maylie,', 'to return to the subject in
which your humanity is so much interested. Will you let me know what
intelligence you have of this poor child: allowing me to promise that I
exhausted every means in my power of discovering him, and that since I
have been absent from this country, my first impression that he had
imposed upon me, and had been persuaded by his former associates to rob
me, has been considerably shaken.']
speaker: Mr. Brownlow
mentionEntitiesList: [[['Rose Maylie']], [['Rose Maylie'], ['Rose Maylie'], ['Rose Maylie'], ['Oliver Twist'], ['Oliver Twist'], ['Oliver Twist'], ['Oliver Twist']]]

quoteText:
Thank God! This is great happiness to me,
great happiness. But you have not told me where he is now, Miss Maylie.
You must pardon my finding fault with you, but why not have brought
him?
subQuotationList:
['Thank God!', 'This is great happiness to me,
great happiness. But you have not told me where he is now, Miss Maylie.
You must pardon my finding fault with you, but why not have brought
him?']
speaker: Mr. Brownlow
mentionEntitiesList: [[], [['Rose Maylie'], ['Oliver Twist'], ['Rose Maylie'], ['Rose Maylie'], ['Rose Maylie'], ['Oliver Twist']]]

quoteText: He is waiting in a coach at the door,
subQuotationList: ['He is waiting in a coach at the door,']
speaker: Rose Maylie

quoteText: At this door!
subQuotationList: ['At this door!']
speaker: Mr. Brownlow

quoteText:
Hush! Don't be afraid. I'm old enough to be your grandfather.
You're a sweet girl. I like you. Here they are!
subQuotationList: ['Hush!', "Don't be afraid. I'm old enough to be your grandfather.\nYou're a sweet girl. I like you. Here they are!"]
speaker: Mr. Grimwig

quoteText: There is somebody else who should not be forgotten, by the bye, Send Mrs. Bedwin here, if you please.
subQuotationList: ['There is somebody else who should not be forgotten, by the bye,', 'Send Mrs. Bedwin here, if you please.']
speaker: Mr. Brownlow

quoteText: Why, you get blinder every day, Bedwin,
subQuotationList: ['Why, you get blinder every day, Bedwin,']
speaker: Mr. Brownlow

quoteText:
Well, that I do, sir, People's eyes, at my
time of life, don't improve with age, sir.
subQuotationList: ['Well, that I do, sir,', "People's eyes, at my\ntime of life, don't improve with age, sir."]
speaker: Mrs. Bedwin

quoteText:
I could have told you that, but put on your
glasses, and see if you can't find out what you were wanted for, will
you?
subQuotationList: ['I could have told you that,', "but put on your\nglasses, and see if you can't find out what you were wanted for, will\nyou?"]
speaker: Mr. Brownlow

quoteText:
God be good to me! it is my
innocent boy!
subQuotationList: ['God be good to me!', 'it is my\ninnocent boy!']
speaker: Mrs. Bedwin

quoteText: My dear old nurse!
subQuotationList: ['My dear old nurse!']
speaker: Oliver Twist

quoteText:
He would come back I knew he would, How well he looks, and how like a gentleman's son he is
dressed again! Where have you been, this long, long while? Ah! the same
sweet face, but not so pale; the same soft eye, but not so sad. I have
never forgotten them or his quiet smile, but have seen them every day,
side by side with those of my own dear children, dead and gone since I
was a lightsome young creature.
subQuotationList:
['He would come back I knew he would,', "How well he looks, and how like a gentleman's son he is
dressed again! Where have you been, this long, long while? Ah! the same
sweet face, but not so pale; the same soft eye, but not so sad. I have
never forgotten them or his quiet smile, but have seen them every day,
side by side with those of my own dear children, dead and gone since I
was a lightsome young creature."]
speaker: Mrs. Bedwin
mentionEntitiesList: [[['Oliver Twist'], ['Oliver Twist']], [['Oliver Twist'], ['Oliver Twist'], ['Oliver Twist'], ['Oliver Twist']]]

quoteText:
Then what the devil is to be done? Are we to pass a vote of thanks to
all these vagabonds, male and female, and beg them to accept a hundred
pounds, or so, apiece, as a trifling mark of our esteem, and some
slight acknowledgment of their kindness to Oliver?
subQuotationList:
['Then what the devil is to be done?', 'Are we to pass a vote of thanks to
all these vagabonds, male and female, and beg them to accept a hundred
pounds, or so, apiece, as a trifling mark of our esteem, and some
slight acknowledgment of their kindness to Oliver?']
speaker: Mr. Losberne
mentionEntitiesList: [[], [['Mr. Brownlow', 'Mr. Losberne', 'Rose Maylie', 'Mrs. Maylie'], ['Bill Sikes', 'Fagin', 'Charley Bates', 'Nance', 'The Artful Dodger'], ['The Artful Dodger', 'Nance', 'Fagin', 'Bill Sikes', 'Charley Bates'], ['The Artful Dodger', 'Nance', 'Fagin', 'Bill Sikes', 'Charley Bates'], ['Oliver Twist']]]

quoteText:
Not exactly that, but we must
proceed gently and with great care.
subQuotationList: ['Not exactly that,', 'but we must\nproceed gently and with great care.']
speaker: Mr. Brownlow

quoteText:
Gentleness and care, I'd send them one and all
to
subQuotationList: ['Gentleness and care,', "I'd send them one and all\nto"]
speaker: Mr. Losberne

quoteText:
Never mind where, But reflect whether
sending them anywhere is likely to attain the object we have in view.
subQuotationList: ['Never mind where,', 'But reflect whether\nsending them anywhere is likely to attain the object we have in view.']
speaker: Mr. Brownlow
mentionEntitiesList: [[], [['The Artful Dodger', 'Nance', 'Fagin', 'Bill Sikes', 'Charley Bates'], ['Mr. Brownlow', 'Mr. Losberne', 'Rose Maylie', 'Mrs. Maylie']]]

quoteText: What object?
subQuotationList: ['What object?']
speaker: Mr. Losberne

quoteText:
Simply, the discovery of Oliver's parentage, and regaining for him the
inheritance of which, if this story be true, he has been fraudulently
deprived.
subQuotationList: ["Simply, the discovery of Oliver's parentage, and regaining for him the\ninheritance of which, if this story be true, he has been fraudulently\ndeprived."]
speaker: Mr. Brownlow

quoteText: Ah! I almost forgot that.
subQuotationList: ['Ah!', 'I almost forgot that.']
speaker: Mr. Losberne

quoteText:
You see, placing this poor girl entirely out
of the question, and supposing it were possible to bring these
scoundrels to justice without compromising her safety, what good should
we bring about?
subQuotationList:

of the question, and supposing it were possible to bring these
scoundrels to justice without compromising her safety, what good should
we bring about?']
speaker: Mr. Brownlow

quoteText: Hanging a few of them at least, in all probability, and transporting the rest.
subQuotationList: ['Hanging a few of them at least, in all probability,', 'and transporting the rest.']
speaker: Mr. Losberne

quoteText:
Very good, but no doubt they will
bring that about for themselves in the fulness of time, and if we step
in to forestall them, it seems to me that we shall be performing a very
Quixotic act, in direct opposition to our own interest or at least to
Oliver's, which is the same thing.

quoteText: How?
speaker: Mr. Losberne

quoteText:
Thus. It is quite clear that we shall have extreme difficulty in
getting to the bottom of this mystery, unless we can bring this man,
Monks, upon his knees. That can only be done by stratagem, and by
catching him when he is not surrounded by these people. For, suppose he
were apprehended, we have no proof against him. He is not even (so far
as we know, or as the facts appear to us) concerned with the gang in
any of their robberies. If he were not discharged, it is very unlikely
that he could receive any further punishment than being committed to
prison as a rogue and vagabond; and of course ever afterwards his mouth
would be so obstinately closed that he might as well, for our purposes,
be deaf, dumb, blind, and an idiot.

quoteText:
Then, I put it to you again, whether
you think it reasonable that this promise to the girl should be
considered binding; a promise made with the best and kindest
intentions, but really
subQuotationList:
['Then,', 'I put it to you again, whether
you think it reasonable that this promise to the girl should be
considered binding; a promise made with the best and kindest
intentions, but really']
speaker: Mr. Losberne

quoteText:
Do not discuss the point, my dear young lady, pray, The promise
shall be kept. I don't think it will, in the slightest degree,
interfere with our proceedings. But, before we can resolve upon any
precise course of action, it will be necessary to see the girl; to
ascertain from her whether she will point out this Monks, on the
understanding that he is to be dealt with by us, and not by the law;
or, if she will not, or cannot do that, to procure from her such an
account of his haunts and description of his person, as will enable us
to identify him. She cannot be seen until next Sunday night; this is
Tuesday. I would suggest that in the meantime, we remain perfectly
quiet, and keep these matters secret even from Oliver himself.

quoteText:
I should like, to call in the aid of my friend Grimwig. He
is a strange creature, but a shrewd one, and might prove of material
assistance to us; I should say that he was bred a lawyer, and quitted
the Bar in disgust because he had only one brief and a motion of
course, in twenty years, though whether that is recommendation or not,
you must determine for yourselves.

I have no objection to your calling in your friend if I may call in

quoteText:
We stay in town, of course, while there remains
the slightest prospect of prosecuting this inquiry with a chance of
success. I will spare neither trouble nor expense in behalf of the
object in which we are all so deeply interested, and I am content to
remain here, if it be for twelve months, so long as you assure me that
any hope remains.

quoteText:
Good! And as I see on the faces about me, a
disposition to inquire how it happened that I was not in the way to
corroborate Oliver's tale, and had so suddenly left the kingdom, let me
stipulate that I shall be asked no questions until such time as I may
deem it expedient to forestall them by telling my own story. Believe
me, I make this request with good reason, for I might otherwise excite
hopes destined never to be realised, and only increase difficulties and
disappointments already quite numerous enough. Come! Supper has been
announced, and young Oliver, who is all alone in the next room, will
have begun to think, by this time, that we have wearied of his company,
and entered into some dark conspiracy to thrust him forth upon the
world.

Heavy! What are yer talking about? What are yer made for? Oh, there yer are, resting again! Well, if yer ain't
enough to tire anybody's patience out, I don't know what is!

When I tell yer that I don't mean to do a thing, that's enough,
without any why or because either,

quoteText: Well, you needn't be so cross,
subQuotationList: ["Well, you needn't be so cross,"]
speaker: Mrs. Bolter

quoteText:
A pretty thing it would be, wouldn't it to go and stop at the very
first public-house outside the town, so that Sowerberry, if he come up
after us, might poke in his old nose, and have us taken back in a cart
with handcuffs on, No! I shall
go and lose myself among the narrowest streets I can find, and not stop
till we come to the very out-of-the-wayest house I can set eyes on.
Cod, yer may thanks yer stars I've got a head; for if we hadn't gone,
at first, the wrong road a purpose, and come back across country, yer'd
have been locked up hard and fast a week ago, my lady. And serve yer
right for being a fool.

Show us the tap, and give us a bit of cold meat and a drop of beer

Ah! Ad rub uds too, Frob the cuttry, but subthig in

Aha! I like that fellow's

I shall look out to get into company with them as can, They'll be able to make us useful some way or another. Why, you
yourself are worth fifty women; I never see such a precious sly and

speaker: Fagin

quoteText: Is he in a good way of business; that's where it is!
subQuotationList: ["Is he in a good way of business; that's where it is!"]
speaker: Noah Claypole

quoteText:
The top of the tree; employs a power of hands; has the very best
society in the profession.
subQuotationList: ['The top of the tree; employs a power of hands; has the very best\nsociety in the profession.']
speaker: Fagin

quoteText: Regular town-maders?
subQuotationList: ['Regular town-maders?']
speaker: Noah Claypole

quoteText:
Not a countryman among 'em; and I don't think he'd take you, even on
my recommendation, if he didn't run rather short of assistants just
now,
subQuotationList: ["Not a countryman among 'em; and I don't think he'd take you, even on\nmy recommendation, if he didn't run rather short of assistants just\nnow,"]
speaker: Fagin

quoteText: Should I have to hand over?
subQuotationList: ['Should I have to hand over?']
speaker: Noah Claypole

quoteText: It couldn't possibly be done without,
subQuotationList: ["It couldn't possibly be done without,"]
speaker: Fagin

quoteText: Twenty pound, though it's a lot of money!
subQuotationList: ["Twenty pound, though it's a lot of money!"]
speaker: Noah Claypole

quoteText:
Not when it's in a note you can't get rid of, Number
and date taken, I suppose? Payment stopped at the Bank? Ah! It's not
worth much to him. It'll have to go abroad, and he couldn't sell it for
a great deal in the market.
subQuotationList:
["Not when it's in a note you can't get rid of,", "Number
and date taken, I suppose? Payment stopped at the Bank? Ah! It's not
worth much to him. It'll have to go abroad, and he couldn't sell it for
a great deal in the market."]
speaker: Fagin

quoteText: When could I see him?
subQuotationList: ['When could I see him?']
speaker: Noah Claypole

quoteText: To-morrow morning.
subQuotationList: ['To-morrow morning.']
speaker: Fagin

quoteText: Where?
subQuotationList: ['Where?']
speaker: Noah Claypole

quoteText: Here.
subQuotationList: ['Here.']
speaker: Fagin

quoteText: Um! What's the wages?
subQuotationList: ['Um!', "What's the wages?"]
speaker: Noah Claypole

quoteText:
Live like a gentleman board and lodging, pipes and spirits free half
of all you earn, and half of all the young woman earns,
subQuotationList: ['Live like a gentleman board and lodging, pipes and spirits free half\nof all you earn, and half of all the young woman earns,']
speaker: Fagin

quoteText:
But, yer see, as she will be able to do a good deal,
I should like to take something very light.
subQuotationList: ['But, yer see,', 'as she will be able to do a good deal,\nI should like to take something very light.']
speaker: Noah Claypole

quoteText: A little fancy work?
subQuotationList: ['A little fancy work?']
speaker: Fagin

quoteText:
Ah! something of that sort, What do you think would
suit me now? Something not too trying for the strength, and not very
dangerous, you know. That's the sort of thing!
subQuotationList: ['Ah! something of that sort,', "What do you think would\nsuit me now? Something not too trying for the strength, and not very\ndangerous, you know. That's the sort of thing!"]
speaker: Noah Claypole

quoteText:
I heard you talk of something in the spy way upon the others, my
dear, My friend wants somebody who would do that well,
very much.
subQuotationList: ['I heard you talk of something in the spy way upon the others, my\ndear,', 'My friend wants somebody who would do that well,\nvery much.']
speaker: Fagin

quoteText:
Why, I did mention that, and I shouldn't mind turning my hand to it
sometimes, but it wouldn't pay by
itself, you know.
subQuotationList: ["Why, I did mention that, and I shouldn't mind turning my hand to it\nsometimes,", "but it wouldn't pay by\nitself, you know."]
speaker: Noah Claypole

quoteText: That's true! No, it might not.
subQuotationList: ["That's true!", 'No, it might not.']
speaker: Fagin

quoteText:
What do you think, then? Something in the sneaking way, where it was pretty sure work, and not
much more risk than being at home.
subQuotationList: ['What do you think, then?', 'Something in the sneaking way, where it was pretty sure work, and not\nmuch more risk than being at home.']
speaker: Noah Claypole

quoteText:
What do you think of the old ladies? There's a good
deal of money made in snatching their bags and parcels, and running
round the corner.
subQuotationList: ['What do you think of the old ladies?', "There's a good\ndeal of money made in snatching their bags and parcels, and running\nround the corner."]
speaker: Fagin

quoteText:
Don't they holler out a good deal, and scratch sometimes? I don't think that would answer my purpose. Ain't
there any other line open?
subQuotationList: ["Don't they holler out a good deal, and scratch sometimes?", "I don't think that would answer my purpose. Ain't\nthere any other line open?"]
speaker: Noah Claypole

quoteText: Stop! The kinchin lay.
subQuotationList: ['Stop!', 'The kinchin lay.']
speaker: Fagin

quoteText: What's that?
subQuotationList: ["What's that?"]
speaker: Noah Claypole

quoteText:
The kinchins, my dear, is the young children that's sent
on errands by their mothers, with sixpences and shillings; and the lay
is just to take their money away they've always got it ready in their
hands, then knock 'em into the kennel, and walk off very slow, as if
there were nothing else the matter but a child fallen down and hurt
itself. Ha! ha! ha!
subQuotationList:
['The kinchins, my dear,', "is the young children that's sent
on errands by their mothers, with sixpences and shillings; and the lay
is just to take their money away they've always got it ready in their
hands, then knock 'em into the kennel, and walk off very slow, as if
there were nothing else the matter but a child fallen down and hurt
itself. Ha! ha! ha!"]
speaker: Fagin

quoteText: Ha! ha! Lord, that's the very thing!
subQuotationList: ['Ha! ha!', "Lord, that's the very thing!"]
speaker: Noah Claypole

quoteText:
To be sure it is, and you can have a few good beats
chalked out in Camden Town, and Battle Bridge, and neighborhoods like
that, where they're always going errands; and you can upset as many
kinchins as you want, any hour in the day. Ha! ha! ha!
subQuotationList:
['To be sure it is,', "and you can have a few good beats
chalked out in Camden Town, and Battle Bridge, and neighborhoods like
that, where they're always going errands; and you can upset as many

speaker: Fagin

quoteText: Well, that's all right! What time to-morrow shall we say?
subQuotationList: ["Well, that's all right!", 'What time to-morrow shall we say?']
speaker: Noah Claypole

quoteText: Will ten do? What name shall I tell my good friend.
subQuotationList: ['Will ten do?', 'What name shall I tell my good friend.']
speaker: Fagin

quoteText: Mr. Bolter, Mr. Morris Bolter. This is Mrs. Bolter.
subQuotationList: ['Mr. Bolter,', 'Mr. Morris Bolter. This is Mrs. Bolter.']
speaker: Noah Claypole

quoteText: Mrs. Bolter's humble servant, I hope I shall know her better very shortly.
subQuotationList: ["Mrs. Bolter's humble servant,", 'I hope I shall know her better very shortly.']
speaker: Fagin

quoteText: Do you hear the gentleman, Charlotte?
subQuotationList: ['Do you hear the gentleman, Charlotte?']
speaker: Noah Claypole

quoteText: Yes, Noah, dear!
subQuotationList: ['Yes, Noah, dear!']
speaker: Mrs. Bolter

quoteText: She calls me Noah, as a sort of fond way of talking, You understand?
subQuotationList: ['She calls me Noah, as a sort of fond way of talking,', 'You understand?']
speaker: Noah Claypole

quoteText: Oh yes, I understand perfectly, Good-night! Good-night!
subQuotationList: ['Oh yes, I understand perfectly,', 'Good-night! Good-night!']
speaker: Fagin

quoteText:
And so it was you that was your own friend, was it? Cod, I thought
as much last night!
subQuotationList: ['And so it was you that was your own friend, was it?', 'Cod, I thought\nas much last night!']
speaker: Noah Claypole

quoteText: Every man's his own friend, my dear, He hasn't as good a one as himself anywhere.
subQuotationList: ["Every man's his own friend, my dear,", "He hasn't as good a one as himself anywhere."]
speaker: Fagin

quoteText: Except sometimes, Some people are nobody's enemies but their own, yer know.
subQuotationList: ['Except sometimes,', "Some people are nobody's enemies but their own, yer know."]
speaker: Noah Claypole

quoteText:
Don't believe that, When a man's his own enemy, it's
only because he's too much his own friend; not because he's careful for
everybody but himself. Pooh! pooh! There ain't such a thing in nature.
subQuotationList: ["Don't believe that,", "When a man's his own enemy, it's\nonly because he's too much his own friend; not because he's careful for\neverybody but himself. Pooh! pooh! There ain't such a thing in nature."]
speaker: Fagin

quoteText: There oughn't to be, if there is,
subQuotationList: ["There oughn't to be, if there is,"]
speaker: Noah Claypole

quoteText:
That stands to reason. Some conjurers say that number three is the
magic number, and some say number seven. It's neither, my friend,
neither. It's number one.
subQuotationList: ["That stands to reason. Some conjurers say that number three is the\nmagic number, and some say number seven. It's neither, my friend,\nneither. It's number one."]
speaker: Fagin

quoteText: Ha! ha! Number one for ever.
subQuotationList: ['Ha! ha!', 'Number one for ever.']
speaker: Noah Claypole

quoteText:
In a little community like ours, my dear, we have a general number one,
without considering me too as the same, and all the other young
people.
subQuotationList: ['In a little community like ours, my dear,', 'we have a general number one,\nwithout considering me too as the same, and all the other young\npeople.']
speaker: Fagin
mentionEntitiesList: [[['Noah Claypole']], [['Fagin', 'Charley Bates', 'Bill Sikes', 'Nance', 'The Artful Dodger'], ['The Artful Dodger', 'Charley Bates']]]

quoteText: Oh, the devil!
subQuotationList: ['Oh, the devil!']
speaker: Noah Claypole

quoteText:
You see, we
are so mixed up together, and identified in our interests, that it must
be so. For instance, it's your object to take care of number
one meaning yourself.
subQuotationList:
['You see,', "we
are so mixed up together, and identified in our interests, that it must
be so. For instance, it's your object to take care of number
one meaning yourself."]
speaker: Fagin
mentionEntitiesList: [[['Noah Claypole']], [['Charley Bates', 'Bill Sikes', 'Fagin', 'Nance', 'The Artful Dodger'], ['Noah Claypole'], ['Noah Claypole']]]

quoteText: Certainly, Yer about right there.
subQuotationList: ['Certainly,', 'Yer about right there.']
speaker: Noah Claypole

quoteText:
Well! You can't take care of yourself, number one, without taking care
of me, number one.
subQuotationList: ["Well! You can't take care of yourself, number one, without taking care\nof me, number one."]
speaker: Fagin

quoteText: Number two, you mean,
subQuotationList: ['Number two, you mean,']
speaker: Noah Claypole

quoteText:
No, I don't! I'm of the same importance to you, as
you are to yourself.
subQuotationList: ["No, I don't!", "I'm of the same importance to you, as\nyou are to yourself."]
speaker: Fagin

quoteText:
I say, yer a very nice man, and I'm very
fond of yer; but we ain't quite so thick together, as all that comes
to.
subQuotationList: ['I say,', "yer a very nice man, and I'm very\nfond of yer; but we ain't quite so thick together, as all that comes\nto."]
speaker: Noah Claypole

quoteText:
Only think, only consider. You've done what's a very pretty thing, and
what I love you for doing; but what at the same time would put the
cravat round your throat, that's so very easily tied and so very
difficult to unloose in plain English, the halter!
subQuotationList:
['Only think,', "only consider. You've done what's a very pretty thing, and
what I love you for doing; but what at the same time would put the
cravat round your throat, that's so very easily tied and so very
difficult to unloose in plain English, the halter!"]
speaker: Fagin

quoteText:
The gallows, the gallows, my dear, is an ugly
finger-post, which points out a very short and sharp turning that has
stopped many a bold fellow's career on the broad highway. To keep in
the easy road, and keep it at a distance, is object number one with
you.
subQuotationList:
['The gallows,', "the gallows, my dear, is an ugly
finger-post, which points out a very short and sharp turning that has
stopped many a bold fellow's career on the broad highway. To keep in
the easy road, and keep it at a distance, is object number one with
