quoteText:
Of course it is, What do yer talk about such
things for?
subQuotationList: ['Of course it is,', 'What do yer talk about such\nthings for?']
speaker: Noah Claypole

quoteText:
Only to show you my meaning clearly, To be able to do that, you depend upon me. To keep my little
business all snug, I depend upon you. The first is your number one, the
second my number one. The more you value your number one, the more
careful you must be of mine; so we come at last to what I told you at
first that a regard for number one holds us all together, and must do
so, unless we would all go to pieces in company.
subQuotationList:
['Only to show you my meaning clearly,', 'To be able to do that, you depend upon me. To keep my little
business all snug, I depend upon you. The first is your number one, the
second my number one. The more you value your number one, the more
careful you must be of mine; so we come at last to what I told you at
first that a regard for number one holds us all together, and must do
so, unless we would all go to pieces in company.']

quoteText:
That's true, Oh! yer a cunning
old codger!
subQuotationList: ["That's true,", 'Oh! yer a cunning\nold codger!']
speaker: Noah Claypole

quoteText:
It's this mutual trust we have in each other that consoles me under
heavy losses, My best hand was taken from me, yesterday
morning.
subQuotationList: ["It's this mutual trust we have in each other that consoles me under\nheavy losses,", 'My best hand was taken from me, yesterday\nmorning.']
speaker: Fagin

quoteText: You don't mean to say he died?
subQuotationList: ["You don't mean to say he died?"]
speaker: Noah Claypole

quoteText: No, no, not so bad as that. Not quite so bad.
subQuotationList: ['No, no,', 'not so bad as that. Not quite so bad.']
speaker: Fagin

quoteText: What, I suppose he was
subQuotationList: ['What, I suppose he was']
speaker: Noah Claypole

quoteText: Wanted, Yes, he was wanted.
subQuotationList: ['Wanted,', 'Yes, he was wanted.']
speaker: Fagin

quoteText: Very particular?
subQuotationList: ['Very particular?']
speaker: Noah Claypole

quoteText:
No, not very. He was charged with attempting to pick
a pocket, and they found a silver snuff-box on him, his own, my dear,
his own, for he took snuff himself, and was very fond of it. They
remanded him till to-day, for they thought they knew the owner. Ah! he
was worth fifty boxes, and I'd give the price of as many to have him
back. You should have known the Dodger, my dear; you should have known
the Dodger.
subQuotationList:
['No,', "not very. He was charged with attempting to pick
a pocket, and they found a silver snuff-box on him, his own, my dear,
his own, for he took snuff himself, and was very fond of it. They
remanded him till to-day, for they thought they knew the owner. Ah! he
was worth fifty boxes, and I'd give the price of as many to have him
back. You should have known the Dodger, my dear; you should have known
the Dodger."]

subQuotationList: ["Well, but I shall know him, I hope; don't yer think so?"]
speaker: Noah Claypole

quoteText:
I'm doubtful about it, If they don't get
any fresh evidence, it'll only be a summary conviction, and we shall
have him back again after six weeks or so; but, if they do, it's a case
of lagging. They know what a clever lad he is; he'll be a lifer.
They'll make the Artful nothing less than a lifer.
subQuotationList:
["I'm doubtful about it,", "If they don't get
any fresh evidence, it'll only be a summary conviction, and we shall
have him back again after six weeks or so; but, if they do, it's a case
of lagging. They know what a clever lad he is; he'll be a lifer.
They'll make the Artful nothing less than a lifer."]

What do you mean by lagging and a lifer? What's
the good of talking in that way to me; why don't yer speak so as I can
understand yer?
subQuotationList: ['What do you mean by lagging and a lifer?', "What's\nthe good of talking in that way to me; why don't yer speak so as I can\nunderstand yer?"]
speaker: Noah Claypole

quoteText: It's all up, Fagin,
subQuotationList: ["It's all up, Fagin,"]
speaker: Charley Bates

quoteText: What do you mean?
subQuotationList: ['What do you mean?']
speaker: Fagin

quoteText:
They've found the gentleman as owns the box; two or three more's a
coming to 'dentify him; and the Artful's booked for a passage out, I must have a full suit of mourning, Fagin, and
a hatband, to wisit him in, afore he sets out upon his travels. To
think of Jack Dawkins lummy Jack the Dodger the Artful Dodger going
abroad for a common twopenny-halfpenny sneeze-box! I never thought he'd
a done it under a gold watch, chain, and seals, at the lowest. Oh, why
didn't he rob some rich old gentleman of all his walables, and go out
as a gentleman, and not like a common prig, without no honour nor
glory!
subQuotationList:
["They've found the gentleman as owns the box; two or three more's a
coming to 'dentify him; and the Artful's booked for a passage out,", "I must have a full suit of mourning, Fagin, and
a hatband, to wisit him in, afore he sets out upon his travels. To
think of Jack Dawkins lummy Jack the Dodger the Artful Dodger going

quoteText:
What do you talk about his having neither honour nor glory for! Wasn't he always
the top-sawyer among you all! Is there one of you that could touch him
or come near him on any scent! Eh?
subQuotationList: ['What do you talk about his having neither honour nor glory for!', "Wasn't he always\nthe top-sawyer among you all! Is there one of you that could touch him\nor come near him on any scent! Eh?"]
speaker: Fagin
mentionEntitiesList: [[['The Artful Dodger']], [['The Artful Dodger'], ['Charley Bates'], ['Charley Bates'], ['The Artful Dodger'], ['The Artful Dodger']]]

quoteText: Not one, not one.
subQuotationList: ['Not one,', 'not one.']
speaker: Charley Bates

quoteText:
Then what do you talk of? what are you
blubbering for?
subQuotationList: ['Then what do you talk of?', 'what are you\nblubbering for?']
speaker: Fagin

quoteText:
'Cause it isn't on the rec-ord, is it? 'cause it can't come out in the 'dictment; 'cause nobody will never
know half of what he was. How will he stand in the Newgate Calendar?
P'raps not be there at all. Oh, my eye, my eye, wot a blow it is!
subQuotationList: ["'Cause it isn't on the rec-ord, is it?", "'cause it can't come out in the 'dictment; 'cause nobody will never\nknow half of what he was. How will he stand in the Newgate Calendar?\nP'raps not be there at all. Oh, my eye, my eye, wot a blow it is!"]
speaker: Charley Bates

quoteText:
Ha! ha! see what a pride they take in their profession, my dear. Ain't
it beautiful?
subQuotationList: ['Ha! ha!', "see what a pride they take in their profession, my dear. Ain't\nit beautiful?"]
speaker: Fagin
mentionEntitiesList: [[], [['Toby Crackit', 'Mr. Chitling', 'Charley Bates'], ['Toby Crackit', 'Mr. Chitling', 'Charley Bates']]]

quoteText:
Never mind, Charley, it'll come out, it'll be
sure to come out. They'll all know what a clever fellow he was; he'll
show it himself, and not disgrace his old pals and teachers. Think how
young he is too! What a distinction, Charley, to be lagged at his time
of life!
subQuotationList:

subQuotationList: ['Well, it is a honour that is!']
speaker: Charley Bates

quoteText:
He shall have all he wants, He shall be kept in
the Stone Jug, Charley, like a gentleman. Like a gentleman! With his
beer every day, and money in his pocket to pitch and toss with, if he
can't spend it.

quoteText:
Ha! ha! what a lark that would be, wouldn't
it, Fagin? I say, how the Artful would bother 'em wouldn't he?
subQuotationList: ['Ha! ha!', "what a lark that would be, wouldn't\nit, Fagin? I say, how the Artful would bother 'em wouldn't he?"]

quoteText:

was another man with such a face as yours, unless it was your father,
and I suppose _he_ is singeing his grizzled red beard by this time,
unless you came straight from the old 'un without any father at all
betwixt you; which I shouldn't wonder at, a bit.
subQuotationList:

such a grip on your throat as'll tear some of that screaming voice out.

Let me go, Bill, let me go; you
don't know what you are doing. You don't, indeed. For only one

subQuotationList: ['Wot did she take it into her head to go out to-night for, do you\nthink?', 'Come; you should know her better than me. Wot\ndoes it mean?']

subQuotationList: ["Obstinacy; woman's obstinacy, I suppose, my dear."]

Well, I suppose it is, I thought I had tamed her, but
she's as bad as ever.
subQuotationList: ['Well, I suppose it is,', "I thought I had tamed her, but\nshe's as bad as ever."]

Worse, I never knew her like this, for such
a little cause.
subQuotationList: ['Worse,', 'I never knew her like this, for such\na little cause.']

Nor I, I think she's got a touch of that fever in her
blood yet, and it won't come out eh?

quoteText: Like enough.
subQuotationList: ['Like enough.']

quoteText:
I'll let her a little blood, without troubling the doctor, if she's
took that way again, She was hanging about me all day, and night too, when I was stretched
on my back; and you, like a blackhearted wolf as you are, kept yourself
aloof, We was poor too, all the time, and I think, one
way or other, it's worried and fretted her; and that being shut up here
so long has made her restless eh?
subQuotationList:
["I'll let her a little blood, without troubling the doctor, if she's
took that way again,", 'She was hanging about me all day, and night too, when I was stretched
on my back; and you, like a blackhearted wolf as you are, kept yourself
aloof,', "We was poor too, all the time, and I think, one
way or other, it's worried and fretted her; and that being shut up here

subQuotationList: ["That's it, my dear,", 'Hush!']

subQuotationList: ["Why, now she's on the other tack!"]

referringExpression: he laid his finger on his lip and drawing close to the girl said

subQuotationList: ['What do you mean?']
speaker: Nance

quoteText:
The reason of all this, If _he_ is so hard with you (he's a brute,
Nance, a brute-beast), why don't you
subQuotationList: ['The reason of all this,', 'If _he_', "is so hard with you (he's a brute,\nNance, a brute-beast), why don't you"]
speaker: Fagin

quoteText: Well?
subQuotationList: ['Well?']
speaker: Nance

quoteText:
No matter just now. We'll talk of this again. You have a friend in me,
Nance; a staunch friend. I have the means at hand, quiet and close. If
you want revenge on those that treat you like a dog like a dog! worse
than his dog, for he humours him sometimes come to me. I say, come to
me. He is the mere hound of a day, but you know me of old, Nance.
subQuotationList:
["No matter just now. We'll talk of this again. You have a friend in me,

you want revenge on those that treat you like a dog like a dog! worse
than his dog, for he humours him sometimes come to me. I say, come to

subQuotationList: ['I know you well,', 'Good-night.']
speaker: Nance

quoteText:
With a little persuasion, what more likely than that
she would consent to poison him? Women have done such things, and
worse, to secure the same object before now. There would be the
dangerous villain: the man I hate: gone; another secured in his place;
and my influence over the girl, with a knowledge of this crime to back
it, unlimited. How, can I increase my influence with her? What new
power can I acquire?
subQuotationList:
['With a little persuasion,', 'what more likely than that
she would consent to poison him? Women have done such things, and
worse, to secure the same object before now. There would be the
dangerous villain: the man I hate: gone; another secured in his place;
and my influence over the girl, with a knowledge of this crime to back
it, unlimited.', 'How,', 'can I increase my influence with her? What new
power can I acquire?']

I can, She durst not refuse me then. Not
for her life, not for her life! I have it all. The means are ready, and
shall be set to work. I shall have you yet!
subQuotationList: ['I can,', 'She durst not refuse me then. Not\nfor her life, not for her life! I have it all. The means are ready, and\nshall be set to work. I shall have you yet!']

subQuotationList: ['Bolter,']

quoteText:
Well, here I am, What's the matter? Don't yer ask me
to do anything till I have done eating. That's a great fault in this
place. Yer never get time enough over yer meals.
subQuotationList: ['Well, here I am,', "What's the matter? Don't yer ask me\nto do anything till I have done eating. That's a great fault in this\nplace. Yer never get time enough over yer meals."]

Out, I sent her out this morning with the other young
woman, because I wanted us to be alone.
subQuotationList: ['Out,', 'I sent her out this morning with the other young\nwoman, because I wanted us to be alone.']
speaker: Fagin

Oh! I wish yer'd ordered her to make some buttered toast
first. Well. Talk away. Yer won't interrupt me.

You did well yesterday, my dear, Beautiful! Six
shillings and ninepence halfpenny on the very first day! The kinchin
lay will be a fortune to you.
subQuotationList: ['You did well yesterday, my dear,', 'Beautiful! Six\nshillings and ninepence halfpenny on the very first day! The kinchin\nlay will be a fortune to you.']

milk-can was a perfect masterpiece.
subQuotationList: ['No, no, my dear. The pint-pots were great strokes of genius: but the\nmilk-can was a perfect masterpiece.']
speaker: Fagin

quoteText:
Pretty well, I think, for a beginner, The pots I took off airy railings, and the milk-can was
standing by itself outside a public-house. I thought it might get rusty
with the rain, or catch cold, yer know. Eh? Ha! ha! ha!
subQuotationList: ['Pretty well, I think, for a beginner,', 'The pots I took off airy railings, and the milk-can was\nstanding by itself outside a public-house. I thought it might get rusty\nwith the rain, or catch cold, yer know. Eh? Ha! ha! ha!']

I want you, Bolter, to do a
piece of work for me, my dear, that needs great care and caution.
subQuotationList: ['I want you, Bolter,', 'to do a\npiece of work for me, my dear, that needs great care and caution.']
speaker: Fagin

quoteText:
I say, don't yer go shoving me into danger, or
sending me any more o' yer police-offices. That don't suit me, that
don't; and so I tell yer.
subQuotationList: ['I say,', "don't yer go shoving me into danger, or\nsending me any more o' yer police-offices. That don't suit me, that\ndon't; and so I tell yer."]
speaker: Noah Claypole

quoteText: That's not the smallest danger in it not the very smallest, it's only to dodge a woman.
subQuotationList: ["That's not the smallest danger in it not the very smallest,", "it's only to dodge a woman."]
speaker: Fagin

quoteText: An old woman?
subQuotationList: ['An old woman?']
speaker: Noah Claypole

quoteText: A young one,
subQuotationList: ['A young one,']
speaker: Fagin

quoteText:
I can do that pretty well, I know, I was a regular
cunning sneak when I was at school. What am I to dodge her for? Not
to
subQuotationList: ['I can do that pretty well, I know,', 'I was a regular\ncunning sneak when I was at school. What am I to dodge her for? Not\nto']
speaker: Noah Claypole

quoteText:
Not to do anything, but to tell me where she goes, who she sees, and,
if possible, what she says; to remember the street, if it is a street,
or the house, if it is a house; and to bring me back all the
information you can.
subQuotationList:
['Not to do anything, but to tell me where she goes, who she sees, and,
if possible, what she says; to remember the street, if it is a street,
or the house, if it is a house; and to bring me back all the
information you can.']
speaker: Fagin

quoteText: What'll yer give me?
subQuotationList: ["What'll yer give me?"]
speaker: Noah Claypole

quoteText:
If you do it well, a pound, my dear. One pound, And that's what I
never gave yet, for any job of work where there wasn't valuable
consideration to be gained.
subQuotationList: ['If you do it well, a pound, my dear. One pound,', "And that's what I\nnever gave yet, for any job of work where there wasn't valuable\nconsideration to be gained."]
speaker: Fagin

quoteText: Who is she?
subQuotationList: ['Who is she?']
speaker: Noah Claypole

quoteText: One of us.
subQuotationList: ['One of us.']
speaker: Fagin

quoteText:
Oh Lor! Yer doubtful of her, are
yer?
subQuotationList: ['Oh Lor!', 'Yer doubtful of her, are\nyer?']
speaker: Noah Claypole

quoteText:
She has found out some new friends, my dear, and I must know who they
are,
subQuotationList: ['She has found out some new friends, my dear, and I must know who they\nare,']
speaker: Fagin

quoteText:
I see, Just to have the pleasure of knowing them, if
they're respectable people, eh? Ha! ha! ha! I'm your man.
subQuotationList: ['I see,', "Just to have the pleasure of knowing them, if\nthey're respectable people, eh? Ha! ha! ha! I'm your man."]
speaker: Noah Claypole

quoteText: I knew you would be,
subQuotationList: ['I knew you would be,']
speaker: Fagin

quoteText:
Of course, of course, Where is she? Where am I to wait
for her? Where am I to go?
subQuotationList: ['Of course, of course,', 'Where is she? Where am I to wait\nfor her? Where am I to go?']
speaker: Noah Claypole

quoteText:
All that, my dear, you shall hear from me. I'll point her out at the
proper time, You keep ready, and leave the rest to me. She goes abroad to-night, and on the right errand, I'm
sure; for she has been alone all day, and the man she is afraid of will
not be back much before daybreak. Come with me. Quick!
subQuotationList:

sure; for she has been alone all day, and the man she is afraid of will

speaker: Fagin

quoteText: Is that the woman?
subQuotationList: ['Is that the woman?']
speaker: Noah Claypole

quoteText:
I can't see her face well, She is looking down, and
the candle is behind her.
subQuotationList: ["I can't see her face well,", 'She is looking down, and\nthe candle is behind her.']
speaker: Noah Claypole

quoteText: Stay there,
subQuotationList: ['Stay there,']
speaker: Fagin

quoteText: I see her now,
subQuotationList: ['I see her now,']
speaker: Noah Claypole

quoteText: Plainly?
subQuotationList: ['Plainly?']
speaker: Fagin

quoteText: I should know her among a thousand.
subQuotationList: ['I should know her among a thousand.']
speaker: Noah Claypole

quoteText: Hist! Dow.
subQuotationList: ['Hist!', 'Dow.']
speaker: Barney
referringExpression: cried the lad who held the door

quoteText:
To the left, take the left had, and keep od the
other side.
subQuotationList: ['To the left,', 'take the left had, and keep od the\nother side.']
speaker: Barney

quoteText:
Not here, I am afraid to speak to you here.
Come away out of the public road down the steps yonder!
subQuotationList: ['Not here,', 'I am afraid to speak to you here.\nCome away out of the public road down the steps yonder!']
speaker: Nance

quoteText:
This is far enough, I will not suffer the young lady to go any farther. Many
people would have distrusted you too much to have come even so far, but
you see I am willing to humour you.
subQuotationList: ['This is far enough,', 'I will not suffer the young lady to go any farther. Many\npeople would have distrusted you too much to have come even so far, but\nyou see I am willing to humour you.']
speaker: Mr. Brownlow
referringExpression: said a voice which was evidently that of the gentleman

quoteText:
To humour me! You're considerate, indeed, sir. To humour me! Well, well, it's no
matter.
subQuotationList: ['To humour me!', "You're considerate, indeed, sir. To humour me! Well, well, it's no\nmatter."]
speaker: Nance
referringExpression: cried the voice of the girl whom he had followed

quoteText:
Why, for what, for what purpose
can you have brought us to this strange place? Why not have let me
speak to you, above there, where it is light, and there is something
stirring, instead of bringing us to this dark and dismal hole?
subQuotationList:
['Why, for what,', 'for what purpose
can you have brought us to this strange place? Why not have let me
speak to you, above there, where it is light, and there is something
stirring, instead of bringing us to this dark and dismal hole?']
speaker: Mr. Brownlow

quoteText:
I told you before, that I was afraid to speak to you
there. I don't know why it is, but I have
such a fear and dread upon me to-night that I can hardly stand.
subQuotationList: ['I told you before,', "that I was afraid to speak to you\nthere. I don't know why it is,", 'but I have\nsuch a fear and dread upon me to-night that I can hardly stand.']
speaker: Nance

quoteText: A fear of what?
subQuotationList: ['A fear of what?']
speaker: Mr. Brownlow

quoteText:
I scarcely know of what, I wish I did. Horrible
thoughts of death, and shrouds with blood upon them, and a fear that
has made me burn as if I was on fire, have been upon me all day. I was
reading a book to-night, to wile the time away, and the same things
came into the print.
subQuotationList:
['I scarcely know of what,', 'I wish I did. Horrible
thoughts of death, and shrouds with blood upon them, and a fear that
has made me burn as if I was on fire, have been upon me all day. I was
reading a book to-night, to wile the time away, and the same things
came into the print.']
speaker: Nance

quoteText: Imagination,
subQuotationList: ['Imagination,']
speaker: Mr. Brownlow

quoteText:
No imagination, I'll swear I saw
 coffin' written in every page of the book in large black letters, aye,
and they carried one close to me, in the streets to-night.
subQuotationList: ['No imagination,', "I'll swear I saw\n coffin' written in every page of the book in large black letters, aye,\nand they carried one close to me, in the streets to-night."]
speaker: Nance

quoteText:
There is nothing unusual in that, They have
passed me often.
subQuotationList: ['There is nothing unusual in that,', 'They have\npassed me often.']
speaker: Mr. Brownlow

quoteText: _Real ones_, This was not.
subQuotationList: ['_Real ones_,', 'This was not.']
speaker: Nance

quoteText:
Speak to her kindly, Poor
creature! She seems to need it.
subQuotationList: ['Speak to her kindly,', 'Poor\ncreature! She seems to need it.']
speaker: Rose Maylie
referringExpression: said the young lady to her companion

quoteText:
Your haughty religious people would have held their heads up to see me
as I am to-night, and preached of flames and vengeance, Oh, dear lady, why ar'n't those who claim to be God's own folks
as gentle and as kind to us poor wretches as you, who, having youth,
and beauty, and all that they have lost, might be a little proud
instead of so much humbler?
subQuotationList:
['Your haughty religious people would have held their heads up to see me
as I am to-night, and preached of flames and vengeance,', "Oh, dear lady, why ar'n't those who claim to be God's own folks
as gentle and as kind to us poor wretches as you, who, having youth,
and beauty, and all that they have lost, might be a little proud
instead of so much humbler?"]
speaker: Nance

quoteText:
Ah! A Turk turns his face, after washing it
well, to the East, when he says his prayers; these good people, after
giving their faces such a rub against the World as to take the smiles
off, turn with no less regularity, to the darkest side of Heaven.
Between the Mussulman and the Pharisee, commend me to the first!
subQuotationList:
['Ah!', 'A Turk turns his face, after washing it
well, to the East, when he says his prayers; these good people, after
giving their faces such a rub against the World as to take the smiles
off, turn with no less regularity, to the darkest side of Heaven.
Between the Mussulman and the Pharisee, commend me to the first!']
speaker: Mr. Brownlow

quoteText: You were not here last Sunday night,
subQuotationList: ['You were not here last Sunday night,']
speaker: Mr. Brownlow

quoteText: I couldn't come, I was kept by force.
subQuotationList: ["I couldn't come,", 'I was kept by force.']
speaker: Nance

quoteText: By whom?
subQuotationList: ['By whom?']
speaker: Mr. Brownlow

quoteText: Him that I told the young lady of before.
subQuotationList: ['Him that I told the young lady of before.']
speaker: Nance

quoteText:
You were not suspected of holding any communication with anybody on
the subject which has brought us here to-night, I hope?
subQuotationList: ['You were not suspected of holding any communication with anybody on\nthe subject which has brought us here to-night, I hope?']
speaker: Mr. Brownlow

quoteText:
No, It's not very easy for me to
leave him unless he knows why; I couldn't give him a drink of laudanum
before I came away.
subQuotationList: ['No,', "It's not very easy for me to\nleave him unless he knows why; I couldn't give him a drink of laudanum\nbefore I came away."]
speaker: Nance

quoteText: Did he awake before you returned?
subQuotationList: ['Did he awake before you returned?']
speaker: Mr. Brownlow

quoteText: No; and neither he nor any of them suspect me.
subQuotationList: ['No; and neither he nor any of them suspect me.']
speaker: Nance

quoteText: Good, Now listen to me.
subQuotationList: ['Good,', 'Now listen to me.']
speaker: Mr. Brownlow

quoteText: I am ready,
subQuotationList: ['I am ready,']
speaker: Nance

quoteText:
This young lady, has communicated to me, and to
some other friends who can be safely trusted, what you told her nearly
a fortnight since. I confess to you that I had doubts, at first,
whether you were to be implicitly relied upon, but now I firmly believe
you are.
subQuotationList:
['This young lady,', 'has communicated to me, and to
some other friends who can be safely trusted, what you told her nearly
a fortnight since. I confess to you that I had doubts, at first,
whether you were to be implicitly relied upon, but now I firmly believe
you are.']
speaker: Mr. Brownlow
mentionTextsList: [['This young lady'], ['some other friends who can be safely trusted', 'you', 'her', 'you', 'you', 'you']]

quoteText: I am,
speaker: Nance

quoteText:
I repeat that I firmly believe it. To prove to you that I am disposed
to trust you, I tell you without reserve, that we propose to extort the
secret, whatever it may be, from the fear of this man Monks. But
if if he cannot be secured, or, if secured,
cannot be acted upon as we wish, you must deliver up the Jew.
subQuotationList:
['I repeat that I firmly believe it. To prove to you that I am disposed
to trust you, I tell you without reserve, that we propose to extort the
secret, whatever it may be, from the fear of this man Monks. But
if if', 'he cannot be secured, or, if secured,
cannot be acted upon as we wish, you must deliver up the Jew.']

quoteText: Fagin,
subQuotationList: ['Fagin,']
speaker: Nance

quoteText: That man must be delivered up by you,
subQuotationList: ['That man must be delivered up by you,']
speaker: Mr. Brownlow

quoteText:
I will not do it! I will never do it! Devil that
he is, and worse than devil as he has been to me, I will never do
that.
subQuotationList: ['I will not do it! I will never do it!', 'Devil that\nhe is, and worse than devil as he has been to me, I will never do\nthat.']
speaker: Nance

quoteText: You will not?
subQuotationList: ['You will not?']
speaker: Mr. Brownlow

quoteText: Never!
subQuotationList: ['Never!']
speaker: Nance

quoteText: Tell me why?
subQuotationList: ['Tell me why?']
speaker: Mr. Brownlow

quoteText:
For one reason, for one reason, that the
lady knows and will stand by me in, I know she will, for I have her
promise: and for this other reason, besides, that, bad life as he has
led, I have led a bad life too; there are many of us who have kept the
same courses together, and I'll not turn upon them, who might any of
them have turned upon me, but didn't, bad as they are.
subQuotationList:
['For one reason,', "for one reason, that the
lady knows and will stand by me in, I know she will, for I have her
promise: and for this other reason, besides, that, bad life as he has
led, I have led a bad life too; there are many of us who have kept the

mentionEntitiesList: [[], [['Rose Maylie'], ['Rose Maylie'], ['Rose Maylie'], ['Fagin'], ['Bill Sikes', 'Charley Bates', 'Fagin', 'Monks', 'Nance', 'Noah Claypole'], ['Bill Sikes', 'Charley Bates', 'Noah Claypole'], ['Bill Sikes', 'Charley Bates', 'Noah Claypole'], ['Bill Sikes', 'Charley Bates', 'Noah Claypole']]]

quoteText:
Then, put Monks into my hands, and leave him to
me to deal with.
subQuotationList: ['Then,', 'put Monks into my hands, and leave him to\nme to deal with.']
speaker: Mr. Brownlow

quoteText: What if he turns against the others?
subQuotationList: ['What if he turns against the others?']
speaker: Nance

quoteText:
I promise you that in that case, if the truth is forced from him,
there the matter will rest; there must be circumstances in Oliver's
little history which it would be painful to drag before the public eye,
and if the truth is once elicited, they shall go scot free.
subQuotationList:
["I promise you that in that case, if the truth is forced from him,
there the matter will rest; there must be circumstances in Oliver's
little history which it would be painful to drag before the public eye,
and if the truth is once elicited, they shall go scot free."]
speaker: Mr. Brownlow

quoteText: And if it is not?
subQuotationList: ['And if it is not?']
speaker: Nance

quoteText:
Then, this Fagin shall not be brought to
justice without your consent. In such a case I could show you reasons,
I think, which would induce you to yield it.
subQuotationList: ['Then,', 'this Fagin shall not be brought to\njustice without your consent. In such a case I could show you reasons,\nI think, which would induce you to yield it.']
speaker: Mr. Brownlow

quoteText: Have I the lady's promise for that?
subQuotationList: ["Have I the lady's promise for that?"]
speaker: Nance

quoteText: You have, My true and faithful pledge.
subQuotationList: ['You have,', 'My true and faithful pledge.']
speaker: Rose Maylie

quoteText: Monks would never learn how you knew what you do?
subQuotationList: ['Monks would never learn how you knew what you do?']
speaker: Nance

quoteText:
Never, The intelligence should be brought to
bear upon him, that he could never even guess.
subQuotationList: ['Never,', 'The intelligence should be brought to\nbear upon him, that he could never even guess.']
speaker: Mr. Brownlow

quoteText:
I have been a liar, and among liars from a little child, but I will take your words. He is tall, and a strongly made man, but not stout;
he has a lurking walk; and as he walks, constantly looks over his
shoulder, first on one side, and then on the other. Don't forget that,
for his eyes are sunk in his head so much deeper than any other man's,
that you might almost tell him by that alone. His face is dark, like
his hair and eyes; and, although he can't be more than six or eight and
twenty, withered and haggard. His lips are often discoloured and
disfigured with the marks of teeth; for he has desperate fits, and
sometimes even bites his hands and covers them with wounds why did you
start? Part of this, I have drawn out from other people at
the house I tell you of, for I have only seen him twice, and both times
he was covered up in a large cloak. I think that's all I can give you
to know him by. Stay though, Upon his throat: so high that
you can see a part of it below his neckerchief when he turns his face:
there is

quoteText: A broad red mark, like a burn or scald?
subQuotationList: ['A broad red mark, like a burn or scald?']
speaker: Mr. Brownlow

quoteText: How's this? You know him!
subQuotationList: ["How's this?", 'You know him!']
speaker: Nance

quoteText:
I think I do, I should by your
description. We shall see. Many people are singularly like each other.
It may not be the same.
subQuotationList: ['I think I do,', 'I should by your\ndescription. We shall see. Many people are singularly like each other.\nIt may not be the same.']
speaker: Mr. Brownlow

quoteText: It must be he!
subQuotationList: ['It must be he!']
speaker: Mr. Brownlow

quoteText:
Now, you have given us most valuable assistance, young
woman, and I wish you to be the better for it. What can I do to serve
you?
subQuotationList: ['Now,', 'you have given us most valuable assistance, young\nwoman, and I wish you to be the better for it. What can I do to serve\nyou?']
speaker: Mr. Brownlow

quoteText: Nothing,
subQuotationList: ['Nothing,']
speaker: Nance

quoteText: You will not persist in saying that, Think now. Tell me.
subQuotationList: ['You will not persist in saying that,', 'Think now. Tell me.']
speaker: Mr. Brownlow

quoteText:
Nothing, sir, You can do nothing to help
me. I am past all hope, indeed.
subQuotationList: ['Nothing, sir,', 'You can do nothing to help\nme. I am past all hope, indeed.']
speaker: Nance

quoteText:
You put yourself beyond its pale, The past has
been a dreary waste with you, of youthful energies mis-spent, and such
priceless treasures lavished, as the Creator bestows but once and never
grants again, but, for the future, you may hope. I do not say that it
is in our power to offer you peace of heart and mind, for that must
come as you seek it; but a quiet asylum, either in England, or, if you
fear to remain here, in some foreign country, it is not only within the
compass of our ability but our most anxious wish to secure you. Before
the dawn of morning, before this river wakes to the first glimpse of
day-light, you shall be placed as entirely beyond the reach of your
former associates, and leave as utter an absence of all trace behind
you, as if you were to disappear from the earth this moment. Come! I
would not have you go back to exchange one word with any old companion,
or take one look at any old haunt, or breathe the very air which is
pestilence and death to you. Quit them all, while there is time and
opportunity!
subQuotationList:
['You put yourself beyond its pale,', 'The past has
been a dreary waste with you, of youthful energies mis-spent, and such
priceless treasures lavished, as the Creator bestows but once and never
grants again, but, for the future, you may hope. I do not say that it
is in our power to offer you peace of heart and mind, for that must
come as you seek it; but a quiet asylum, either in England, or, if you

or take one look at any old haunt, or breathe the very air which is
pestilence and death to you. Quit them all, while there is time and

speaker: Mr. Brownlow

quoteText:
She will be persuaded now, She hesitates, I am
sure.
subQuotationList: ['She will be persuaded now,', 'She hesitates, I am\nsure.']
speaker: Rose Maylie

quoteText: I fear not, my dear,
subQuotationList: ['I fear not, my dear,']
speaker: Mr. Brownlow

quoteText:
No sir, I do not, I am
chained to my old life. I loathe and hate it now, but I cannot leave
it. I must have gone too far to turn back, and yet I don't know, for if
you had spoken to me so, some time ago, I should have laughed it off.
But, this fear comes over me again.
I must go home.
subQuotationList:
['No sir, I do not,', "I am
chained to my old life. I loathe and hate it now, but I cannot leave
it. I must have gone too far to turn back, and yet I don't know, for if
you had spoken to me so, some time ago, I should have laughed it off.
But,", 'this fear comes over me again.
I must go home.']
speaker: Nance

quoteText: Home!
subQuotationList: ['Home!']
speaker: Rose Maylie

quoteText:
Home, lady, To such a home as I have raised for
myself with the work of my whole life. Let us part. I shall be watched
or seen. Go! Go! If I have done you any service all I ask is, that you
leave me, and let me go my way alone.
subQuotationList:
['Home, lady,', 'To such a home as I have raised for
myself with the work of my whole life. Let us part. I shall be watched
or seen. Go! Go! If I have done you any service all I ask is, that you
leave me, and let me go my way alone.']
speaker: Nance

quoteText:
It is useless, We compromise her
safety, perhaps, by staying here. We may have detained her longer than
she expected already.
subQuotationList: ['It is useless,', 'We compromise her\nsafety, perhaps, by staying here. We may have detained her longer than\nshe expected already.']
speaker: Mr. Brownlow

quoteText: Yes, yes, You have.
subQuotationList: ['Yes, yes,', 'You have.']
speaker: Nance

quoteText:
What, can be the end of this poor creature's
life!
subQuotationList: ['What,', "can be the end of this poor creature's\nlife!"]
speaker: Rose Maylie

quoteText:
What! Look before you, lady. Look at that dark
water. How many times do you read of such as I who spring into the
tide, and leave no living thing, to care for, or bewail them. It may be
years hence, or it may be only months, but I shall come to that at
last.
subQuotationList:
['What!', 'Look before you, lady. Look at that dark
water. How many times do you read of such as I who spring into the
tide, and leave no living thing, to care for, or bewail them. It may be
years hence, or it may be only months, but I shall come to that at
last.']
speaker: Nance

quoteText: Do not speak thus, pray,
subQuotationList: ['Do not speak thus, pray,']
speaker: Rose Maylie

quoteText:
It will never reach your ears, dear lady, and God forbid such horrors
should! Good-night, good-night!
subQuotationList: ['It will never reach your ears, dear lady, and God forbid such horrors\nshould!', 'Good-night, good-night!']
speaker: Nance

quoteText:
This purse, Take it for my sake, that you may
have some resource in an hour of need and trouble.
subQuotationList: ['This purse,', 'Take it for my sake, that you may\nhave some resource in an hour of need and trouble.']
speaker: Rose Maylie

quoteText:
No! I have not done this for money. Let me have
that to think of. And yet give me something that you have worn: I
should like to have something no, no, not a ring your gloves or
handkerchief anything that I can keep, as having belonged to you, sweet
lady. There. Bless you! God bless you. Good-night, good-night!
subQuotationList:
['No!', 'I have not done this for money. Let me have
that to think of. And yet give me something that you have worn: I
should like to have something no, no, not a ring your gloves or

quoteText:
Hark! Did she call! I thought I
heard her voice.
subQuotationList: ['Hark!', 'Did she call! I thought I\nheard her voice.']
speaker: Rose Maylie

quoteText:
No, my love, She has not
moved, and will not till we are gone.
subQuotationList: ['No, my love,', 'She has not\nmoved, and will not till we are gone.']
speaker: Mr. Brownlow

quoteText: At last, At last!
subQuotationList: ['At last,', 'At last!']
speaker: Fagin

quoteText:
There! Take care of that,
and do the most you can with it. It's been trouble enough to get; I
thought I should have been here, three hours ago.
subQuotationList: ['There!', "Take care of that,\nand do the most you can with it. It's been trouble enough to get; I\nthought I should have been here, three hours ago."]
speaker: Bill Sikes

quoteText: Wot now? Wot do you look at a man so for?
subQuotationList: ['Wot now?', 'Wot do you look at a man so for?']
speaker: Bill Sikes

quoteText:
Damme! He's
gone mad. I must look to myself here.
subQuotationList: ['Damme!', "He's\ngone mad. I must look to myself here."]
speaker: Bill Sikes

quoteText:
No, no, It's not you're not the
person, Bill. I've no no fault to find with you.
subQuotationList: ['No, no,', "It's not you're not the\nperson, Bill. I've no no fault to find with you."]
speaker: Fagin

quoteText:
Oh, you haven't, haven't you? That's
lucky for one of us. Which one that is, don't matter.
subQuotationList: ["Oh, you haven't, haven't you?", "That's\nlucky for one of us. Which one that is, don't matter."]
speaker: Bill Sikes

quoteText: I've got that to tell you, Bill, will make you worse than me.
subQuotationList: ["I've got that to tell you, Bill,", 'will make you worse than me.']
speaker: Fagin

quoteText:
Aye? Tell away! Look
sharp, or Nance will think I'm lost.
subQuotationList: ['Aye?', "Tell away! Look\nsharp, or Nance will think I'm lost."]
speaker: Bill Sikes

quoteText:
Lost! She has pretty well settled that, in her own
mind, already.
subQuotationList: ['Lost!', 'She has pretty well settled that, in her own\nmind, already.']
speaker: Fagin

quoteText:
Speak, will you! or if you don't, it shall be for want of
breath. Open your mouth and say wot you've got to say in plain words.
Out with it, you thundering old cur, out with it!
subQuotationList: ['Speak, will you!', "or if you don't, it shall be for want of\nbreath. Open your mouth and say wot you've got to say in plain words.\nOut with it, you thundering old cur, out with it!"]
speaker: Bill Sikes

quoteText: Suppose that lad that's laying there
subQuotationList: ["Suppose that lad that's laying there"]
speaker: Fagin

quoteText: Well!
subQuotationList: ['Well!']
speaker: Bill Sikes

quoteText:
Suppose that lad, was to peach to blow upon us
all first seeking out the right folks for the purpose, and then having
a meeting with 'em in the street to paint our likenesses, describe
every mark that they might know us by, and the crib where we might be
most easily taken. Suppose he was to do all this, and besides to blow
upon a plant we've all been in, more or less of his own fancy; not
grabbed, trapped, tried, earwigged by the parson and brought to it on
bread and water, but of his own fancy; to please his own taste;
stealing out at nights to find those most interested against us, and
peaching to them. Do you hear me?
subQuotationList:
['Suppose that lad,', "was to peach to blow upon us
all first seeking out the right folks for the purpose, and then having
a meeting with 'em in the street to paint our likenesses, describe
every mark that they might know us by, and the crib where we might be
most easily taken. Suppose he was to do all this, and besides to blow
upon a plant we've all been in, more or less of his own fancy; not

stealing out at nights to find those most interested against us, and
peaching to them. Do you hear me?"]
speaker: Fagin

quoteText: Suppose he did all this, what then?
subQuotationList: ['Suppose he did all this, what then?']
speaker: Fagin

quoteText:
What then! If he was left
alive till I came, I'd grind his skull under the iron heel of my boot
into as many grains as there are hairs upon his head.
subQuotationList: ['What then!', "If he was left\nalive till I came, I'd grind his skull under the iron heel of my boot\ninto as many grains as there are hairs upon his head."]
speaker: Bill Sikes

quoteText:
What if I did it! I, that knows so
much, and could hang so many besides myself!
subQuotationList: ['What if I did it!', 'I, that knows so\nmuch, and could hang so many besides myself!']
speaker: Fagin

quoteText:
I don't know, I'd do something in the jail that 'ud get me put
in irons; and if I was tried along with you, I'd fall upon you with
them in the open court, and beat your brains out afore the people. I
should have such strength, that I could smash your head as if a loaded waggon had gone over
it.
subQuotationList:
["I don't know,", "I'd do something in the jail that 'ud get me put
in irons; and if I was tried along with you, I'd fall upon you with

speaker: Bill Sikes

quoteText: You would?
subQuotationList: ['You would?']
speaker: Fagin

quoteText: Would I! Try me.
subQuotationList: ['Would I!', 'Try me.']
speaker: Bill Sikes

quoteText: If it was Charley, or the Dodger, or Bet, or
subQuotationList: ['If it was Charley, or the Dodger, or Bet, or']
speaker: Fagin

quoteText:
I don't care who, Whoever it was, I'd
serve them the same.
subQuotationList: ["I don't care who,", "Whoever it was, I'd\nserve them the same."]
speaker: Bill Sikes

quoteText:
Bolter, Bolter! Poor lad! He's tired tired with watching for her so long, watching for _her_,
Bill.
subQuotationList: ['Bolter, Bolter! Poor lad!', "He's tired tired with watching for her so long, watching for _her_,\nBill."]
speaker: Fagin

quoteText: Wot d'ye mean?
subQuotationList: ["Wot d'ye mean?"]
speaker: Bill Sikes

quoteText: Tell me that again once again, just for him to hear,
subQuotationList: ['Tell me that again once again, just for him to hear,']
speaker: Fagin

quoteText: Tell yer what?
subQuotationList: ['Tell yer what?']
speaker: Noah Claypole

quoteText:
That about  _Nancy_, You
followed her?
subQuotationList: ['That about  _Nancy_,', 'You\nfollowed her?']
speaker: Fagin

quoteText: Yes.
speaker: Noah Claypole

quoteText: To London Bridge?
subQuotationList: ['To London Bridge?']
speaker: Fagin

quoteText: Yes.
speaker: Noah Claypole

quoteText: Where she met two people.
subQuotationList: ['Where she met two people.']
speaker: Fagin

quoteText: So she did.
subQuotationList: ['So she did.']
speaker: Noah Claypole

quoteText:
A gentleman and a lady that she had gone to of her own accord before,
who asked her to give up all her pals, and Monks first, which she
did and to describe him, which she did and to tell her what house it
was that we meet at, and go to, which she did and where it could be
best watched from, which she did and what time the people went there,
which she did. She did all this. She told it all every word without a
threat, without a murmur she did did she not?
subQuotationList:
['A gentleman and a lady that she had gone to of her own accord before,

quoteText:
All right, That's just what it
was!
subQuotationList: ['All right,', "That's just what it\nwas!"]
speaker: Noah Claypole

quoteText: What did they say, about last Sunday?
subQuotationList: ['What did they say, about last Sunday?']
speaker: Fagin

quoteText:
About last Sunday! Why I told yer that
before.
subQuotationList: ['About last Sunday!', 'Why I told yer that\nbefore.']
speaker: Noah Claypole

quoteText: Again. Tell it again!
subQuotationList: ['Again. Tell it again!']
speaker: Fagin

quoteText:
They asked her, they asked her why she didn't
come, last Sunday, as she promised. She said she couldn't.
subQuotationList: ['They asked her,', "they asked her why she didn't\ncome, last Sunday, as she promised. She said she couldn't."]
speaker: Noah Claypole

quoteText: Why why? Tell him that.
subQuotationList: ['Why why? Tell him that.']
speaker: Fagin

quoteText:
Because she was forcibly kept at home by Bill, the man she had told
them of before,
subQuotationList: ['Because she was forcibly kept at home by Bill, the man she had told\nthem of before,']
speaker: Noah Claypole

quoteText:
What more of him? What more of the man she had told
them of before? Tell him that, tell him that.
subQuotationList: ['What more of him?', 'What more of the man she had told\nthem of before? Tell him that, tell him that.']
speaker: Fagin
mentionEntitiesList: [[['Bill Sikes']], [['Bill Sikes'], ['Nance'], ['Rose Maylie', 'Mr. Brownlow'], ['Bill Sikes'], ['Bill Sikes']]]

quoteText:
Why, that she couldn't very easily get out of doors unless he knew
where she was going to, and so the first time she went to
see the lady, she ha! ha! ha! it made me laugh when she said it, that
it did she gave him a drink of laudanum.
subQuotationList:
["Why, that she couldn't very easily get out of doors unless he knew
where she was going to,", 'and so the first time she went to
see the lady, she ha! ha! ha! it made me laugh when she said it, that
it did she gave him a drink of laudanum.']
speaker: Noah Claypole

quoteText:
Hell's fire! Let me
go!
subQuotationList: ["Hell's fire!", 'Let me\ngo!']
speaker: Bill Sikes

quoteText:
Bill, Bill! A word. Only a
word.
subQuotationList: ['Bill, Bill!', 'A word. Only a\nword.']
speaker: Fagin

quoteText:
Let me out, Don't speak to me; it's not safe. Let me
out, I say!
subQuotationList: ['Let me out,', "Don't speak to me; it's not safe. Let me\nout, I say!"]
speaker: Bill Sikes

quoteText: Hear me speak a word, You won't be
subQuotationList: ['Hear me speak a word,', "You won't be"]
speaker: Fagin

quoteText: Well,
subQuotationList: ['Well,']
speaker: Bill Sikes

quoteText: You won't be too violent, Bill?
subQuotationList: ["You won't be too violent, Bill?"]
speaker: Fagin

quoteText:
I mean, not too violent for safety. Be crafty, Bill, and not too
bold.
subQuotationList: ['I mean,', 'not too violent for safety. Be crafty, Bill, and not too\nbold.']
speaker: Fagin

quoteText: Get up!
subQuotationList: ['Get up!']
speaker: Bill Sikes

quoteText: It is you, Bill!
subQuotationList: ['It is you, Bill!']
speaker: Nance

quoteText: It is, Get up.
subQuotationList: ['It is,', 'Get up.']
speaker: Bill Sikes

quoteText:
Let it be, There's enough
light for wot I've got to do.
subQuotationList: ['Let it be,', "There's enough\nlight for wot I've got to do."]
speaker: Bill Sikes

quoteText:
Bill, why do you look like
that at me!
subQuotationList: ['Bill,', 'why do you look like\nthat at me!']
speaker: Nance

quoteText:
Bill, Bill! I I won't scream or cry not once hear me speak to me tell me
what I have done!
subQuotationList: ['Bill, Bill!', "I I won't scream or cry not once hear me speak to me tell me\nwhat I have done!"]
speaker: Nance

quoteText: You know, you she devil! You were watched to-night; every word you said was heard.
subQuotationList: ['You know, you she devil!', 'You were watched to-night; every word you said was heard.']
speaker: Bill Sikes

quoteText:
Then spare my life for the love of Heaven, as I spared yours, Bill, dear Bill, you cannot have
the heart to kill me. Oh! think of all I have given up, only this one
night, for you. You _shall_ have time to think, and save yourself this
crime; I will not loose my hold, you cannot throw me off. Bill, Bill,
for dear God's sake, for your own, for mine, stop before you spill my
blood! I have been true to you, upon my guilty soul I have!
subQuotationList:
['Then spare my life for the love of Heaven, as I spared yours,', "Bill, dear Bill, you cannot have
the heart to kill me. Oh! think of all I have given up, only this one
night, for you. You _shall_ have time to think, and save yourself this
crime; I will not loose my hold, you cannot throw me off. Bill, Bill,
for dear God's sake, for your own, for mine, stop before you spill my
blood! I have been true to you, upon my guilty soul I have!"]
speaker: Nance
mentionEntitiesList: [[], [['Bill Sikes'], ['Bill Sikes'], ['Bill Sikes'], ['Bill Sikes'], ['Bill Sikes'], ['Bill Sikes'], ['Bill Sikes'], ['Bill Sikes'], ['Bill Sikes'], ['Bill Sikes'], ['Bill Sikes'], ['Bill Sikes']]]

quoteText:
Bill, the
gentleman and that dear lady, told me to-night of a home in some
foreign country where I could end my days in solitude and peace. Let me
see them again, and beg them, on my knees, to show the same mercy and
goodness to you; and let us both leave this dreadful place, and far
apart lead better lives, and forget how we have lived, except in
prayers, and never see each other more. It is never too late to repent.
They told me so I feel it now but we must have time a little, little
time!
subQuotationList:
['Bill,', 'the
gentleman and that dear lady, told me to-night of a home in some
foreign country where I could end my days in solitude and peace. Let me
see them again, and beg them, on my knees, to show the same mercy and
goodness to you; and let us both leave this dreadful place, and far

They told me so I feel it now but we must have time a little, little

quoteText: And what be that stoof? Good to eat, Harry?
subQuotationList: ['And what be that stoof? Good to eat, Harry?']
speaker: The Grinning Countryman

quoteText:
This, this is the infallible and
invaluable composition for removing all sorts of stain, rust, dirt,
mildew, spick, speck, spot, or spatter, from silk, satin, linen,
cambric, cloth, crape, stuff, carpet, merino, muslin, bombazeen, or
woollen stuff. Wine-stains, fruit-stains, beer-stains, water-stains,
paint-stains, pitch-stains, any stains, all come out at one rub with
the infallible and invaluable composition. If a lady stains her honour,
she has only need to swallow one cake and she's cured at once for it's
poison. If a gentleman wants to prove this, he has only need to bolt
one little square, and he has put it beyond question for it's quite as
satisfactory as a pistol-bullet, and a great deal nastier in the
flavour, consequently the more credit in taking it. One penny a square.
With all these virtues, one penny a square!
subQuotationList:
['This,', "this is the infallible and
invaluable composition for removing all sorts of stain, rust, dirt,
mildew, spick, speck, spot, or spatter, from silk, satin, linen,
cambric, cloth, crape, stuff, carpet, merino, muslin, bombazeen, or
woollen stuff. Wine-stains, fruit-stains, beer-stains, water-stains,
paint-stains, pitch-stains, any stains, all come out at one rub with
the infallible and invaluable composition. If a lady stains her honour,
she has only need to swallow one cake and she's cured at once for it's
poison. If a gentleman wants to prove this, he has only need to bolt
one little square, and he has put it beyond question for it's quite as
satisfactory as a pistol-bullet, and a great deal nastier in the
flavour, consequently the more credit in taking it. One penny a square.
With all these virtues, one penny a square!"]
speaker: Harry The Peddler

quoteText:
It's all bought up as fast as it can be made, There
are fourteen water-mills, six steam-engines, and a galvanic battery,
always a-working upon it, and they can't make it fast enough, though
the men work so hard that they die off, and the widows is pensioned
directly, with twenty pound a-year for each of the children, and a
premium of fifty for twins. One penny a square! Two half-pence is all
the same, and four farthings is received with joy. One penny a square!
Wine-stains, fruit-stains, beer-stains, water-stains, paint-stains,
pitch-stains, mud-stains, blood-stains! Here is a stain upon the hat of
a gentleman in company, that I'll take clean out, before he can order
me a pint of ale.
subQuotationList:
["It's all bought up as fast as it can be made,", "There
are fourteen water-mills, six steam-engines, and a galvanic battery,
always a-working upon it, and they can't make it fast enough, though

the same, and four farthings is received with joy. One penny a square!
Wine-stains, fruit-stains, beer-stains, water-stains, paint-stains,

me a pint of ale."]
speaker: Harry The Peddler

quoteText: Hah! Give that back.
subQuotationList: ['Hah!', 'Give that back.']
speaker: Bill Sikes

quoteText:
I'll take it clean out, sir, before you can come across the room to get it. Gentlemen all, observe
the dark stain upon this gentleman's hat, no wider than a shilling, but
thicker than a half-crown. Whether it is a wine-stain, fruit-stain,
beer-stain, water-stain, paint-stain, pitch-stain, mud-stain, or
blood-stain
subQuotationList:
["I'll take it clean out, sir,", "before you can come across the room to get it. Gentlemen all, observe
the dark stain upon this gentleman's hat, no wider than a shilling, but

speaker: Harry The Peddler

quoteText:
That's for your people, Now, look alive in there,
will you. Damn that 'ere bag, it warn't ready night afore last; this
won't do, you know!
subQuotationList: ["That's for your people,", "Now, look alive in there,\nwill you. Damn that 'ere bag, it warn't ready night afore last; this\nwon't do, you know!"]
speaker: Ben

quoteText: Anything new up in town, Ben?
subQuotationList: ['Anything new up in town, Ben?']
speaker: The Game-keeper

quoteText:
No, nothing that I knows on, Corn's up a little. I heerd talk of a murder, too, down Spitalfields
way, but I don't reckon much upon it.
subQuotationList: ['No, nothing that I knows on,', "Corn's up a little. I heerd talk of a murder, too, down Spitalfields\nway, but I don't reckon much upon it."]
speaker: Ben

quoteText: Oh, that's quite true, And a dreadful murder it was.
subQuotationList: ["Oh, that's quite true,", 'And a dreadful murder it was.']
speaker: _unknowable

quoteText:
Was it, sir? Man or woman,
pray, sir?
subQuotationList: ['Was it, sir?', 'Man or woman,\npray, sir?']
speaker: Ben

quoteText: A woman, It is supposed
subQuotationList: ['A woman,', 'It is supposed']
speaker: _unknowable

quoteText: Now, Ben,
subQuotationList: ['Now, Ben,']
speaker: The Coachman

quoteText: Damn that 'ere bag, are you gone to sleep in there?
subQuotationList: ["Damn that 'ere bag,", 'are you gone to sleep in there?']
speaker: Ben

quoteText: Coming!
subQuotationList: ['Coming!']
speaker: The Office Keeper

quoteText:
Coming, Ah, and so's the young 'ooman of property
that's going to take a fancy to me, but I don't know when. Here, give
hold. All ri ight!
subQuotationList: ['Coming,', "Ah, and so's the young 'ooman of property\nthat's going to take a fancy to me, but I don't know when. Here, give\nhold. All ri ight!"]
speaker: Ben

quoteText:
He has gone to Birmingham, they say, but they'll
have him yet, for the scouts are out, and by to-morrow night there'll
be a cry all through the country.
subQuotationList: ['He has gone to Birmingham, they say,', "but they'll\nhave him yet, for the scouts are out, and by to-morrow night there'll\nbe a cry all through the country."]
speaker: The Fireman

quoteText:
There's somebody to speak to there, at all event, A good
hiding-place, too. They'll never expect to nab me there, after this
country scent. Why can't I lie by for a week or so, and, forcing blunt
from Fagin, get abroad to France? Damme, I'll risk it.
subQuotationList:
["There's somebody to speak to there, at all event,", "A good
hiding-place, too. They'll never expect to nab me there, after this
country scent. Why can't I lie by for a week or so, and, forcing blunt
from Fagin, get abroad to France? Damme, I'll risk it."]
speaker: Bill Sikes

quoteText: Do you hear me call? Come here!
subQuotationList: ['Do you hear me call? Come here!']
speaker: Bill Sikes

quoteText: Come back!
subQuotationList: ['Come back!']
speaker: Bill Sikes

quoteText:
He knows the alternative, If he hesitates or moves
a finger but as you bid him, drag him into the street, call for the aid
of the police, and impeach him as a felon in my name.
subQuotationList: ['He knows the alternative,', 'If he hesitates or moves\na finger but as you bid him, drag him into the street, call for the aid\nof the police, and impeach him as a felon in my name.']
speaker: Mr. Brownlow

quoteText: How dare you say this of me?
subQuotationList: ['How dare you say this of me?']
speaker: Monks

quoteText:
How dare you urge me to it, young man? Are you mad enough to leave this
house? Unhand him. There, sir. You are free to go, and we to follow.
But I warn you, by all I hold most solemn and most sacred, that instant
will have you apprehended on a charge of fraud and robbery. I am
resolute and immoveable. If you are determined to be the same, your
blood be upon your own head!
subQuotationList:
['How dare you urge me to it, young man?', 'Are you mad enough to leave this
house? Unhand him. There, sir. You are free to go, and we to follow.
But I warn you, by all I hold most solemn and most sacred, that instant
will have you apprehended on a charge of fraud and robbery. I am
resolute and immoveable. If you are determined to be the same, your
blood be upon your own head!']
speaker: Mr. Brownlow

quoteText:
By what authority am I kidnapped in the street, and brought here by
these dogs?
subQuotationList: ['By what authority am I kidnapped in the street, and brought here by\nthese dogs?']
speaker: Monks

quoteText:
By mine, Those persons are indemnified by me.
If you complain of being deprived of your liberty you had power and
opportunity to retrieve it as you came along, but you deemed it
advisable to remain quiet I say again, throw yourself for protection on
the law. I will appeal to the law too; but when you have gone too far
to recede, do not sue to me for leniency, when the power will have
passed into other hands; and do not say I plunged you down the gulf
into which you rushed, yourself.
subQuotationList:
['By mine,', 'Those persons are indemnified by me.
If you complain of being deprived of your liberty you had power and
opportunity to retrieve it as you came along, but you deemed it
advisable to remain quiet I say again, throw yourself for protection on
the law. I will appeal to the law too; but when you have gone too far
to recede, do not sue to me for leniency, when the power will have
passed into other hands; and do not say I plunged you down the gulf

quoteText:
You will decide quickly, If you wish me to prefer my charges publicly, and consign
you to a punishment the extent of which, although I can, with a
shudder, foresee, I cannot control, once more, I say, for you know the
way. If not, and you appeal to my forbearance, and the mercy of those
you have deeply injured, seat yourself, without a word, in that chair.
It has waited for you two whole days. You will be prompt, A word from me, and the
alternative has gone for ever. I have not the inclination to parley, and, as I
advocate the dearest interests of others, I have not the right.

quoteText: This is pretty treatment, sir, from my father's oldest friend.
subQuotationList: ['This is pretty treatment, sir,', "from my father's oldest friend."]
speaker: Monks

quoteText:
It is because I was your father's oldest friend, young man, it is because the hopes and wishes of young and happy
years were bound up with him, and that fair creature of his blood and
kindred who rejoined her God in youth, and left me here a solitary,
lonely man: it is because he knelt with me beside his only sisters's
death-bed when he was yet a boy, on the morning that would but Heaven
willed otherwise have made her my young wife; it is because my seared
heart clung to him, from that time forth, through all his trials and
errors, till he died; it is because old recollections and associations
filled my heart, and even the sight of you brings with it old thoughts
of him; it is because of all these things that I am moved to treat you
gently now yes, Edward Leeford, even now and blush for your
unworthiness who bear the name.

Nothing, nothing to you. But it was _hers_,
and even at this distance of time brings back to me, an old man, the

quoteText:
You have a brother, a brother,
the whisper of whose name in your ear when I came behind you in the
street, was, in itself, almost enough to make you accompany me hither,
in wonder and alarm.

quoteText:
Attend to what I do know, and you may not, I
shall interest you by and by. I know that of the wretched marriage,
into which family pride, and the most sordid and narrowest of all
ambition, forced your unhappy father when a mere boy, you were the sole
and most unnatural issue.
subQuotationList:

quoteText: I don't care for hard names, You know the fact, and that's enough for me.
subQuotationList: ["I don't care for hard names,", "You know the fact, and that's enough for me."]
speaker: Monks

quoteText:
But I also know, the misery, the slow
torture, the protracted anguish of that ill-assorted union. I know how
listlessly and wearily each of that wretched pair dragged on their
heavy chain through a world that was poisoned to them both. I know how
cold formalities were succeeded by open taunts; how indifference gave
place to dislike, dislike to hate, and hate to loathing, until at last
they wrenched the clanking bond asunder, and retiring a wide space
apart, carried each a galling fragment, of which nothing but death
could break the rivets, to hide it in new society beneath the gayest
looks they could assume. Your mother succeeded; she forgot it soon. But
it rusted and cankered at your father's heart for years.

quoteText:

utterly forgotten the young husband ten good years her junior, who,
with prospects blighted, lingered on at home, he fell among new
friends. This circumstance, at least, you know already.

quoteText:
Your manner, no less than your actions, assures me that you have never
forgotten it, or ceased to think of it with bitterness, I speak of fifteen years ago, when you were not more than
eleven years old, and your father but one-and-thirty for he was, I
repeat, a boy, when _his_ father ordered him to marry. Must I go back
to events which cast a shade upon the memory of your parent, or will
you spare it, and disclose to me the truth?

before, and left him with two children there had been more, but, of all

quoteText:
They resided, in a part of the country to which your father in his
wandering had repaired, and where he had taken up his abode.
Acquaintance, intimacy, friendship, fast followed on each other. Your
father was gifted as few men are. He had his sister's soul and person.
As the old officer knew him more and more, he grew to love him. I would
that it had ended there. His daughter did the same.

quoteText:
It is a true tale of grief and trial, and sorrow, young man, and such tales usually are; if it were one of unmixed
joy and happiness, it would be very brief. At length one of those rich
relations to strengthen whose interest and importance your father had
been sacrificed, as others are often it is no uncommon case died, and
to repair the misery he had been instrumental in occasioning, left him
his panacea for all griefs Money. It was necessary that he should
immediately repair to Rome, whither this man had sped for health, and
where he had died, leaving his affairs in great confusion. He went; was
seized with mortal illness there; was followed, the moment the
intelligence reached Paris, by your mother who carried you with her; he
died the day after her arrival, leaving no will _no will_ so that the
whole property fell to her and you.

subQuotationList: ['I never heard of that,']
speaker: Monks

quoteText:
He came to me, and left with me, among some other things, a picture a
portrait painted by himself a likeness of this poor girl which he did
not wish to leave behind, and could not carry forward on his hasty
journey. He was worn by anxiety and remorse almost to a shadow; talked
in a wild, distracted way, of ruin and dishonour worked by himself;
confided to me his intention to convert his whole property, at any
loss, into money, and, having settled on his wife and you a portion of
his recent acquisition, to fly the country I guessed too well he would
not fly alone and never see it more. Even from me, his old and early
friend, whose strong attachment had taken root in the earth that
covered one most dear to both even from me he withheld any more
particular confession, promising to write and tell me all, and after
that to see me once again, for the last time on earth. Alas! _That_ was
the last time. I had no letter, and I never saw him more.

in my way by a stronger hand than chance, and rescued by me from a life

misery, there was a lingering expression in his face that came upon me
like a glimpse of some old friend flashing on one in a vivid dream. I
need not tell you he was snared away before I knew his history

know more than that.

quoteText:
You you can't prove anything against me, I defy you
to do it!
subQuotationList: ["You you can't prove anything against me,", 'I defy you\nto do it!']
speaker: Monks

quoteText:
We shall see, I
lost the boy, and no efforts of mine could recover him. Your mother
being dead, I knew that you alone could solve the mystery if anybody
could, and as when I had last heard of you you were on your own estate
in the West Indies whither, as you well know, you retired upon your
mother's death to escape the consequences of vicious courses here I
made the voyage. You had left it, months before, and were supposed to
be in London, but no one could tell where. I returned. Your agents had
no clue to your residence. You came and went, they said, as strangely
as you had ever done: sometimes for days together and sometimes not for
months: keeping to all appearance the same low haunts and mingling with
the same infamous herd who had been your associates when a fierce
ungovernable boy. I wearied them with new applications. I paced the
streets by night and day, but until two hours ago, all my efforts were
fruitless, and I never saw you for an instant.

quoteText:
And now you do see me, what then? Fraud
and robbery are high-sounding words justified, you think, by a fancied
resemblance in some young imp to an idle daub of a dead man's Brother!
You don't even know that a child was born of this maudlin pair; you
don't even know that.
subQuotationList:
['And now you do see me,', "what then? Fraud
and robbery are high-sounding words justified, you think, by a fancied
resemblance in some young imp to an idle daub of a dead man's Brother!
You don't even know that a child was born of this maudlin pair; you
don't even know that."]
speaker: Monks

quoteText:
I _did not_, but within the last
fortnight I have learnt it all. You have a brother; you know it, and
him. There was a will, which your mother destroyed, leaving the secret
and the gain to you at her own death. It contained a reference to some
child likely to be the result of this sad connection, which child was
born, and accidentally encountered by you, when your suspicions were
first awakened by his resemblance to your father. You repaired to the
place of his birth. There existed proofs proofs long suppressed of his
birth and parentage. Those proofs were destroyed by you, and now, in
your own words to your accomplice the Jew,  _the only proofs of the
boy's identity lie at the bottom of the river, and the old hag that
received them from the mother is rotting in her coffin_.' Unworthy son,
coward, liar, you, who hold your councils with thieves and murderers in
dark rooms at night, you, whose plots and wiles have brought a violent
death upon the head of one worth millions such as you, you, who from
your cradle were gall and bitterness to your own father's heart, and in
whom all evil passions, vice, and profligacy, festered, till they found
a vent in a hideous disease which had made your face an index even to
your mind you, Edward Leeford, do you still brave me!

quoteText:
Every word! every word that has passed between
you and this detested villain, is known to me. Shadows on the wall have
caught your whispers, and brought them to my ear; the sight of the
persecuted child has turned vice itself, and given it the courage and
almost the attributes of virtue. Murder has been done, to which you
were morally if not really a party.

brother is concerned, and then go where you please. In this world you
need meet no more.

quoteText:
Yes, yes, His dog has been seen lurking about
some old haunt, and there seems little doubt that his master either is,
or will be, there, under cover of the darkness. Spies are hovering
about in every direction. I have spoken to the men who are charged with
his capture, and they tell me he cannot escape. A reward of a hundred
pounds is proclaimed by Government to-night.

quoteText:
I will give fifty more, and proclaim it with my
own lips upon the spot, if I can reach it. Where is Mr. Maylie?

quoteText:
Harry? As soon as he had seen your friend here, safe in a coach with
you, he hurried off to where he heard this, and
mounting his horse sallied forth to join the first party at some place
in the outskirts agreed upon between them.

this time. They're sure of him.

subQuotationList: ['Have you made up your mind?']
speaker: Mr. Brownlow
referringExpression: asked Mr Brownlow in a low voice of Monks

quoteText: Yes, You you will be secret with me?
subQuotationList: ['Yes,', 'You you will be secret with me?']
speaker: Monks

quoteText: I will. Remain here till I return. It is your only hope of safety.
subQuotationList: ['I will. Remain here till I return. It is your only hope of safety.']
speaker: Mr. Brownlow

quoteText: What have you done?
subQuotationList: ['What have you done?']
speaker: Mr. Losberne

quoteText:
All that I could hope to do, and even more. Coupling the poor girl's
intelligence with my previous knowledge, and the result of our good
friend's inquiries on the spot, I left him no loophole of escape, and
laid bare the whole villainy which by these lights became plain as day.
Write and appoint the evening after to-morrow, at seven, for the
meeting. We shall be down there, a few hours before, but shall require
rest: especially the young lady, who _may_ have greater need of
firmness than either you or I can quite foresee just now. But my blood
boils to avenge this poor murdered creature. Which way have they
taken?
subQuotationList:
["All that I could hope to do, and even more. Coupling the poor girl's
intelligence with my previous knowledge, and the result of our good
friend's inquiries on the spot, I left him no loophole of escape, and
laid bare the whole villainy which by these lights became plain as day.
Write and appoint the evening after to-morrow, at seven, for the
meeting. We shall be down there, a few hours before, but shall require
rest: especially the young lady, who _may_ have greater need of
firmness than either you or I can quite foresee just now. But my blood
boils to avenge this poor murdered creature. Which way have they
taken?"]
speaker: Mr. Brownlow

quoteText:
Why, look'e, young gentleman, when a man keeps himself so
very ex-clusive as I have done, and by that means has a snug house over
his head with nobody a prying and smelling about it, it's rather a
startling thing to have the honour of a wisit from a young gentleman
(however respectable and pleasant a person he may be to play cards with
at conweniency) circumstanced as you are.

Especially, when the exclusive young man has got a friend stopping
with him, that's arrived sooner than was expected from foreign parts,

speaker: Toby Crackit
referringExpression: Toby Crackit seeming to abandon as hopeless any further effort to maintain his usual devilmaycare swagger turned to Chitling and said

quoteText:
Just at dinner-time two o'clock this afternoon. Charley and I made our
lucky up the wash-us chimney, and Bolter got into the empty water-butt,
head downwards; but his legs were so precious long that they stuck out
at the top, and so they took him too.

quoteText:
Poor Bet! She went to see the Body, to speak to who it was, and went off mad,
screaming and raving, and beating her head against the boards; so they
put a strait-weskut on her and took her to the hospital and there she
is.

He hung about, not to come over here afore dark, but he'll be here
soon, There's nowhere else to go to now, for the
people at the Cripples are all in custody, and the bar of the ken I
went up there and see it with my own eyes is filled with traps.

This is a smash, There's more than
one will go with this.

quoteText:
The sessions are on, if they get the inquest over, and
Bolter turns King's evidence: as of course he will, from what he's said
already: they can prove Fagin an accessory before the fact, and get the
trial on on Friday, and he'll swing in six days from this, by G !
subQuotationList:
['The sessions are on,', "if they get the inquest over, and
Bolter turns King's evidence: as of course he will, from what he's said

quoteText:
You should have heard the people groan, the officers
fought like devils, or they'd have torn him away. He was down once, but
they made a ring round him, and fought their way along. You should have
seen how he looked about him, all muddy and bleeding, and clung to them
as if they were his dearest friends. I can see 'em now, not able to
stand upright with the pressing of the mob, and draggin him along
amongst 'em; I can see the people jumping up, one behind another, and
snarling with their teeth and making at him; I can see the blood upon
his hair and beard, and hear the cries with which the women worked
themselves into the centre of the crowd at the street corner, and swore
they'd tear his heart out!
subQuotationList:
['You should have heard the people groan,', "the officers
fought like devils, or they'd have torn him away. He was down once, but

If he had, the dog 'ud want to lead us away to where he

See there, there! that's the stile I came over;
there are the hedges I crept behind, for fear any one should overtake
me and force me back! Yonder is the path across the fields, leading to
the old house where I was a little child! Oh Dick, Dick, my dear old
friend, if I could only see you now!

You will see him soon, You shall tell him how happy you are, and how rich
you have grown, and that in all your happiness you have none so great
as the coming back to make him happy too.

quoteText:
Yes, yes, and we'll we'll take him away from here, and
have him clothed and taught, and send him to some quiet country place
where he may grow strong and well, shall we? You will be kind and good to him, for you are to every one, It will make you cry, I know, to hear what he can tell; but
never mind, never mind, it will be all over, and you will smile again I
know that too to think how changed he is; you did the same with me. He
said  God bless you' to me when I ran away, and I will say  God bless you' now, and show
him how I love him for it!

This is a painful task, but these declarations, which have
been signed in London before many gentlemen, must be in substance
repeated here. I would have spared you the degradation, but we must
hear them from your own lips before we part, and you know why.

speaker: Mr. Brownlow

quoteText:
Listen then! You! His father being taken ill at
Rome, was joined by his wife, my mother, from whom he had been long
separated, who went from Paris and took me with her to look after his
property, for what I know, for she had no great affection for him, nor
he for her. He knew nothing of us, for his senses were gone, and he
slumbered on till next day, when he died. Among the papers in his desk,
were two, dated on the night his illness first came on, directed to
yourself and enclosed in a few
short lines to you, with an intimation on the cover of the package that
it was not to be forwarded till after he was dead. One of these papers
was a letter to this girl Agnes; the other a will.
subQuotationList:

separated, who went from Paris and took me with her to look after his

were two, dated on the night his illness first came on, directed to
yourself', 'and enclosed in a few
short lines to you, with an intimation on the cover of the package that

quoteText: What of the letter?
subQuotationList: ['What of the letter?']
speaker: Mr. Brownlow

quoteText:
The letter? A sheet of paper crossed and crossed again, with a
penitent confession, and prayers to God to help her. He had palmed a
tale on the girl that some secret mystery to be explained one
day prevented his marrying her just then; and so she had gone on,
trusting patiently to him, until she trusted too far, and lost what
none could ever give her back. She was, at that time, within a few
months of her confinement. He told her all he had meant to do, to hide
her shame, if he had lived, and prayed her, if he died, not to curse
his memory, or think the consequences of their sin would be visited on
her or their young child; for all the guilt was his. He reminded her of
the day he had given her the little locket and the ring with her
christian name engraved upon it, and a blank left for that which he
hoped one day to have bestowed upon her prayed her yet to keep it, and
wear it next her heart, as she had done before and then ran on, wildly,
in the same words, over and over again, as if he had gone distracted. I
believe he had.
